{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778631437470,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed3d9ffetUHSBNjB6UZ0DO","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_u2WQFoJ365umbWuMHhYhq9C5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\n+title: \"Recode M ALU op class\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already separates the RV32I and RV32M ALU result cones, but\n+  the final result still depends on decoding a contiguous mixed numeric range of\n+  ALU op values to decide whether the M-extension mux should be selected. Prior\n+  broad ALU resource sharing and extra fast paths regressed, so the safest timing\n+  opportunity is a tiny encoding cleanup that preserves the existing datapaths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Reassign the internal ALU op localparams so every RV32M operation has op[4]=1\n+  and every RV32I operation keeps op[4]=0. Then simplify rtl/alu.sv so the final\n+  RV32I-versus-RV32M result select is just op[4] rather than an eight-arm case or\n+  synthesized range compare.\n+\n+  This should slightly reduce EX-stage control decode and output-mux fan-in around\n+  the already successful RV32I/RV32M split, improving median FPGA Fmax without any\n+  CoreMark cycle-count change. The decoder still recognizes the same RV32IM\n+  encodings, the ALTOPS formulas remain behaviorally identical, and the NRET=1\n+  RVFI contract is untouched.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Recode ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU to values with bit 4 set while keeping all RV32I ALU op values below 16.\"\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the M-op membership case with the encoded op[4] class bit and keep the existing RV32I, RV32M, and ALTOPS result logic unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n+    description: \"Continue emitting the same named ALU operation constants for each RV32IM instruction after the internal numeric recoding.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\n+title: \"Recode M ALU op class\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already separates the RV32I and RV32M ALU result cones, but\n+  the final result still depends on decoding a contiguous mixed numeric range of\n+  ALU op values to decide whether the M-extension mux should be selected. Prior\n+  broad ALU resource sharing and extra fast paths regressed, so the safest timing\n+  opportunity is a tiny encoding cleanup that preserves the existing datapaths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Reassign the internal ALU op localparams so every RV32M operation has op[4]=1\n+  and every RV32I operation keeps op[4]=0. Then simplify rtl/alu.sv so the final\n+  RV32I-versus-RV32M result select is just op[4] rather than an eight-arm case or\n+  synthesized range compare.\n+\n+  This should slightly reduce EX-stage control decode and output-mux fan-in around\n+  the already successful RV32I/RV32M split, improving median FPGA Fmax without any\n+  CoreMark cycle-count change. The decoder still recognizes the same RV32IM\n+  encodings, the ALTOPS formulas remain behaviorally identical, and the NRET=1\n+  RVFI contract is untouched.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n