{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778631442609,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed3d9ffetUHSBNjB6UZ0DO","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ijf54dFeem5S6cuYR8NJUif1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\n2: title: \"Recode M ALU op class\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current best core already separates the RV32I and RV32M ALU result cones, but\n6:   the final result still depends on decoding a contiguous mixed numeric range of\n7:   ALU op values to decide whether the M-extension mux should be selected. Prior\n8:   broad ALU resource sharing and extra fast paths regressed, so the safest timing\n9:   opportunity is a tiny encoding cleanup that preserves the existing datapaths.\n10: hypothesis: |\n11:   Reassign the internal ALU op localparams so every RV32M operation has op[4]=1\n12:   and every RV32I operation keeps op[4]=0. Then simplify rtl/alu.sv so the final\n13:   RV32I-versus-RV32M result select is just op[4] rather than an eight-arm case or\n14:   synthesized range compare.\n15: \n16:   This should slightly reduce EX-stage control decode and output-mux fan-in around\n17:   the already successful RV32I/RV32M split, improving median FPGA Fmax without any\n18:   CoreMark cycle-count change. The decoder still recognizes the same RV32IM\n19:   encodings, the ALTOPS formulas remain behaviorally identical, and the NRET=1\n20:   RVFI contract is untouched.\n21: expected_impact:\n22:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n23:   confidence: medium\n24: changes:\n25:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n26:     description: \"Recode ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU to values with bit 4 set while keeping all RV32I ALU op values below 16.\"\n27:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n28:     description: \"Replace the M-op membership case with the encoded op[4] class bit and keep the existing RV32I, RV32M, and ALTOPS result logic unchanged.\"\n29:   - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n30:     description: \"Continue emitting the same named ALU operation constants for each RV32IM instruction after the internal numeric recoding.\"\n\n(End of file - total 30 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\ntitle: \"Recode M ALU op class\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current best core already separates the RV32I and RV32M ALU result cones, but\n  the final result still depends on decoding a contiguous mixed numeric range of\n  ALU op values to decide whether the M-extension mux should be selected. Prior\n  broad ALU resource sharing and extra fast paths regressed, so the safest timing\n  opportunity is a tiny encoding cleanup that preserves the existing datapaths.\nhypothesis: |\n  Reassign the internal ALU op localparams so every RV32M operation has op[4]=1\n  and every RV32I operation keeps op[4]=0. Then simplify rtl/alu.sv so the final\n  RV32I-versus-RV32M result select is just op[4] rather than an eight-arm case or\n  synthesized range compare.\n\n  This should slightly reduce EX-stage control decode and output-mux fan-in around\n  the already successful RV32I/RV32M split, improving median FPGA Fmax without any\n  CoreMark cycle-count change. The decoder still recognizes the same RV32IM\n  encodings, the ALTOPS formulas remain behaviorally identical, and the NRET=1\n  RVFI contract is untouched.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r11s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778631442599,"end":1778631442608}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0ac351ee4bc4cfcd016a03c312314c81988875091ba74bd5c6"}},"id":"prt_e1eb1ff6f001sTRxNpFhURo6up","sessionID":"ses_1e14ed3d9ffetUHSBNjB6UZ0DO","messageID