{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778632408636,"sessionID":"ses_1e14017c9ffeZNY9joTXT7GJgw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_5v7VmUu9K5TBhwwm6HzPXMzG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Factor forwarding matches\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core already gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but that makes the forwarding selector part of a hot EX operand path. Recent attempts that added state, new stalls, or broad datapath gating regressed, so the next micro_opt should be a very small cleanup that preserves the proven pipeline behavior.\n+\n+  The existing forward_unit repeats the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB register-destination comparisons inside separate ALU-result, load-result, and writeback arms for each source operand. Even if synthesis can sometimes common-subexpression these terms, making the producer matches explicit should reduce comparator duplication, fanout, and select-control depth with no cycle-count or architectural risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/forward_unit.sv to compute per-source producer match terms once: ex_mem_match_rs1/rs2 and mem_wb_match_rs1/rs2. Then choose EX/MEM ALU forwarding, MEM load forwarding, MEM/WB forwarding, or no forwarding from those match terms plus the existing ex_mem_is_load and ex_mem_load_fwd_valid qualifiers.\n+\n+  This keeps the same priority order and preserves the ready-qualified MEM-load bypass semantics that made the earlier forwarding change successful. It does not alter RVFI source tracking, load-stall behavior, the ALU, branch prediction, memory masks, or the NRET=1 top-level interface. The expected win is a modest Fmax improvement from a smaller forwarding-control cone on every EX operand mux, with no CoreMark IPC loss.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Precompute EX/MEM and MEM/WB destination match terms once per source operand, then reuse them to drive the existing forwarding priority and load-forwarding qualifiers.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Factor forwarding matches\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core already gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but that makes the forwarding selector part of a hot EX operand path. Recent attempts that added state, new stalls, or broad datapath gating regressed, so the next micro_opt should be a very small cleanup that preserves the proven pipeline behavior.\n+\n+  The existing forward_unit repeats the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB register-destination comparisons inside separate ALU-result, load-result, and writeback arms for each source operand. Even if synthesis can sometimes common-subexpression these terms, making the producer matches explicit should reduce comparator duplication, fanout, and select-control depth with no cycle-count or architectural risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/forward_unit.sv to compute per-source producer match terms once: ex_mem_match_rs1/rs2 and mem_wb_match_rs1/rs2. Then choose EX/MEM ALU f