nless synthesis can perfectly prune them through hierarchy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the late pipeline metadata into compact stage-specific payloads. Keep the full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, then have EX/MEM carry only memory width/sign, memory enables, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal; have MEM/WB carry only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Remove EX/MEM branch_taken and branch_target fields because redirect and pc_next are already resolved in EX and no downstream stage consumes those fields.\\n\\nThis should slightly reduce FF count, LUT muxing, and inter-stage routing on the Ta...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Word-only MEM load bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but the\\nforwarded operand path now includes byte/halfword lane selection and\\nsign-extension before feeding the EX operand muxes. A recent attempt to\\nrewrite that lane logic regressed, which suggests the load-forwarding cone is\\ntiming-sensitive and should be shortened rather than expanded. CoreMark's hot\\npointer and array chains are expected to be dominated by aligned LW uses, while\\ndependent LB/LH/LBU/LHU pairs should be rarer.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but the\\nforwarded operand path now includes byte/halfword lane selection and\\nsign-extension before feeding the EX operand muxes. A recent attempt to\\nrewrite that lane logic regressed, which suggests the load-forwarding cone is\\ntiming-sensitive and should be shortened rather than expanded. CoreMark's hot\\npointer and array chains are expected to be dominated by aligned LW uses, while\\ndependent LB/LH/LBU/LHU pairs should be rarer.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the structural MEM-to-EX bypass for word loads only, where the forwarded\\nvalue is simply the ready dmem word, and reintroduce a targeted one-cycle\\ninterlock for consumers of subword loads. Byte and halfword loads still use the\\nexisting sign/zero-extension path for WB and RVFI, but they no longer drive the\\nhot same-cycle MEM-load-forward operand path into EX. This should recover Fmax\\nby removing lane extraction and sign-extension from the load-use bypass while\\npreserving the important zero-bubble LW load-use cases that made the original\\nforwarding change profitable.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a targeted subword-load-use interlock using the ID/EX load width so LB/LH/LBU/LHU consumers wait for MEM/WB fo...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Share static predictor target adder\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\\n\\nThe existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\\n\\nThe existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the direct-control predictor chooses a single signed target offset first, then uses one shared pc-plus-offset adder for both predicted JAL targets and predicted backward branch targets. Keep the default pc+4 path, the JAL-always-taken rule, the backward-branch-taken rule, and the carried pred_next_pc semantics unchanged.\\n\\nThis should preserve the proven CoreMark cycle-count win from static prediction while reducing LUT use and IF-stage timing pressure. Because it adds no predictor state, tags, return stack, loop counter, or new redirect source, it avoids the failure mode seen in the previous predicto...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Isolate M-extension ALU mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\\nand MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\\nMEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\\nthe EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\\nlarge result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\\nthe RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\\nchanging cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\\nand MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\\nMEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\\nthe EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\\nlarge result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\\nthe RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\\nchanging cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv into two local result cones: a compact RV32I result mux for\\nADD/SUB/logic/shift/SLT/LUI and a separate RV32M result mux that keeps the existing\\nexact multiply/divide/remainder expressions unchanged. The final output should be\\nselected by a simple is_m_op predicate, rather than muxing every RV32I and RV32M\\noperation in one flat case statement.\\n\\nThis is intentionally not another attempt to share or redesign RV32M arithmetic,\\nwhich previously hurt timing. The ALTOPS branch must keep the same substituted\\nformulas, a...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Predicted path fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\\nfront end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\\nan isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\\nimmediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\\npc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\\nloop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\\nJAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\\nto hold correct useful instructions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\\nfront end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\\nan isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\\nimmediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\\npc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\\nloop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\\nJAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\\nto hold correct useful instructions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure IF into a two-entry predicted-path skid buffer with separate fetch and decode sides.\\nThe fetch side advances its private fetch PC along the existing static predicted next PC whenever\\nio_imemReady is high and the queue has space, including cycles where dmem backpressure is holding\\nID/EX and EX/MEM. The decode side consumes the oldest queued pc/instruction/pred_next_pc only\\nwhen ID is allowed to advance; when ...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Encode static prediction as direction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the simple stateless rule: predict direct JAL\\ntaken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior predictor attempts that\\nadded BHTs, RAS/JALR state, loop counters, or extra IF target muxing all\\nregressed, so the next predictor hypothesis should preserve that proven policy\\nand reduce its implementation cost instead of adding new prediction behavior.\\n\\nToday IF carries a full 32-bit pred_next_pc through IF/ID and ID/EX only so EX\\ncan compare it with the resolved next PC. For this predictor, correctness only\\ndepends on whether fetch predicted the direct control transfer taken or\\nfall-through: EX can recompute the same direct JAL/branch target from pc and imm\\nwhen needed, and JALR is still predicted fall-through.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the simple stateless rule: predict direct JAL\\ntaken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior predictor attempts that\\nadded BHTs, RAS/JALR state, loop counters, or extra IF target muxing all\\nregressed, so the next predictor hypothesis should preserve that proven policy\\nand reduce its implementation cost instead of adding new prediction behavior.\\n\\nToday IF carries a full 32-bit pred_next_pc through IF/ID and ID/EX only so EX\\ncan compare it with the resolved next PC. For this predictor, correctness only\\ndepends on whether fetch predicted the direct control transfer taken or\\nfall-through: EX can recompute the same direct JAL/branch target from pc and imm\\nwhen needed, and JALR is still predicted fall-through.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the carried pred_next_pc metadata with a compact prediction-direction\\nbit for the existing static predictor. IF still computes the predicted next PC\\nlocally to update the fetch PC, but it exports only whether it predicted a\\ndirect JAL/backward branch as taken. ID passes that bit to EX. EX comp...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Fast-path simple ALU results\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv to compute simple RV32I results in a small fast cone: ADD/ADDI/address-generation as a dedicated sum, SUB as a dedicated difference, and LUI as the direct immediate operand. Keep the existing non-simple RV32I mux for logic, shifts, and comparisons, and keep the RV32M mux and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions behaviorally unchanged. The final ...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Register fetch decode boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nA minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nA minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single valid IF/ID pipeline register owned by if_stage, with explicit consume/hold behavior so an imem-not-ready cycle drains to one bubble instead of replaying the previous instruction. When decode is stalled by dmem backpressure, hold the IF/ID register and PC; when imem is ready and decode can advance, capture pc, instr, and pred_next_pc from the existing static predictor. Redirects flush the registered IF/ID payload and update PC exactly as today.\\n\\nThis turns the current pseudo five-stage pipe into a true fetch/decode split without adding multi-entry queue state, tag...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Gate static branch target formation\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor change with a large proven CoreMark gain is the current\\nstateless fetch rule: predict direct JAL taken and backward conditional\\nbranches taken. Later predictor attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, skid buffering, or extra target muxing all regressed from\\nIF-stage timing and control cost. The remaining predictor opportunity is\\ntherefore not a smarter predictor, but a cheaper implementation of the same\\nsuccessful policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor change with a large proven CoreMark gain is the current\\nstateless fetch rule: predict direct JAL taken and backward conditional\\nbranches taken. Later predictor attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, skid buffering, or extra target muxing all regressed from\\nIF-stage timing and control cost. The remaining predictor opportunity is\\ntherefore not a smarter predictor, but a cheaper implementation of the same\\nsuccessful policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the exact JAL-always-taken and backward-branch-taken behavior, but\\nrewrite the IF predictor so branch target formation is gated by the cheap\\nbranch-opcode and sign-bit predicate before the B-immediate shuffle and\\npc-plus-branch-target adder are used. Forward conditional branches should\\nfall through through the pc+4 path without driving the full branch-target\\ncone, while JAL keeps its existing direct target path.\\n\\nThis targets median FPGA Fmax with unchanged CoreMark IPC and avoids the\\nfailed pattern of adding predictor state or new redirect sources. Correctness\\nis unchanged because EX still compares the resolved next PC against the\\ncarried pred_next_pc and repairs every mismatch before retirement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refactor the existing static predictor...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Gate EX control target arithmetic\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from reducing unnecessary fetch-side branch target work and isolating the ALU's RV32M mux. The execute stage still unconditionally forms branch targets, JAL/JALR targets, pc+4, and branch comparison results even for ordinary ALU and load/store instructions that only need the ALU result and fall-through next PC.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot path is dominated by integer arithmetic, address generation, and loads/stores, so pruning duplicate control-flow arithmetic from the common EX cone may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax without changing cycle count, prediction policy, memory behavior, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from reducing unnecessary fetch-side branch target work and isolating the ALU's RV32M mux. The execute stage still unconditionally forms branch targets, JAL/JALR targets, pc+4, and branch comparison results even for ordinary ALU and load/store instructions that only need the ALU result and fall-through next PC.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot path is dominated by integer arithmetic, address generation, and loads/stores, so pruning duplicate control-flow arithmetic from the common EX cone may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax without changing cycle count, prediction policy, memory behavior, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv so control-flow next-PC work is explicitly factored and gated. Compute pc_plus4 once, share one pc_plus_imm target for both conditional branches and JAL, compute the JALR rs1+imm target only for JALR, and only evaluate the full branch comparator case when ctrl.is_branch is set. Non-control instructions should drive resolved_next_pc directly from pc_plus4 and avoid the branch/jump target mux tree.\\n\\nThis is intentionally a narrow timing cleanup, not a new predictor or early redirect. It preserves t...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Sidecar iterative divider\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU still contains full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators even though CoreMark's hot timed path is dominated by loads, stores,\\nbranches, integer ALU ops, and occasional multiply. Prior structural attempts\\nthat added front-end queues, store buffering, early JALR, or register-file\\nrestructuring regressed because they added control to hot paths. Removing the\\nrare divider/remainder cone from the single-cycle EX result path is a more\\nlocalized structural change with a direct chance to improve FPGA Fmax and LUT\\npressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU still contains full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators even though CoreMark's hot timed path is dominated by loads, stores,\\nbranches, integer ALU ops, and occasional multiply. Prior structural attempts\\nthat added front-end queues, store buffering, early JALR, or register-file\\nrestructuring regressed because they added control to hot paths. Removing the\\nrare divider/remainder cone from the single-cycle EX result path is a more\\nlocalized structural change with a direct chance to improve FPGA Fmax and LUT\\npressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M division and remainder out of the combinational ALU into a small\\niterative divide sidecar that is only activated for DIV, DIVU, REM, and REMU.\\nEX should hold ID/EX and suppress EX/MEM advancement while the sidecar is busy,\\nthen inject the completed quotient or remainder into the normal EX/MEM result\\npath with the original instruction metadata intact. ADD/SUB/logic/shift,\\naddress generation, branches, jumps, and MUL/MULH variants remain one-cycle,\\nand RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS keeps its one-cycle substituted behavior. This should\\nimprove median Tang Nano 20K Fmax more than it costs IPC because real divide\\nand remainder instructions are rare in the benchmark window.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_d...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Gate static JAL target formation\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor result is still the stateless direct-control rule:\\npredict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Later attempts to\\nadd predictor state, richer direction heuristics, indirect prediction, or\\nfetch buffering mostly regressed from added IF-path cost. The latest win came\\nfrom keeping the same policy while gating branch-target formation, which\\nsuggests the best remaining predictor angle is another fetch-path pruning\\nchange rather than smarter prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor result is still the stateless direct-control rule:\\npredict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Later attempts to\\nadd predictor state, richer direction heuristics, indirect prediction, or\\nfetch buffering mostly regressed from added IF-path cost. The latest win came\\nfrom keeping the same policy while gating branch-target formation, which\\nsuggests the best remaining predictor angle is another fetch-path pruning\\nchange rather than smarter prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the exact current prediction behavior, but gate JAL immediate shuffle and\\nJAL target addition behind the cheap JAL opcode predicate. Today the fetch\\npredictor still forms the J-immediate and pc-plus-JAL target for every fetched\\ninstruction even though only opcode 1101111 can select that path. Non-JAL\\ninstructions should use the existing pc+4 or gated backward-branch path\\nwithout driving the JAL target cone.\\n\\nThis should improve median FPGA Fmax with no CoreMark IPC change, preserve the\\nsuccessful static predictor, and avoid the failed pattern of adding BHT/RAS/\\nloop/JALR state. EX still compares resolved_next_pc against the carried\\npred_next_pc, so architectural correction, RVFI pc_wdata, and NRET=1\\nretirement behavior are unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"cha...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Recode M ALU op class\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already separates the RV32I and RV32M ALU result cones, but\\nthe final result still depends on decoding a contiguous mixed numeric range of\\nALU op values to decide whether the M-extension mux should be selected. Prior\\nbroad ALU resource sharing and extra fast paths regressed, so the safest timing\\nopportunity is a tiny encoding cleanup that preserves the existing datapaths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already separates the RV32I and RV32M ALU result cones, but\\nthe final result still depends on decoding a contiguous mixed numeric range of\\nALU op values to decide whether the M-extension mux should be selected. Prior\\nbroad ALU resource sharing and extra fast paths regressed, so the safest timing\\nopportunity is a tiny encoding cleanup that preserves the existing datapaths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Reassign the internal ALU op localparams so every RV32M operation has op[4]=1\\nand every RV32I operation keeps op[4]=0. Then simplify rtl/alu.sv so the final\\nRV32I-versus-RV32M result select is just op[4] rather than an eight-arm case or\\nsynthesized range compare.\\n\\nThis should slightly reduce EX-stage control decode and output-mux fan-in around\\nthe already successful RV32I/RV32M split, improving median FPGA Fmax without any\\nCoreMark cycle-count change. The decoder still recognizes the same RV32IM\\nencodings, the ALTOPS formulas remain behaviorally identical, and the NRET=1\\nRVFI contract is untouched.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Recode ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU to values with bit 4 set while keeping all RV32I ALU op values below 16.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the M-op membership case with the encoded op[4] class bit and keep the existing RV32I, RV32M, and ALTOPS result logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\"...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Skid one ALU op behind dmem stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry execute skid register for safe younger instructions while EX/MEM is holding an older stalled memory operation. When dmem_stall is asserted and ID/EX holds a valid non-memory, non-branch, non-jump instruction that does not depend on the stalled load's rd, EX computes it once and captures the full ex_mem_t result into the skid entry. The front end and ID/EX then remain held until the older memory operation completes; after the memory instruction retires, the skid entry drains into the normal EX/MEM to MEM/WB path before any newly decoded instruction advances.\\n\\nThis is intentionally not a general store buffer, fetch FIFO, or out-of-order engine. It only hides one cycle of memory backpressure for independent straight-line ALU/LUI/AUIPC/MUL-class work, preserves strict in-order RVFI retirement by draining after the older memory op, and leaves loads, stores, branches, jum...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Gate predictor repair compare\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\\nrule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\\ncheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\\nJAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\\n\\nOne remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\\nincluding ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\\npred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\\nrequire predictor repair.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\\nrule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\\ncheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\\nJAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\\n\\nOne remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\\nincluding ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\\npred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\\nrequire predictor repair.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Preserve the exact existing fetch prediction policy and pred_next_pc metadata,\\nbut gate the EX-stage redirect/mispredict compare with the decoded control-flow\\nclass. Non-branch, non-jump instructions should never assert redirect, so they\\ncan bypass the 32-bit next-PC mismatch check and simply retire with pc+4 as\\ntoday. Branches and JAL/JALR continue to compute resolved_next_pc exactly as\\nthey do now, including misaligned-target trap handling, and still compare\\nagainst pred_next_pc to repair bad pr...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Factor forwarding matches\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but that makes the forwarding selector part of a hot EX operand path. Recent attempts that added state, new stalls, or broad datapath gating regressed, so the next micro_opt should be a very small cleanup that preserves the proven pipeline behavior.\\n\\nThe existing forward_unit repeats the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB register-destination comparisons inside separate ALU-result, load-result, and writeback arms for each source operand. Even if synthesis can sometimes common-subexpression these terms, making the producer matches explicit should reduce comparator duplication, fanout, and select-control depth with no cycle-count or architectural risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but that makes the forwarding selector part of a hot EX operand path. Recent attempts that added state, new stalls, or broad datapath gating regressed, so the next micro_opt should be a very small cleanup that preserves the proven pipeline behavior.\\n\\nThe existing forward_unit repeats the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB register-destination comparisons inside separate ALU-result, load-result, and writeback arms for each source operand. Even if synthesis can sometimes common-subexpression these terms, making the producer matches explicit should reduce comparator duplication, fanout, and select-control depth with no cycle-count or architectural risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/forward_unit.sv to compute per-source producer match terms once: ex_mem_match_rs1/rs2 and mem_wb_match_rs1/rs2. Then choose EX/MEM ALU forwarding, MEM load forwarding, MEM/WB forwarding, or no forwarding from those match terms plus the existing ex_mem_is_load and ex_mem_load_fwd_valid qualifiers.\\n\\nThis keeps the same priority order and preserves the ready-qualifi...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Register final writeback value\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB stage carries both alu_result and read_data, then selects the\\narchitectural writeback value through a combinational WB mux. That mux output\\nfans out to the register file write port, same-cycle regfile read bypass,\\nMEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata. Prior structural attempts that\\nadded queues, buffers, or sidecars regressed because they added broad control;\\nthis targets a narrower pipeline-boundary fanout point without changing IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB stage carries both alu_result and read_data, then selects the\\narchitectural writeback value through a combinational WB mux. That mux output\\nfans out to the register file write port, same-cycle regfile read bypass,\\nMEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata. Prior structural attempts that\\nadded queues, buffers, or sidecars regressed because they added broad control;\\nthis targets a narrower pipeline-boundary fanout point without changing IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a preselected rd_wdata field to the MEM/WB payload and compute it in\\nmem_stage when the MEM/WB register captures. Loads register the extended\\nload_data, while ALU/JAL/JALR/LUI/AUIPC results register the existing\\nalu_result. Then make wb_stage and RVFI consume that registered final value\\ndirectly instead of rebuilding the mem_to_reg mux in WB. This should shorten\\nthe WB forwarding and register-file bypass cone, reduce ctrl.mem_to_reg\\nfanout, and preserve the current single-retire RVFI ordering and all memory\\nmetadata. During dmem stalls, the held MEM/WB fields keep the registered\\nrd_wdata alive for the existing forwarding behavior while valid is cleared.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an rd_wdata field to mem_wb_t so the final architectural writeback value is registere...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Drop JAL fetch prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor lesson is that added state or richer control-flow\\nheuristics have repeatedly cost more FPGA timing than they saved in CoreMark\\nbubbles. The current IF predictor still forms a JAL immediate and JAL target\\nfor every fetched instruction, and the recent attempt to gate that path\\nregressed from extra mux/control cost. If direct JALs are uncommon inside the\\nbracketed CoreMark hot loops after -O3 inlining, removing this predictor path\\noutright may recover Fmax while keeping the proven backward-branch prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor lesson is that added state or richer control-flow\\nheuristics have repeatedly cost more FPGA timing than they saved in CoreMark\\nbubbles. The current IF predictor still forms a JAL immediate and JAL target\\nfor every fetched instruction, and the recent attempt to gate that path\\nregressed from extra mux/control cost. If direct JALs are uncommon inside the\\nbracketed CoreMark hot loops after -O3 inlining, removing this predictor path\\noutright may recover Fmax while keeping the proven backward-branch prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep conditional branch prediction exactly as it is today: backward branches\\nare predicted taken and forward branches fall through. Stop predicting direct\\nJAL in IF, so JAL follows pc+4 and is repaired by the existing EX-stage\\nresolved_next_pc versus pred_next_pc redirect check. This deletes the\\nalways-active J-immediate shuffle, JAL target adder, and JAL arm of the IF\\npredicted-next-PC mux instead of trying to gate them. The expected cycle loss\\nis limited if timed CoreMark has few direct JALs, while the Fmax gain can\\napply to every fetch cycle.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove direct-JAL target formation and prediction from the fetch pred...","metadata":{"matches":37,"truncated":false},"title":"micro_opt|forward|operand|branch|ALU|critical|timing|Fmax|regression|improvement","time":{"start":1778633182547,"end":1778633182556}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06dc5d4c47ab4626016a03c9de6a70819bba2a765655f16910"}},"id":"prt_e1ecc8d51002FVbWG0tlinRnV3","sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","messageID":"msg_e1ecc64b9001W4sKNI86Ja29nT"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778633182561,"sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_goldlgQlmAoqGjnuVPVzXZiN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +4.17%): Decode-to-IF JAL fast paths can lose more to added imem/decode/PC-mux timing than they save in bubbles, so direct jumps are better handled by a lightweight fetch predictor or kept off the critical PC path.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (regression, +3.34%): A sequential IF FIFO that only buffers pc+4 fetches did not hide enough randomized imem/dmem backpressure to pay for its extra queue/control state, so front-end decoupling needs redirect-aware prefetch value beyond isolated stall absorption.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (improvement, +19.74%): Static fetch prediction for JAL and backward BRANCH targets pays on CoreMark's tight counted loops because carrying pred_next_pc to EX removes taken-back-edge redirect bubbles without BTB state or broadening the critical path much.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-to-store stalls can only be pruned if the MEM-stage store-data bypass also updates RVFI rs2 source metadata; fixing dmem_wdata alone leaves stale ID-read operands that riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -10.26%): A one-entry store buffer that still stalls all younger loads/stores behind sb_valid adds dmem mux/control cost without enough CoreMark memory-level parallelism to offset it; store decoupling needs forwarding or deeper disambiguation to pay.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -1.79%): A tiny non-speculative RAS for canonical JALR returns adds IF-stage stack/index/PC-mux control that CoreMark's remaining call-return bubbles do not repay, so indirect-return prediction needs very low fetch-path cost to be worthwhile.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (broken, n/a): Source-aware load-use pruning should gate only hazard comparisons unless the cosim/RVFI contract is updated too; zeroing unused rs1/rs2 metadata for JAL/LUI/AUIPC-style instructions breaks the bench ISS trace, which reports raw instruction register fields.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (improvement, +4.90%): MEM-stage extended load forwarding pays on CoreMark's pointer-heavy load-use chains when dmemReady qualifies the bypass and branch/JALR redirects wait for ready forwarded operands, removing interlock bubbles without weakening RVFI source tracking.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -9.20%): A 16-entry tagged 2-bit BHT in IF adds enough counter/tag read and update state to outweigh the few CoreMark misses left after JAL plus backward-branch static prediction, so dynamic direction needs a cheaper fetch-path integration or stronger bias target.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -11.19%): Sharing RV32M work inside the combinational ALU can hurt synthesis timing more than it saves area; a single 33x33 signed multiplier plus centralized div/rem datapath is a wider rare-op cone than simple per-op expressions.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -9.78%): Refining the static backward-branch predictor by funct3 hurt CoreMark, suggesting backward BEQ and other simple back-edge cases are common enough that the coarse all-backward-taken rule beats extra direction bias logic in IF.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -11.92%): Removing the small reg-file reset loop and x0 storage did not pay on Tang Nano 20K; the reset fanout was not the limiting path, and the irregular 31-entry array can cost more synthesis/routing quality than it saves.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -9.62%): Forcing the reg file toward resetless LUTRAM with scrub/init-mask logic added read-side masking and pipeline holdoff control that outweighed reset-fanout savings, so RF area optimizations must stay off the ID read critical path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -5.56%): Even an exact one-entry JALR target memo regressed after static JAL/backward-BRANCH prediction; its IF-stage opcode/funct3/PC compare and target mux cost outweighed CoreMark's remaining repeated-indirect bubbles.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (regression, -10.61%): Replacing MEM load shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] lane cases can duplicate mux/decode cones on the load-forwarding path; FPGA synthesis already handled the compact variable-shift form better here.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -13.31%): Exact ID-stage JALR redirects still put rs1 dependency compares, target add/alignment, and an early PC mux on decode/fetch timing, so ready-indirect bubble recovery must be nearly free to beat the current EX redirect path.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -11.99%): A one-entry loop-exit predictor still adds IF-stage PC/count compares and predictor update state, and CoreMark's final counted-loop exit misses are too sparse to repay that cost after the static JAL/backward-BRANCH rule.\n18: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (regression, -12.38%): Manually splitting late ctrl_t into compact EX/MEM and MEM/WB payloads can hurt more than help when synthesis already prunes unused branch/decode bits, because the added control repacking and trap muxing create new late-stage cones.\n19: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.45%): Making MEM-to-EX load bypass word-only saved subword lane logic but added width-dependent interlock and branch-wait control that cost more, so CoreMark's load-use path favors one simple ready-qualified forwarding scheme over selective bypass pruning.\n20: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -11.22%): Sharing the static predictor target adder by muxing a 32-bit JAL/BRANCH offset before pc+offset can lengthen the IF critical path more than parallel target adds, so PC-path arithmetic sharing is not automatically cheaper.\n21: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r8s0 (improvement, +3.03%): Splitting the ALU into a compact RV32I result cone plus a separate RV32M mux improves CoreMark timing because hot ADD/SUB/compare/address ops avoid the wide multiply/divide/remainder selector without changing IPC.\n22: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r8s1 (regression, -7.51%): Even predictor-aware two-entry IF skid buffering adds fetch-PC, queue-count, and enqueue/dequeue control cost that CoreMark's randomized bus stalls did not repay after static JAL/backward-branch prediction.\n23: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r8s2 (regression, -2.05%): Compressing static predictor metadata from pred_next_pc to a direction bit did not pay, implying the IF/ID register width and EX next-PC comparator were not the limiting cost compared with the remaining redirect/control logic.\n24: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r9s0 (regression, -2.90%): Further splitting ADD/SUB/LUI into a separate simple-ALU priority path can add op-decode and final-result mux control that outweighs any reduction in the already-isolated RV32I case mux.\n25: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r9s1 (regression, +5.10%): A single registered IF/ID boundary with imem-ready drain control still regressed, so the imem-to-decode cone is not the current limiter and CoreMark favors the existing zero-latency fetch/decode handoff over extra redirect/fill latency.\n26: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r9s2 (improvement, +14.85%): Gating B-immediate formation with branch opcode plus sign bit keeps the successful static JAL/backward-BRANCH policy while letting forward branches use pc+4 without driving the full branch-target cone, so predictor wins here come from fetch-path pruning rather than added state.\n27: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r10s0 (regression, -48.12%): Gating EX-stage branch/JAL/JALR target arithmetic behind is_branch/is_jump muxes can add more control and selector depth than unconditional parallel pc+imm, rs1+imm, and comparator cones, so late control-flow arithmetic is best kept simple unless timing reports prove it is critical.\n28: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r10s1 (regression, -13.71%): Moving DIV/REM into an iterative EX sidecar can cost more than the divider cone it removes because start/busy/done, EX/MEM bubble injection, and ID/EX hold control sit on common pipeline timing while CoreMark rarely executes divides.\n29: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r10s2 (regression, -12.64%): Gating IF-stage JAL immediate/target formation adds opcode-controlled muxing that can cost more than the unconditional J-immediate adder, so fetch pruning must be validated per target cone rather than extrapolated from the B-immediate win.\n30: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r11s0 (regression, -1.85%): Recoding ALU op values so `op[4]` directly selects RV32M can still regress timing; a removed local case decode may be cheaper than adding a high-fanout semantic bit to the final ALU mux select.\n31: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r11s1 (regression, -13.91%): A one-entry EX skid slot behind stalled dmem ops adds skiddability dependency checks plus capture/drain muxing on common hazard and EX/MEM paths, and CoreMark's in-order drain opportunity is too small to offset that control cost.\n32: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r11s2 (regression, -22.68%): Gating the EX redirect mismatch compare behind `can_redirect` adds late decoded/opcode control on the repair path that costs more than the unconditional `resolved_next_pc != pred_next_pc` compare.\n33: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r12s0 (improvement, +4.12%): Factoring EX/MEM and MEM/WB producer register matches once in the forward unit can improve Fmax because duplicated rd/rs comparators and priority qualifiers sit directly on the hot EX operand mux select path.\n34: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r12s1 (regression, +0.19%): Registering MEM/WB rd_wdata instead of selecting the WB mux late was effectively neutral, implying the load-vs-ALU writeback mux fanout is not a current timing limiter compared with forwarding select/control cones.\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +4.17%): Decode-to-IF JAL fast paths can lose more to added imem/decode/PC-mux timing than they save in bubbles, so direct jumps are better handled by a lightweight fetch predictor or kept off the critical PC path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (regression, +3.34%): A sequential IF FIFO that only buffers pc+4 fetches did not hide enough randomized imem/dmem backpressure to pay for its extra queue/control state, so front-end decoupling needs redirect-aware prefetch value beyond isolated stall absorption.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (improvement, +19.74%): Static fetch prediction for JAL and backward BRANCH targets pays on CoreMark's tight counted loops because carrying pred_next_pc to EX removes taken-back-edge redirect bubbles without BTB state or broadening the critical path much.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-to-store stalls can only be pruned if the MEM-stage store-data bypass also updates RVFI rs2 source metadata; fixing dmem_wdata alone leaves stale ID-read operands that riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -10.26%): A one-entry store buffer that still stalls all younger loads/stores behind sb_valid adds dmem mux/control cost without enough CoreMark memory-level parallelism to offset it; store decoupling needs forwarding or deeper disambiguation to pay.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -1.79%): A tiny non-speculative RAS for canonical JALR returns adds IF-stage stack/index/PC-mux control that CoreMark's remaining call-return bubbles do not repay, so indirect-return prediction needs very low fetch-path cost to be worthwhile.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (broken, n/a): Source-aware load-use pruning should gate only hazard comparisons unless the cosim/RVFI contract is updated too; zeroing unused rs1/rs2 metadata for JAL/LUI/AUIPC-style instructions breaks the bench ISS trace, which reports raw instruction register fields.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (improvement, +4.90%): MEM-stage extended load forwarding pays on CoreMark's pointer-heavy load-use chains when dmemReady qualifies the bypass and branch/JALR redirects wait for ready forwarded operands, removing interlock bubbles without weakening RVFI source tracking.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -9.20%): A 16-entry tagged 2-bit BHT in IF adds enough counter/tag read and update state to outweigh the few CoreMark misses left after JAL plus backward-branch static prediction, so dynamic direction needs a cheaper fetch-path integration or stronger bias target.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -11.19%): Sharing RV32M work inside the combinational ALU can hurt synthesis timing more than it saves area; a single 33x33 signed multiplier plus centralized div/rem datapath is a wider rare-op cone than simple per-op expressions.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -9.78%): Refining the static backward-branch predictor by funct3 hurt CoreMark, suggesting backward BEQ and other simple back-edge cases are common enough that the coarse all-backward-taken rule beats extra direction bias logic in IF.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -11.92%): Removing the small reg-file reset loop and x0 storage did not pay on Tang Nano 20K; the reset fanout was not the limiting path, and the irregular 31-entry array can cost more synthesis/routing quality than it saves.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -9.62%): Forcing the reg file toward