{"type":"text","timestamp":1778633194803,"sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","part":{"id":"prt_e1eccbc9f002HaOhHuvngEK6gB","messageID":"msg_e1ecc8daf001d9PpY9hBByK5Yw","sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","type":"text","text":"The prior wins now point toward very small timing cleanups around hot control/forwarding rather than added state. I’m going to write a narrow `micro_opt` hypothesis that removes stale, unused load-use hazard inputs from the hazard path to reduce fanout/routing without changing pipeline behavior.","time":{"start":1778633194655,"end":1778633194803},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0f6795de6ebe8b51016a03c9ea8b98819a9ac243be2ef181ed","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778633203067,"sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Ztyf52wDeRCE5VXWWOrYgIoW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\n+title: \"Prune dead hazard inputs\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core already removed load-use bubbles with MEM-to-EX load forwarding, and the recent successful micro-opt was a tiny cleanup on the forwarding select path. The hazard unit still carries the old load-use interlock inputs from ID/EX and IF/ID even though they are now explicitly unused, which needlessly fans out hot instruction, rd, and control signals into an extra module boundary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the obsolete load-use interlock ports from rtl/hazard_unit.sv and their wiring in rtl/core.sv. The unit should continue to control only redirects plus imem/dmem backpressure exactly as it does today, preserving MEM-to-EX load forwarding, RVFI ordering, traps, memory behavior, and the NRET=1 top-level port set.\n+\n+  This should slightly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax by reducing routing pressure and synthesis-visible fanout from IF/ID instruction fields and ID/EX load metadata, with zero cycle-count change and very low architectural risk. It deliberately avoids reintroducing source-aware load-use logic, store bypasses, or any predictor/control-path state that prior iterations showed to be fragile.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Delete the unused id_ex_mem_read, id_ex_rd, if_id_rs1, and if_id_rs2 ports and lint suppressions, leaving only redirect and bus-stall control logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the corresponding dead hazard_unit connections so IF/ID instruction bits and ID/EX load metadata no longer fan out into the hazard module.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\n+title: \"Prune dead hazard inputs\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core already removed load-use bubbles with MEM-to-EX load forwarding, and the recent successful micro-opt was a tiny cleanup on the forwarding select path. The hazard unit still carries the old load-use interlock inputs from ID/EX and IF/ID even though they are now explicitly unused, which needlessly fans out hot instruction, rd, and control signals into an extra module boundary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the obsolete load-use interlock ports from rtl/hazard_unit.sv and their wiring in rtl/core.sv. The unit should continue to control only redirects plus imem/dmem backpressure exactly as it does today, preserving MEM-to-EX load forwarding, RVFI ordering, traps, memory behavior, and the NRET=1 top-level port set.\n+\n+  This should slightly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax by reducing routing pressure and synthesis-visible fanout from IF/ID instruction fields and ID/EX load metadata, with zero cycle-count change and very low architectural risk. It deliberately avoids reintroducing source-aware load-use logic, store bypasses, or any predictor/control-path state that prior iterations showed to be fragile.\n+expected_i