{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778633210734,"sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_TIxHmkGUeJTs485rkdVGRECp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\n2: title: \"Prune dead hazard inputs\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current best bench core already removed load-use bubbles with MEM-to-EX load forwarding, and the recent successful micro-opt was a tiny cleanup on the forwarding select path. The hazard unit still carries the old load-use interlock inputs from ID/EX and IF/ID even though they are now explicitly unused, which needlessly fans out hot instruction, rd, and control signals into an extra module boundary.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Remove the obsolete load-use interlock ports from rtl/hazard_unit.sv and their wiring in rtl/core.sv. The unit should continue to control only redirects plus imem/dmem backpressure exactly as it does today, preserving MEM-to-EX load forwarding, RVFI ordering, traps, memory behavior, and the NRET=1 top-level port set.\n8: \n9:   This should slightly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax by reducing routing pressure and synthesis-visible fanout from IF/ID instruction fields and ID/EX load metadata, with zero cycle-count change and very low architectural risk. It deliberately avoids reintroducing source-aware load-use logic, store bypasses, or any predictor/control-path state that prior iterations showed to be fragile.\n10: expected_impact:\n11:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n12:   confidence: medium\n13: changes:\n14:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n15:     description: \"Delete the unused id_ex_mem_read, id_ex_rd, if_id_rs1, and if_id_rs2 ports and lint suppressions, leaving only redirect and bus-stall control logic.\"\n16:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n17:     description: \"Remove the corresponding dead hazard_unit connections so IF/ID instruction bits and ID/EX load metadata no longer fan out into the hazard module.\"\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\ntitle: \"Prune dead hazard inputs\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current best bench core already removed load-use bubbles with MEM-to-EX load forwarding, and the recent successful micro-opt was a tiny cleanup on the forwarding select path. The hazard unit still carries the old load-use interlock inputs from ID/EX and IF/ID even though they are now explicitly unused, which needlessly fans out hot instruction, rd, and control signals into an extra module boundary.\nhypothesis: |\n  Remove the obsolete load-use interlock ports from rtl/hazard_unit.sv and their wiring in rtl/core.sv. The unit should continue to control only redirects plus imem/dmem backpressure exactly as it does today, preserving MEM-to-EX load forwarding, RVFI ordering, traps, memory behavior, and the NRET=1 top-level port set.\n\n  This should slightly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax by reducing routing pressure and synthesis-visible fanout from IF/ID instruction fields and ID/EX load metadata, with zero cycle-count change and very low architectural risk. It deliberately avoids reintroducing source-aware load-use logic, store bypasses, or any predictor/control-path state that prior iterations showed to be fragile.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Delete the unused id_ex_mem_read, id_ex_rd, if_id_rs1, and if_id_rs2 ports and lint suppressions, leaving only redirect and bus-stall control logic.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Remove the corresponding dead hazard_unit connections so IF/ID instruction bits and ID/EX load metadata no longer fan out into the hazard module.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r13s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778633210723,"end":1778633210733}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02ced2194c8dcbb6016a03c9fa682481989450e882a7ae9293"}},"id":"prt_e1eccfa800013XgGGkqdcDnZh1","sessionID":"ses_1e1339b88ffeesp0m9sJguS317","messageID":"msg_e1eccddc6002ptz1DsLES6FP7c"}}
