{"type":"text","timestamp":1778634220133,"sessionID":"ses_1e12497f5ffeSbuhADgHT2Gd26","part":{"id":"prt_e1edc6184001lUn5vCPJjcKzt5","messageID":"msg_e1edb8977001UUiVgh5US5wBrJ","sessionID":"ses_1e12497f5ffeSbuhADgHT2Gd26","type":"text","text":"The prior data points away from broad rewrites and syntax-only cleanup. I’m choosing a narrow micro-opt on the hot EX operand path: carry explicit decoded source-use bits into forwarding so unused operands do not drive producer-match and forwarding-select control, while preserving raw RVFI source addresses/data semantics.","time":{"start":1778634219908,"end":1778634220132},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_063edcd4cc07923d016a03cdebc850819bbeaea287edf7d564","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778634235799,"sessionID":"ses_1e12497f5ffeSbuhADgHT2Gd26","part":{"id":"prt_e1edc9f2c001iRw1E9PWZY6eEc","messageID":"msg_e1edb8977001UUiVgh5US5wBrJ","sessionID":"ses_1e12497f5ffeSbuhADgHT2Gd26","type":"text","text":"I’ll write the hypothesis as a small dynamic-forwarding encoding change rather than source-aware pruning, because it preserves operand/RVFI behavior exactly and targets the same forwarding-select cone that most recently improved Fmax.","time":{"start":1778634235692,"end":1778634235796},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_063edcd4cc07923d016a03cdfb986c819bb54f402294d3ea0f","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778634242442,"sessionID":"ses_1e12497f5ffeSbuhADgHT2Gd26","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_9HsUX3ZinMkzyMu18tPaCyLo","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r14s0\n+title: \"One-hot forwarding selects\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The recent successful micro-opt showed that the EX operand forwarding selector is still a timing-sensitive path after MEM-to-EX load forwarding. The current forward unit already factors producer matches, but it still encodes each source choice into a two-bit select that EX immediately decodes back into a four-way operand mux.\n+\n+  Prior attempts to move forwarding decisions earlier regressed because dmem stalls and producer validity made stale hints expensive to repair. A smaller dynamic encoding cleanup can keep the same late, correct match logic while reducing select decode depth on the hot operand path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the binary fwd_rs1_sel/fwd_rs2_sel controls with one-hot forwarding controls for NONE, EX/MEM ALU, MEM/WB, and MEM load. The forward_unit should continue computing the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB match terms and the same priority order, but drive one-hot vectors directly. The EX stage should use those vectors in one-hot operand muxes instead of case-decoding a two-bit selector.\n+\n+  This preserves all cycle behavior, dmem-ready-qualified load forwarding semantics, RVFI source values, memory ordering, traps, and the NRET=1 top-level port set. The expected benefit is modest Fmax improvement from removing binary encode/decode and reducing LUT depth in the forwarding-select-to-ALU-input cone, with lower risk than predecoded forwarding or broader source-aware pruning.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Change rs1/rs2 forwarding outputs from two-bit encoded selects to one-hot controls while preserving existing producer-match factoring and priority.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume one-hot forwarding controls with behavior-equivalent operand muxes and keep forwarded rs1/rs2 values latched for RVFI exactly as today.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update forwarding-control wire declarations and module connections without changing the core top-level IO or NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r14s0\n+title: \"One-hot forwarding selects\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The recent successful micro-opt showed that the EX operand forwarding selector is still a timing-sensitive path after MEM-to-EX load forwarding. The current forward unit already factors producer matches, but it still encodes each source choice into a two-bit select that EX immediately decodes back into a four-way operand mux.\n+\n+  Prior attempts to move forwarding decisions earlier regressed because dmem stalls and producer validity made stale hints expensive to repair. A smaller dynamic encoding cleanup can keep the same late, correct match logic while reducing select decode depth on the hot operand path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the binary fwd_rs1_sel/fwd_rs2_sel controls with one-hot forwarding controls for NONE, EX/MEM ALU, MEM/WB, and MEM load. The forward_unit should continue computing the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB match terms and the same priority order, but drive one-hot vectors directly. The EX stage should use those vectors in one-hot operand muxes instead of case-decoding a two-bit selector.\n+\n+  This preserves all cycle behavior, dmem-ready-qualified load forwarding semantics, RVFI source values, memory ordering, traps, and the NRET=1 top-level port set. The expected benefit is modest Fmax improvement from removing binary encode/decode and reducing LUT depth in the forwarding-select-to-ALU-input cone, with lower risk than predecoded forwarding or broader source-aware pruning.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Change rs1/rs2 forwarding outputs from two-bit encoded selects to one-hot controls while preserving existing producer-match factoring and priority.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume one-hot forwarding controls with behavior-equivalent operand muxes and keep forwarded rs1/rs2 values latched for RVFI exactly as today.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update forwarding-control wire declarations and module connections without changing the core top-level IO or NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-