{"type":"text","timestamp":1778635212512,"sessionID":"ses_1e1157f78ffe8Ay8SmEz377dxA","part":{"id":"prt_e1eeb8339001NZ4WMDzki4suUc","messageID":"msg_e1eeb7239001CYQNAE8OsBdNyw","sessionID":"ses_1e1157f78ffe8Ay8SmEz377dxA","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the hypothesis as a small control-path micro-optimization: make load writeback selection derive from `mem_read` and remove the redundant `mem_to_reg` bit through decode and late pipeline control, avoiding new state or IPC changes.","time":{"start":1778635211577,"end":1778635212512},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0e9e242c46a97258016a03d1cb7c70819ab1bcd8ce36001d94","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778635224048,"sessionID":"ses_1e1157f78ffe8Ay8SmEz377dxA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_RHMX1Yc9bngKVKA8eTBaOZq3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r15s0\n+title: Alias load writeback select\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best recent bench improvements came from very localized timing cleanups: isolating the RV32M ALU mux, factoring forwarding matches, and registering memory request metadata. Broader rewrites of forwarding, late metadata, the register file, and fetch/control state have usually regressed from extra muxing or routing perturbation.\n+\n+  A small remaining redundant control bit is `mem_to_reg`. In this core it is asserted exactly for loads, while `mem_read` is already carried through the same pipeline control bundle for memory behavior and load forwarding. Keeping both bits through decode, ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB adds decode assignments, packed control width, and WB mux fanout without representing an independent architectural choice.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the independent `mem_to_reg` control signal and use `mem_read` as the load-result writeback selector. Loads still write `read_data`, all other register-writing instructions still write `alu_result`, and misaligned loads remain safe because their trap path clears `reg_write`; the selected WB data is ignored when the instruction does not retire or does not write a register.\n+\n+  This should slightly reduce late control routing and the writeback/forwarding select cone without changing cycle count, memory ordering, RVFI metadata, trap behavior, or the NRET=1 top-level port set. It deliberately avoids the prior failed broad metadata split: only one semantically redundant bit is removed, and existing stage boundaries and datapaths remain intact.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Delete ctrl_t.mem_to_reg and update comments so the packed control bundle no longer carries a redundant load-writeback selector.\"\n+  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the mem_to_reg output and assignments; loads continue to be identified by mem_read with unchanged legality and memory-width decode.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Stop wiring and storing the decoder mem_to_reg signal in ctrl_decoded while preserving all existing decode, immediate, source, and valid behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Select writeback data with in.ctrl.mem_read instead of in.ctrl.mem_to_reg, keeping w_en, x0 handling, forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata behavior unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r15s0\n+title: Alias load writeback select\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best recent bench improvements came from very localized timing cleanups: isolating the RV32M ALU mux, factoring forwarding matches, and registering memory request metadata. Broader rewrites of forwarding, late metadata, the register file, and fetch/control state have usually regressed from extra muxing or routing perturbation.\n+\n+  A small remaining redundant control bit is `mem_to_reg`. In this core it is asserted exactly for loads, while `mem_read` is already carried through the same pipeline control bundle for memory behavior and load forwarding. Keeping both bits through decode, ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB adds decode assignments, packed control width, and WB mux fanout without representing an independent architectural choice.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the independent `mem_to_reg` control signal and use `mem_read` as the load-result writeback selector. Loads still write `read_data`, all other register-writing instructions still write `alu_result`, and misaligned loads remain safe because their trap path clears `reg_write`; the selected WB data is ignored when the instruction does not retire or does not write a register.\n+\n+  This should slightly reduce late control routing and the writeback/forwarding select cone without changing cycle count, memory ordering, RVFI metadata, trap behavior, or the NRET=1 top-level port set. It deliberately avoids the prior failed broad metadata split: only one semantically redundant bit is removed, and existing stage boundaries and datapaths remain intact.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Delete ctrl_t.mem_to_reg and update comments so the packed control bundle no longer carries a redundant load-writeback selector.\"\n+  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the mem_to_reg output and assignments; loads continue to be identified by mem_read with unchanged legality and memory-width decode.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Stop wiring and storing the decoder mem_to_reg signal in ctrl_decoded while preserving all existing decode, immediate, source, and valid behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Select writeback data with in.ctrl.mem_read instead of in.ctrl.mem_to_reg, keeping w_en, x0 handling, forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata behavior unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r15s0\n+title: Alias load writeback select\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best recent bench improvements came from very localized timing cleanups: isolating the RV32M ALU mux, factoring forwarding matches, and registering memory request metadata. Broader rewrites of forwarding, late metadata, the register file, and fetch/control state have usually regressed from extra muxing or routing perturbation.\n+\n+  A small remaining redundant control bit is `mem_to_reg`. In this core it is asserted exactly for loads, while `mem_read` is already carried through the same pipeline control bundle for memory behavior and load forwarding. Keeping both bits through decode, ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB adds decode assignments, packed control width, and WB mux fanout without representing an independent architectural choice.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the independent `mem_to_reg` control signal and use `mem_read` as the load-result writeback selector. Loads still write `read_data`, all other register-writing instructions still write `alu_result`, and misaligned loads remain safe because their trap path clears `reg_write`; the selected WB data is ignored when the instruction does not retire or does not write a register.\n+\n+  This should slightly reduce late control routing and the writeback/forwarding select cone without changing cycle count, memory ordering, RVFI metadata, trap behavior, or the NRET=1 top-level port set. It deliberately avoids the prior failed broad metadata split: only one semantically redundant bit is removed, and existing stage boundaries and datapaths remain intact.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Delete ctrl_t.mem_to_reg and update comments so the packed control bundle no longer carries a redundant load-writeback selector.\"\n+  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the mem_to_reg output and assignments; loads continue to be identified by mem_read with unchanged legality and memory-width decode.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Stop wiring and storing the decoder mem_to_reg signal in ctrl_decoded while preserving all existing decode, immediate, source, and valid behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Select writeback data with in.ctrl.mem_read instead of in.ctrl.mem_to_reg, keeping w_en, x0 handling, forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata behavior unchanged.\"\n","additions":23,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r15s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778635224045,"end":1778635224048}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e9e242c46a97258016a03d1cc6c18819ab7ebaee18cfb6f61"}},"id":"prt_e1eeb86e100125mLsH5wHbK2rN","sessionID":"ses_1e1157f78ffe8Ay8SmEz377dxA","messageID":"msg_e1eeb7239001CYQNAE8OsBdNyw"}}
