{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778620010574,"sessionID":"ses_1e1fcdb32ffeAirdyn469AXXyx","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_vv4HApboo8T5ditXTWxkqrhK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\n+title: \"Resolve JAL one stage earlier\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark contains frequent unconditional calls and loop-control jumps. The current\n+  pipeline treats JAL like every other control transfer and redirects from EX, so each\n+  taken JAL pays the same two wrong-path bubbles as a conditional branch even though\n+  its target is fully known from the instruction bits in decode.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a decode/IF fast path for legal JAL instructions: compute the J-immediate target\n+  from the IF/ID instruction and redirect the PC before the instruction reaches EX,\n+  while preserving the normal EX-stage JAL result and RVFI pc_wdata bookkeeping for\n+  retirement. JALR and conditional branches remain EX-resolved because they require\n+  register operands or comparison results. This should reduce CoreMark cycles by\n+  removing one redirect bubble from unconditional direct jumps with minimal timing cost.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire an early JAL redirect path from decode/IF into instruction fetch and hazard flushing without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Let fetch accept an early redirect target for legal JAL so the PC updates before the existing EX-stage redirect point.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a simple legal-JAL indication and decoded J-immediate target, reusing existing decoder and immediate generation logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Flush the fall-through instruction on early JAL redirect while keeping existing load-use and dmem stall priority intact.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\n+title: \"Resolve JAL one stage earlier\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark contains frequent unconditional calls and loop-control jumps. The current\n+  pipeline treats JAL like every other control transfer and redirects from EX, so each\n+  taken JAL pays the same two wrong-path bubbles as a conditional branch even though\n+  its target is fully known from the instruction bits in decode.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a decode/IF fast path for legal JAL instructions: compute the J-immediate target\n+  from the IF/ID instruction and redirect the PC before the instruction reaches EX,\n+  while preserving the normal EX-stage JAL result and RVFI pc_wdata bookkeeping for\n+  retirement. JALR and conditional branches remain EX-resolved because they require\n+  register operands or comparison results. This should reduce CoreMark cycles by\n+  removing one redirect bubble from unconditional direct jumps with minimal timing cost.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire an early JAL redirect path from decode/IF into instruction fetch and hazard flushing without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Let fetch accept an early redirect target for legal JAL so the PC updates before the existing EX-stage redirect point.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a simple legal-JAL indication and decoded J-immediate target, reusing existing decoder and immediate generation logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Flush the fall-through instruction on early JAL redirect while keeping existing load-use and dmem stall priority intact.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\n+title: \"Resolve JAL one stage earlier\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark contains frequent unconditional calls and loop-control jumps. The current\n+  pipeline treats JAL like every other control transfer and redirects from EX, so each\n+  taken JAL pays the same two wrong-path bubbles as a conditional branch even though\n+  its target is fully known from the instruction bits in decode.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a decode/IF fast path for legal JAL instructions: compute the J-immediate target\n+  from the IF/ID instruction and redirect the PC before the instruction reaches EX,\n+  while preserving the normal EX-stage JAL result and RVFI pc_wdata bookkeeping for\n+  retirement. JALR and conditional branches remain EX-resolved because they require\n+  register operands or comparison results. This should reduce CoreMark cycles by\n+  removing one redirect bubble from unconditional direct jumps with minimal timing cost.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire an early JAL redirect path from decode/IF into instruction fetch and hazard flushing without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Let fetch accept an early redirect target for legal JAL so the PC updates before the existing EX-stage redirect point.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a simple legal-JAL indication and decoded J-immediate target, reusing existing decoder and immediate generation logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Flush the fall-through instruction on early JAL redirect while keeping existing load-use and dmem stall priority intact.\"\n","additions":27,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778620010569,"end":1778620010573}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0759d8d0c95dba3a016a039662e15c819080ae32a2735393a0"}},"id":"prt_e1e0372a3001ZRcxzJJ9T5GXsn","sessionID":"ses_1e1fcdb32ffeAirdyn469AXXyx","messageID":"msg_e1e035db600163DwRGKYXsRuok"}}
