{"type":"text","timestamp":1778621363267,"sessionID":"ses_1e1e8bf73ffeVgAdU7XfSxYSQj","part":{"id":"prt_e1e183366001dkoQG6D6MccNac","messageID":"msg_e1e17803c002hoKFSPM2ayekke","sessionID":"ses_1e1e8bf73ffeVgAdU7XfSxYSQj","type":"text","text":"The strongest `micro_opt` angle is load-use stall precision: the current hazard unit treats `instr[24:20]` as a live `rs2` for every opcode, causing false stalls on I-type/U/J instructions and forcing a stall for load-to-store-data pairs that can be bypassed in MEM. I’m writing that as the hypothesis.","time":{"start":1778621363046,"end":1778621363266},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0759c3bd0dede215016a039bb2ea74819b917c0fba2b882281","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778621371450,"sessionID":"ses_1e1e8bf73ffeVgAdU7XfSxYSQj","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_iCkAMA2S6YpXHAQgaKsKDvtl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Prune false load-use stalls\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current load-use hazard check compares a load destination against both\n+  IF/ID register fields for every following instruction. That is conservative:\n+  I-type, load, JALR, U-type, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not consume the rs2\n+  field in EX, and store rs2 is store data that can be supplied later in MEM.\n+  CoreMark has many immediate operations and memory copies, so these false or\n+  avoidable bubbles directly reduce iterations per cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Make the load-use interlock source-aware. Only stall when the following\n+  instruction actually needs the loaded register in EX: rs1 for address/JALR/ALU\n+  operations and both operands for R-type or branch compares. For store data\n+  dependencies, allow the store to enter EX without a bubble and add a MEM-stage\n+  bypass from the current WB value to the store write-data path. This preserves\n+  precise RVFI retirement and memory masks while removing bubbles that do not\n+  protect any real EX-stage operand.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Decode IF/ID source usage for the load-use interlock so rs2 is ignored for opcodes that do not need it in EX, and store-data dependencies no longer force a bubble.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a WB-to-store-data bypass used when a store reaches MEM immediately behind a load or other producer of its rs2 value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire IF/ID instruction bits into the refined hazard logic and pass WB writeback data into MEM for store-data forwarding without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Prune false load-use stalls\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current load-use hazard check compares a load destination against both\n+  IF/ID register fields for every following instruction. That is conservative:\n+  I-type, load, JALR, U-type, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not consume the rs2\n+  field in EX, and store rs2 is store data that can be supplied later in MEM.\n+  CoreMark has many immediate operations and memory copies, so these false or\n+  avoidable bubbles directly reduce iterations per cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Make the load-use interlock source-aware. Only stall when the following\n+  instruction actually needs the loaded register in EX: rs1 for address/JALR/ALU\n+  operations and both operands for R-type or branch compares. For store data\n+  dependencies, allow the store to enter EX without a bubble and add a MEM-stage\n+  bypass from the current WB value to the store write-data path. This preserves\n+  precise RVFI retirement and memory masks while removing bubbles that do not\n+  protect any real EX-stage operand.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Decode IF/ID source usage for the load-use interlock so rs2 is ignored for opcodes that do not need it in EX, and store-data dependencies no longer force a bubble.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a WB-to-store-data bypass used when a store reaches MEM immediately behind a load or other producer of its rs2 value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire IF/ID instruction bits into the refined hazard logic and pass WB writeback data into MEM for store-data forwarding without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Prune false load-use stalls\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current load-use hazard check compares a load destination against both\n+  IF/ID register fields for every following instruction. That is conservative:\n+  I-type, load, JALR, U-type, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not consume the rs2\n+  field in EX, and store rs2 is store data that can be supplied later in MEM.\n+  CoreMark has many immediate operations and memory copies, so these false or\n+  avoidable bubbles directly reduce iterations per cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Make the load-use interlock source-aware. Only stall when the following\n+  instruction actually needs the loaded register in EX: rs1 for address/JALR/ALU\n+  operations and both operands for R-type or branch compares. For store data\n+  dependencies, allow the store to enter EX without a bubble and add a MEM-stage\n+  bypass from the current WB value to the store write-data path. This preserves\n+  precise RVFI retirement and memory masks while removing bubbles that do not\n+  protect any real EX-stage operand.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Decode IF/ID source usage for the load-use interlock so rs2 is ignored for opcodes that do not need it in EX, and store-data dependencies no longer force a bubble.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a WB-to-store-data bypass used when a store reaches MEM immediately behind a load or other producer of its rs2 value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire IF/ID instruction bits into the refined hazard logic and pass WB writeback data into MEM for store-data forwarding without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"\n","additions":28,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778621371448,"end":1778621371450}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0759c3bd0dede215016a039bb32a24819baa34f6306c7fd5cf"}},"id":"prt_e1e183448001dBsvpe9UcgIZIf","sessionID":"ses_1e1e8bf73ffeVgAdU7XfSxYSQj","messageID":"msg_e1e17803c002hoKFSPM2ayekke"}}
