{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778622388648,"sessionID":"ses_1e1d8d1e7ffeQvBTKnnVTdapD4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7qkOwUAfpWaIDbAwfO1miRFQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r3s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r3s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-001-r3s0\n2: title: \"Prune safe false rs2 load stalls\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   CoreMark has many immediate, load, jump, upper-immediate, fence, and system instructions whose instr[24:20] bits are not an EX-stage rs2 operand. The current load-use interlock still compares a load destination against that field and inserts a bubble on accidental matches, directly reducing iterations per cycle under the same single-retire pipeline.\n6: \n7:   The earlier broader load-use pruning attempt failed because it let stores pass load-data dependencies without keeping RVFI source metadata coherent. A narrower source-aware interlock can keep all store, branch, and R-type rs2 dependencies conservative while removing only false rs2 stalls that are architecturally irrelevant.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Teach the hazard unit which IF/ID instructions actually consume rs1 and rs2 in EX, and gate the load-use comparison with those source-use bits. Keep rs1 dependencies unchanged for address, JALR, branch, and ALU operands, and keep rs2 dependencies for R-type ALU, branches, and stores so no new MEM-stage bypass or RVFI source-data repair is required.\n10: \n11:   This should recover occasional bubbles after loads when the following instruction is an I-type arithmetic op, load, JALR, LUI/AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, or EBREAK with an immediate bit pattern that happens to equal the load rd. The change is localized combinational decode in the hazard path and should have low correctness risk because it does not alter forwarding, memory ordering, retirement, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n17:     description: \"Decode IF/ID opcode usage bits and apply load-use stalls only when the following instruction consumes the matching source register in EX; keep stores and other true rs2 users conservative.\"\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-001-r3s0\ntitle: \"Prune safe false rs2 load stalls\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  CoreMark has many immediate, load, jump, upper-immediate, fence, and system instructions whose instr[24:20] bits are not an EX-stage rs2 operand. The current load-use interlock still compares a load destination against that field and inserts a bubble on accidental matches, directly reducing iterations per cycle under the same single-retire pipeline.\n\n  The earlier broader load-use pruning attempt failed because it let stores pass load-data dependencies without keeping RVFI source metadata coherent. A narrower source-aware interlock can keep all store, branch, and R-type rs2 dependencies conservative while removing only false rs2 stalls that are architecturally irrelevant.\nhypothesis: |\n  Teach the hazard unit which IF/ID instructions actually consume rs1 and rs2 in EX, and gate the load-use comparison with those source-use bits. Keep rs1 dependencies unchanged for address, JALR, branch, and ALU operands, and keep rs2 dependencies for R-type ALU, branches, and stores so no new MEM-stage bypass or RVFI source-data repair is required.\n\n  This should recover occasional bubbles after loads when the following instruction is an I-type arithmetic op, load, JALR, LUI/AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, or EBREAK with an immediate bit pattern that happens to equal the load rd. The change is localized combinational decode in the hazard path and should have low correctness risk because it does not alter forwarding, memory ordering, retirement, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Decode IF/ID opcode usage bits and apply load-use stalls only when the following instruction consumes the matching source register in EX; keep stores and other true rs2 users conservative.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r3s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778622388629,"end":1778622388646}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_069a16b5f74d84cd016a039fb41a408197b8644ca637b092b7"}},"id":"prt_e1e27d7e7001RmCdeu1Leox3tI","sessionID":"ses_1e1d8d1e7ffeQvBTKnnVTdapD4","messageID":"msg_e1e27c6f100130BCfpJbiKBPtZ"}}
