{"type":"text","timestamp":1778623810580,"sessionID":"ses_1e1c2c615ffehafwE79XLz1cNv","part":{"id":"prt_e1e3d8a58001dwb5FSZhgJPGyh","messageID":"msg_e1e3d5ae9001dkDyoYcw11jY3B","sessionID":"ses_1e1c2c615ffehafwE79XLz1cNv","type":"text","text":"The prior micro-opt attempts focused on control/load-use bubbles, with one broken narrow stall-pruning attempt and the successful MEM-to-EX load forwarding already integrated. The remaining high-leverage micro-opt is in the ALU: the current EX path unconditionally builds three 64-bit products and combinational divide/remainder networks even though CoreMark mostly needs RV32I ALU plus occasional MUL, so reducing the always-on M-extension logic is likely to help Fmax without changing IPC semantics.","time":{"start":1778623810136,"end":1778623810579},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0679430d47c0cf49016a03a5420580819aa9a0ce0fb70f4f29","phase":"commentary"}}}}
