{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778627338284,"sessionID":"ses_1e18e19d3ffepbuaJ3c5iyfz0x","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Zluw4LzrJFHLnyq1VjK5vUCX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r7s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r7s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-001-r7s0\n2: title: \"Trim late pipeline metadata\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current best core already gained IPC from static direct-control prediction and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that touched IF prediction, the register file, RV32M sharing, or MEM lane muxing regressed. A lower-risk remaining angle is reducing late-stage register and routing pressure without changing cycle behavior.\n6: \n7:   EX/MEM and MEM/WB still carry full decoded control bundles plus branch metadata after EX has already consumed most of it. Those bits are not needed for memory, writeback, or RVFI, but they still widen packed pipeline buses and module boundaries unless synthesis can perfectly prune them through hierarchy.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Split the late pipeline metadata into compact stage-specific payloads. Keep the full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, then have EX/MEM carry only memory width/sign, memory enables, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal; have MEM/WB carry only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Remove EX/MEM branch_taken and branch_target fields because redirect and pc_next are already resolved in EX and no downstream stage consumes those fields.\n10: \n11:   This should slightly reduce FF count, LUT muxing, and inter-stage routing on the Tang Nano 20K without adding predictor state, altering the ALU, changing load forwarding, or touching the NRET=1 RVFI interface. CoreMark cycle count should be unchanged, so any gain comes from median Fmax and easier placement/routing.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n17:     description: \"Add compact late-stage control typedefs and remove unused EX/MEM branch_taken and branch_target payload fields while preserving RVFI-relevant metadata.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n19:     description: \"Pack only the control bits needed after EX into the EX/MEM register and stop writing unused branch outcome fields.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n21:     description: \"Consume the compact EX/MEM control bundle and emit only writeback/trap control needed by MEM/WB, with unchanged masks, load forwarding, and misalignment traps.\"\n22:   - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n23:     description: \"Use the compact MEM/WB control bundle for regfile write enable and write-data selection.\"\n24:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n25:     description: \"Update hazard, forwarding, WB, and RVFI references to the compact late-stage control fields without changing top-level ports.\"\n\n(End of file - total 25 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-001-r7s0\ntitle: \"Trim late pipeline metadata\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current best core already gained IPC from static direct-control prediction and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that touched IF prediction, the register file, RV32M sharing, or MEM lane muxing regressed. A lower-risk remaining angle is reducing late-stage register and routing pressure without changing cycle behavior.\n\n  EX/MEM and MEM/WB still carry full decoded control bundles plus branch metadata after EX has already consumed most of it. Those bits are not needed for memory, writeback, or RVFI, but they still widen packed pipeline buses and module boundaries unless synthesis can perfectly prune them through hierarchy.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split the late pipeline metadata into compact stage-specific payloads. Keep the full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, then have EX/MEM carry only memory width/sign, memory enables, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal; have MEM/WB carry only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Remove EX/MEM branch_taken and branch_target fields because redirect and pc_next are already resolved in EX and no downstream stage consumes those fields.\n\n  This should slightly reduce FF count, LUT muxing, and inter-stage routing on the Tang Nano 20K without adding predictor state, altering the ALU, changing load forwarding, or touching the NRET=1 RVFI interface. CoreMark cycle count should be unchanged, so any gain comes from median Fmax and easier placement/routing.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add compact late-stage control typedefs and remove unused EX/MEM branch_taken and branch_target payload fields while preserving RVFI-relevant metadata.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Pack only the control bits needed after EX into the EX/MEM register and stop writing unused branch outcome fields.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r7s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778627338280,"end":1778627338283}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_075d7b150bec5b73016a03b30a2d808195964849bb4d13b25b"}},"id":"prt_e1e736027001MqyrmmV0E53WLi","sessionID":"ses_1e18e19d3ffepbuaJ3c5iyfz0x","messageID":"msg_e1e7334b9002Si7qn1Cu75SHB8"}}
