{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778628366581,"sessionID":"ses_1e17dbcd5ffeK8bALaD2B72uHe","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_nh44S270whynyXSXcbmXuIj5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\n+title: \"Isolate M-extension ALU mux\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\n+  and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\n+  MEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\n+  the EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\n+  large result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\n+\n+  CoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\n+  the RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\n+  changing cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv into two local result cones: a compact RV32I result mux for\n+  ADD/SUB/logic/shift/SLT/LUI and a separate RV32M result mux that keeps the existing\n+  exact multiply/divide/remainder expressions unchanged. The final output should be\n+  selected by a simple is_m_op predicate, rather than muxing every RV32I and RV32M\n+  operation in one flat case statement.\n+\n+  This is intentionally not another attempt to share or redesign RV32M arithmetic,\n+  which previously hurt timing. The ALTOPS branch must keep the same substituted\n+  formulas, and the real branch must preserve all RV32M edge-case semantics. The\n+  expected benefit is a small Fmax gain from keeping the common RV32I/branch-address\n+  path out of the wide multiply/divide result selector, with no IPC cost and no\n+  change to RVFI, decode legality, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 top-level IO.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Split ALU result selection into separate RV32I and RV32M local muxes, then choose between them with an is_m_op predicate while preserving existing ALTOPS and real RV32M semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\n+title: \"Isolate M-extension ALU mux\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\n+  and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\n+  MEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\n+  the EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\n+  large result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\n+\n+  CoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\n+  the RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\n+  changing cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv into two local result cones: a compact RV32I result mux for\n+  ADD/SUB/logic/shift/SLT/LUI and a separate RV32M result mux that keeps the existing\n+  exact multiply/divide/remainder expressions unchanged. The final output should be\n+  selected by a simple is_m_op predicate, rather than muxing every RV32I and RV32M\n+  operation in one flat case statement.\n+\n+  This is intentionally not another attempt to share or redesign RV32M arithmetic,\n+  which previously hurt timing. The ALTOPS branch must keep the same substituted\n+  formulas, and the real branch must preserve all RV32M edge-case semantics. The\n+  expected benefit is a small Fmax gain from keeping the common RV32I/branch-address\n+  path out of the wide multiply/divide result selector, with no IPC cost and no\n+  change to RVFI, decode legality, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 top-level IO.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Split ALU result selection into separate RV32I and RV32M local muxes, then choose between them with an is_m_op predicate while preserving existing ALTOPS and real RV32M semantics.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\n+title: \"Isolate M-extension ALU mux\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\n+  and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\n+  MEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\n+  the EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\n+  large result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\n+\n+  CoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\n+  the RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\n+  changing cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv into two local result cones: a compact RV32I result mux for\n+  ADD/SUB/logic/shift/SLT/LUI and a separate RV32M result mux that keeps the existing\n+  exact multiply/divide/remainder expressions unchanged. The final output should be\n+  selected by a simple is_m_op predicate, rather than muxing every RV32I and RV32M\n+  operation in one flat case statement.\n+\n+  This is intentionally not another attempt to share or redesign RV32M arithmetic,\n+  which previously hurt timing. The ALTOPS branch must keep the same substituted\n+  formulas, and the real branch must preserve all RV32M edge-case semantics. The\n+  expected benefit is a small Fmax gain from keeping the common RV32I/branch-address\n+  path out of the wide multiply/divide result selector, with no IPC cost and no\n+  change to RVFI, decode legality, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 top-level IO.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Split ALU result selection into separate RV32I and RV32M local muxes, then choose between them with an is_m_op predicate while preserving existing ALTOPS and real RV32M semantics.\"\n","additions":32,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r8s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778628366578,"end":177862836