{"type":"text","timestamp":1778629402922,"sessionID":"ses_1e16dce29ffe8RVubYGcA3gjhb","part":{"id":"prt_e1e92ddf7001O6UybZhbYu7MEQ","messageID":"msg_e1e9296990025LDts9gud8Q4SL","sessionID":"ses_1e16dce29ffe8RVubYGcA3gjhb","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a single micro_opt hypothesis that extends the successful ALU-mux isolation lesson: keep RV32M untouched, but fast-path the common RV32I ADD/SUB/LUI result around the remaining RV32I case mux.","time":{"start":1778629402103,"end":1778629402921},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0946701cce92043d016a03bb19fdb88190aa1969d793e49eac","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778629415139,"sessionID":"ses_1e16dce29ffe8RVubYGcA3gjhb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_NIRo5pP35bMDHI1jGlVLrzMP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Fast-path simple ALU results\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\n+\n+  Prior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv to compute simple RV32I results in a small fast cone: ADD/ADDI/address-generation as a dedicated sum, SUB as a dedicated difference, and LUI as the direct immediate operand. Keep the existing non-simple RV32I mux for logic, shifts, and comparisons, and keep the RV32M mux and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions behaviorally unchanged. The final output should select simple RV32I results before falling through to the existing non-simple RV32I or RV32M result cones.\n+\n+  This should remove one layer of RV32I case-mux fan-in from the most common ALU operations without changing IPC, branch prediction, load forwarding, RVFI fields, or exact RV32IM arithmetic semantics. The expected gain is modest but plausible because CoreMark Fmax is now likely limited by hot EX-stage datapath routing rather than by the control additions that failed in earlier rounds.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated fast result cone for ADD, SUB, and LUI before the remaining RV32I/RV32M output mux, preserving all existing RV32M and ALTOPS behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Fast-path simple ALU results\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\n+\n+  Prior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv to compute simple RV32I results in a small fast cone: ADD/ADDI/address-generation as a dedicated sum, SUB as a dedicated difference, and LUI as the direct immediate operand. Keep the existing non-simple RV32I mux for logic, shifts, and comparisons, and keep the RV32M mux and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions behaviorally unchanged. The final output should select simple RV32I results before falling through to the existing non-simple RV32I or RV32M result cones.\n+\n+  This should remove one layer of RV32I case-mux fan-in from the most common ALU operations without changing IPC, branch prediction, load forwarding, RVFI fields, or exact RV32IM arithmetic semantics. The expected gain is modest but plausible because CoreMark Fmax is now likely limited by hot EX-stage datapath routing rather than by the control additions that failed in earlier rounds.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated fast result cone for ADD, SUB, and LUI before the remaining RV32I/RV32M output mux, preserving all existing RV32M and ALTOPS behavior.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r9s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Fast-path simple ALU results\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\n+\n+  Prior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv to compute simple RV32I results in a small fast cone: ADD/ADDI/address-generation as a dedicated sum, SUB as a dedicated difference, and LUI as the direct immediate operand. Keep the existing non-simple RV32I mux for logic, shifts, and comparisons, and keep the RV32M mux and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions behaviorally unchanged. The final output should select simple RV32I results before falling through to the existing non-simple RV32I or RV32M result cones.\n+\n+  This should remove one layer of RV32I case-mux fan-in from the most common ALU operations without changing IPC, branch prediction, load forwarding, RVFI fields, or exact RV32IM arithmetic semantics. The expected gain is modest but plausible because CoreMark Fmax is now likely limited by hot EX-stage datapath routing rather than by the control additions that failed in earlier rounds.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated fast result cone for ADD, SUB, and LUI before the remaining RV32I/RV32M output mux, preserving all existing RV32M and ALTOPS behavior.\"\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}],"diag