{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778631408932,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","part":{"id":"prt_e1eb17d2300174wtg1tE3DVKxW","messageID":"msg_e1eb1783d0018WV92Rze2W9osG","sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","snapshot":"3d1a5841c1551e6b829b1cd6523bc164052a80e2","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778631467329,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_SzXL70X0mrMWe8NtkggqxK3d","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":26,"limit":20},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Fast-path simple ALU results\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv to compute simple RV32I results in a small fast cone: ADD/ADDI/address-generation as a dedicated sum, SUB as a dedicated difference, and LUI as the direct immediate operand. Keep the existing non-simple RV32I mux for logic, shifts, and comparisons, and keep the RV32M mux and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions behaviorally unchanged. The final ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Register fetch decode boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nA minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nA minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single valid IF/ID pipeline register owned by if_stage, with explicit consume/hold behavior so an imem-not-ready cycle drains to one bubble instead of replaying the previous instruction. When decode is stalled by dmem backpressure, hold the IF/ID register and PC; when imem is ready and decode can advance, capture pc, instr, and pred_next_pc from the existing static predictor. Redirects flush the registered IF/ID payload and update PC exactly as today.\\n\\nThis turns the current pseudo five-stage pipe into a true fetch/decode split without adding multi-entry queue state, tag... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Gate static branch target formation\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor change with a large proven CoreMark gain is the current\\nstateless fetch rule: predict direct JAL taken and backward conditional\\nbranches taken. Later predictor attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, skid buffering, or extra target muxing all regressed from\\nIF-stage timing and control cost. The remaining predictor opportunity is\\ntherefore not a smarter predictor, but a cheaper implementation of the same\\nsuccessful policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor change with a large proven CoreMark gain is the current\\nstateless fetch rule: predict direct JAL taken and backward conditional\\nbranches taken. Later predictor attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, skid buffering, or extra target muxing all regressed from\\nIF-stage timing and control cost. The remaining predictor opportunity is\\ntherefore not a smarter predictor, but a cheaper implementation of the same\\nsuccessful policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the exact JAL-always-taken and backward-branch-taken behavior, but\\nrewrite the IF predictor so branch target formation is gated by the cheap\\nbranch-opcode and sign-bit predicate before the B-immediate shuffle and\\npc-plus-branch-target adder are used. Forward conditional branches should\\nfall through through the pc+4 path without driving the full branch-target\\ncone, while JAL keeps its existing direct target path.\\n\\nThis targets median FPGA Fmax with unchanged CoreMark IPC and avoids the\\nfailed pattern of adding predictor state or new redirect sources. Correctness\\nis unchanged because EX still compares the resolved next PC against the\\ncarried pred_next_pc and repairs every mismatch before retirement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refactor the existing static predictor... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Gate EX control target arithmetic\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from reducing unnecessary fetch-side branch target work and isolating the ALU's RV32M mux. The execute stage still unconditionally forms branch targets, JAL/JALR targets, pc+4, and branch comparison results even for ordinary ALU and load/store instructions that only need the ALU result and fall-through next PC.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot path is dominated by integer arithmetic, address generation, and loads/stores, so pruning duplicate control-flow arithmetic from the common EX cone may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax without changing cycle count, prediction policy, memory behavior, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from reducing unnecessary fetch-side branch target work and isolating the ALU's RV32M mux. The execute stage still unconditionally forms branch targets, JAL/JALR targets, pc+4, and branch comparison results even for ordinary ALU and load/store instructions that only need the ALU result and fall-through next PC.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot path is dominated by integer arithmetic, address generation, and loads/stores, so pruning duplicate control-flow arithmetic from the common EX cone may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax without changing cycle count, prediction policy, memory behavior, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv so control-flow next-PC work is explicitly factored and gated. Compute pc_plus4 once, share one pc_plus_imm target for both conditional branches and JAL, compute the JALR rs1+imm target only for JALR, and only evaluate the full branch comparator case when ctrl.is_branch is set. Non-control instructions should drive resolved_next_pc directly from pc_plus4 and avoid the branch/jump target mux tree.\\n\\nThis is intentionally a narrow timing cleanup, not a new predictor or early redirect. It preserves t... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Sidecar iterative divider\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU still contains full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators even though CoreMark's hot timed path is dominated by loads, stores,\\nbranches, integer ALU ops, and occasional multiply. Prior structural attempts\\nthat added front-end queues, store buffering, early JALR, or register-file\\nrestructuring regressed because they added control to hot paths. Removing the\\nrare divider/remainder cone from the single-cycle EX result path is a more\\nlocalized structural change with a direct chance to improve FPGA Fmax and LUT\\npressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU still contains full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators even though CoreMark's hot timed path is dominated by loads, stores,\\nbranches, integer ALU ops, and occasional multiply. Prior structural attempts\\nthat added front-end queues, store buffering, early JALR, or register-file\\nrestructuring regressed because they added control to hot paths. Removing the\\nrare divider/remainder cone from the single-cycle EX result path is a more\\nlocalized structural change with a direct chance to improve FPGA Fmax and LUT\\npressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M division and remainder out of the combinational ALU into a small\\niterative divide sidecar that is only activated for DIV, DIVU, REM, and REMU.\\nEX should hold ID/EX and suppress EX/MEM advancement while the sidecar is busy,\\nthen inject the completed quotient or remainder into the normal EX/MEM result\\npath with the original instruction metadata intact. ADD/SUB/logic/shift,\\naddress generation, branches, jumps, and MUL/MULH variants remain one-cycle,\\nand RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS keeps its one-cycle substituted behavior. This should\\nimprove median Tang Nano 20K Fmax more than it costs IPC because real divide\\nand remainder instructions are rare in the benchmark window.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_d... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Gate static JAL target formation\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor result is still the stateless direct-control rule:\\npredict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Later attempts to\\nadd predictor state, richer direction heuristics, indirect prediction, or\\nfetch buffering mostly regressed from added IF-path cost. The latest win came\\nfrom keeping the same policy while gating branch-target formation, which\\nsuggests the best remaining predictor angle is another fetch-path pruning\\nchange rather than smarter prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor result is still the stateless direct-control rule:\\npredict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Later attempts to\\nadd predictor state, richer direction heuristics, indirect prediction, or\\nfetch buffering mostly regressed from added IF-path cost. The latest win came\\nfrom keeping the same policy while gating branch-target formation, which\\nsuggests the best remaining predictor angle is another fetch-path pruning\\nchange rather than smarter prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the exact current prediction behavior, but gate JAL immediate shuffle and\\nJAL target addition behind the cheap JAL opcode predicate. Today the fetch\\npredictor still forms the J-immediate and pc-plus-JAL target for every fetched\\ninstruction even though only opcode 1101111 can select that path. Non-JAL\\ninstructions should use the existing pc+4 or gated backward-branch path\\nwithout driving the JAL target cone.\\n\\nThis should improve median FPGA Fmax with no CoreMark IPC change, preserve the\\nsuccessful static predictor, and avoid the failed pattern of adding BHT/RAS/\\nloop/JALR state. EX still compares resolved_next_pc against the carried\\npred_next_pc, so architectural correction, RVFI pc_wdata, and NRET=1\\nretirement behavior are unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"cha... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 31 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Fast-path simple ALU results\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\