{"type":"text","timestamp":1778631482176,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","part":{"id":"prt_e1eb2972b001qpjDTkvk4VQmiG","messageID":"msg_e1eb261a00012cP9Ge64IN3HuQ","sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a structural hypothesis that avoids the failed broad FIFO/store-buffer pattern: a one-entry EX result skid that uses otherwise dead cycles while an older memory op is waiting, but only for non-memory/non-control instructions and only with in-order retirement.","time":{"start":1778631481131,"end":1778631482176},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0c01e692533706e4016a03c33907848198ab49fa3b9911c6c4","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778631494942,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_2wz52nlOyrjOIWVh6S3nLQxT","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\n+title: \"Skid one ALU op behind dmem stalls\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry execute skid register for safe younger instructions while EX/MEM is holding an older stalled memory operation. When dmem_stall is asserted and ID/EX holds a valid non-memory, non-branch, non-jump instruction that does not depend on the stalled load's rd, EX computes it once and captures the full ex_mem_t result into the skid entry. The front end and ID/EX then remain held until the older memory operation completes; after the memory instruction retires, the skid entry drains into the normal EX/MEM to MEM/WB path before any newly decoded instruction advances.\n+\n+  This is intentionally not a general store buffer, fetch FIFO, or out-of-order engine. It only hides one cycle of memory backpressure for independent straight-line ALU/LUI/AUIPC/MUL-class work, preserves strict in-order RVFI retirement by draining after the older memory op, and leaves loads, stores, branches, jumps, and load-dependent consumers on the existing conservative path. CoreMark has many pointer and loop instructions interleaved with memory traffic, so recovering even one cycle from a fraction of randomized dmem stalls should improve iterations/cycle with less hot-path cost than prior structural buffering attempts.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Reuse ex_mem_t as the skid payload and, if needed, add a small packed control record for skid valid/blocked state without changing top-level IO.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a skiddable EX result path for valid non-memory, non-control instructions during an EX/MEM dmem hold, while keeping normal EX/MEM behavior unchanged when no skid is taken.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add control for capture-on-dmem-stall, skid-full backpressure, and skid-drain priority so the captured instruction is not duplicated and IF/ID remains ordered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the skid valid/payload between EX, hazard control, and MEM so the older memory operation retires first and the skidded instruction drains through channel 0 afterward.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\n+title: \"Skid one ALU op behind dmem stalls\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry execute skid register for safe younger instructions while EX/MEM is holding an older stalled memory operation. When dmem_stall is asserted and ID/EX holds a valid non-memory, non-branch, non-jump instruction that does not depend on the stalled load's rd, EX computes it once and captures the full ex_mem_t result into the skid entry. The front end and ID/EX then remain held until the older memory operation completes; after the memory instruction retires, the skid entry drains into the normal EX/MEM to MEM/WB path before any newly decoded instruction advances.\n+\n+  This is intentionally not a general store buffer, fetch FIFO, or out-of-order engine. It only hides one cycle of memory backpressure for independent straight-line ALU/LUI/AUIPC/MUL-class work, preserves strict in-order RVFI retirement by draining after the older memory op, and leaves loads, stores, branches, jumps, and load-dependent consumers on the existing conservative path. CoreMark has many pointer and loop instructions interleaved with memory traffic, so recovering even one cycle from a fraction of randomized dmem stalls should improve iterations/cycle with less hot-path cost than prior structural buffering attempts.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Reuse ex_mem_t as the skid payload and, if needed, add a small packed control record for skid valid/blocked state without changing top-level IO.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a skiddable EX result path for valid non-memory, non-control instructions during an EX/MEM dmem hold, while keeping normal EX/MEM behavior unchanged when no skid is taken.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add control for capture-on-dmem-stall, skid-full backpressure, and skid-drain priority so the captured instruction is not duplicated and IF/ID remains ordered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the skid valid/payload between EX, hazard control, and MEM so the older memory operation retires first and the skidded instruction drains through channel 0 afterward.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\n+title: \"Skid one ALU op behind dmem stalls\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry execute skid register for safe younger instructions while EX/MEM is holding an older stalled memory operation. When dmem_stall is asserted and ID/EX holds a valid non-memory, non-branch, non-jump instruction that does not depend on the stalled load's rd, EX computes it once and captures the full ex_mem_t result into the skid entry. The front end and ID/EX then remain held until the older memory operation completes; after the memory instruction retires, the skid entry drains into the normal EX/MEM to MEM/WB path before any newly decoded instruction advances.\n+\n+  This is intentionally not a general store buffer, fetch FIFO, or out-of-order engine. It only hides one cycle of memory backpressure for independent straight-line ALU/LUI/AUIPC/MUL-class work, preserves strict in-order RVFI retirement by draining after the older memory op, and leaves loads, stores, branches, jumps, and load-dependent consumers on the existing conservative path. CoreMark has many pointer and loop instructions interleaved with memory traffic, so recovering even one cycle from a fraction of randomized dmem stalls should improve iterations/cycle with less hot-path cost than prior structural buffering attempts.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Reuse ex_mem_t as the skid payload and, if needed, add a small packed control record for skid valid/blocked state without changing top-level IO.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a skiddable EX result path for valid non-memory, non-control instructions during an EX/MEM dmem hold, while keeping normal EX/MEM behavior unchanged when no skid is taken.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add control for capture-on-dmem-stall, skid-full backpressure, and skid-drain priority so the captured instruction is not duplicated and IF/ID remains ordered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the skid valid/payload between EX, hazard control, and MEM so the older memory operation retires first and the skidded instruction drains through channel 0 afterward.\"\n","additions":21,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r11s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778631494935,"end":1778631494940}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c01e692533706e4016a03c33a0c30819897669afccb6d31a3"}},"id":"prt_e1eb29b40002Gd7kV4dbGxIxzH","sessionID":"ses_1e14ed357ffeA57MiySdQujFwm","messageID":"msg_e1eb261a00012cP9Ge64IN3HuQ"}}
