{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778634166053,"sessionID":"ses_1e1249795ffeRbMy3U6KW9KAfw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_sDWvhYkDbVbmrRTj4prVyTBA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +4.17%): Decode-to-IF JAL fast paths can lose more to added imem/decode/PC-mux timing than they save in bubbles, so direct jumps are better handled by a lightweight fetch predictor or kept off the critical PC path.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (regression, +3.34%): A sequential IF FIFO that only buffers pc+4 fetches did not hide enough randomized imem/dmem backpressure to pay for its extra queue/control state, so front-end decoupling needs redirect-aware prefetch value beyond isolated stall absorption.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (improvement, +19.74%): Static fetch prediction for JAL and backward BRANCH targets pays on CoreMark's tight counted loops because carrying pred_next_pc to EX removes taken-back-edge redirect bubbles without BTB state or broadening the critical path much.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-to-store stalls can only be pruned if the MEM-stage store-data bypass also updates RVFI rs2 source metadata; fixing dmem_wdata alone leaves stale ID-read operands that riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -10.26%): A one-entry store buffer that still stalls all younger loads/stores behind sb_valid adds dmem mux/control cost without enough CoreMark memory-level parallelism to offset it; store decoupling needs forwarding or deeper disambiguation to pay.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -1.79%): A tiny non-speculative RAS for canonical JALR returns adds IF-stage stack/index/PC-mux control that CoreMark's remaining call-return bubbles do not repay, so indirect-return prediction needs very low fetch-path cost to be worthwhile.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (broken, n/a): Source-aware load-use pruning should gate only hazard comparisons unless the cosim/RVFI contract is updated too; zeroing unused rs1/rs2 metadata for JAL/LUI/AUIPC-style instructions breaks the bench ISS trace, which reports raw instruction register fields.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (improvement, +4.90%): MEM-stage extended load forwarding pays on CoreMark's pointer-heavy load-use chains when dmemReady qualifies the bypass and branch/JALR redirects wait for ready forwarded operands, removing interlock bubbles without weakening RVFI source tracking.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -9.20%): A 16-entry tagged 2-bit BHT in IF adds enough counter/tag read and update state to outweigh the few CoreMark misses left after JAL plus backward-branch static prediction, so dynamic direction needs a cheaper fetch-path integration or stronger bias target.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -11.19%): Sharing RV32M work inside the combinational ALU can hurt synthesis timing more than it saves area; a single 33x33 signed multiplier plus centralized div/rem datapath is a wider rare-op cone than simple per-op expressions.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -9.78%): Refining the static backward-branch predictor by funct3 hurt CoreMark, suggesting backward BEQ and other simple back-edge cases are common enough that the coarse all-backward-taken rule beats extra direction bias logic in IF.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -11.92%): Removing the small reg-file reset loop and x0 storage did not pay on Tang Nano 20K; the reset fanout was not the limiting path, and the irregular 31-entry array can cost more synthesis/routing quality than it saves.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -9.62%): Forcing the reg file toward resetless LUTRAM with scrub/init-mask logic added read-side masking and pipeline holdoff control that outweighed reset-fanout savings, so RF area optimizations must stay off the ID read critical path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -5.56%): Even an exact one-entry JALR target memo regressed after static JAL/backward-BRANCH prediction; its IF-stage opcode/funct3/PC compare and target mux cost outweighed CoreMark's remaining repeated-indirect bubbles.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (regression, -10.61%): Replacing MEM load shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] lane cases can duplicate mux/decode cones on the load-forwarding path; FPGA synthesis already handled the compact variable-shift form better here.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -13.31%): Exact ID-stage JALR redirects still put rs1 dependency compares, target add/alignment, and an early PC mux on decode/fetch timing, so ready-indirect bubble recovery must be nearly free to beat the current EX redirect path.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -11.99%): A one-entry loop-exit predictor still adds IF-stage PC/count compares and predictor update state, and CoreMark's final counted-loop exit misses are too sparse to repay that cost after the static JAL/backward-BRANCH rule.\n18: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (regression, -12.38%): Manually splitting late ctrl_t into compact EX/MEM and MEM/WB payloads can hurt more than help when synthesis already prunes unused branch/decode bits, because the added control repacking and trap muxing create new late-stage cones.\n19: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.45%): Making MEM-to-EX load bypass word-only saved subword lane logic but added width-dependent interlock and branch-wait control that cost more, so CoreMark's load-use path favors one simple ready-qualified forwarding scheme over selective bypass pruning.\n20: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -11.22%): Sharing the static predictor target adder by muxing a 32-bit JAL/BRANCH offset before pc+offset can lengthen the IF critical path more than parallel target adds, so PC-path arithmetic sharing is not automatically cheaper.\n21: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r8s0 (improvement, +3.03%): Splitting the ALU into a compact RV32I result cone plus a separate RV32M mux improves CoreMark timing because hot ADD/SUB/compare/address ops avoid the wide multiply/divide/remainder selector without changing IPC.\n22: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r8s1 (regression, -7.51%): Even predictor-aware two-entry IF skid buffering adds fetch-PC, queue-count, and enqueue/dequeue control cost that CoreMark's randomized bus stalls did not repay after static JAL/backward-branch prediction.\n23: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r8s2 (regression, -2.05%): Compressing static predictor metadata from pred_next_pc to a direction bit did not pay, implying the IF/ID register width and EX next-PC comparator were not the limiting cost compared with the remaining redirect/control logic.\n24: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r9s0 (regression, -2.90%): Further splitting ADD/SUB/LUI into a separate simple-ALU priority path can add op-decode and final-result mux control that outweighs any reduction in the already-isolated RV32I case mux.\n25: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r9s1 (regression, +5.10%): A single registered IF/ID boundary with imem-ready drain control still regressed, so the imem-to-decode cone is not the current limiter and CoreMark favors the existing zero-latency fetch/decode handoff over extra redirect/fill latency.\n26: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r9s2 (improvement, +14.85%): Gating B-immediate formation with branch opcode plus sign bit keeps the successful static JAL/backward-BRANCH policy while letting forward branches use pc+4 without driving the full branch-target cone, so predictor wins here come from fetch-path pruning rather than added state.\n27: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r10s0 (regression, -48.12%): Gating EX-stage branch/JAL/JALR target arithmetic behind is_branch/is_jump muxes can add more control and selector depth than unconditional parallel pc+imm, rs1+imm, and comparator cones, so late control-flow arithmetic is best kept simple unless timing reports prove it is critical.\n28: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r10s1 (regression, -13.71%): Moving DIV/REM into an iterative EX sidecar can cost more than the divider cone it removes because start/busy/done, EX/MEM bubble injection, and ID/EX hold control sit on common pipeline timing while CoreMark rarely executes divides.\n29: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r10s2 (regression, -12.64%): Gating IF-stage JAL immediate/target formation adds opcode-controlled muxing that can cost more than the unconditional J-immediate adder, so fetch pruning must be validated per target cone rather than extrapolated from the B-immediate win.\n30: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r11s0 (regression, -1.85%): Recoding ALU op values so `op[4]` directly selects RV32M can still regress timing; a removed local case decode may be cheaper than adding a high-fanout semantic bit to the final ALU mux select.\n31: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r11s1 (regression, -13.91%): A one-entry EX skid slot behind stalled dmem ops adds skiddability dependency checks plus capture/drain muxing on common hazard and EX/MEM paths, and CoreMark's in-order drain opportunity is too small to offset that control cost.\n32: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r11s2 (regression, -22.68%): Gating the EX redirect mismatch compare behind `can_redirect` adds late decoded/opcode control on the repair path that costs more than the unconditional `resolved_next_pc != pred_next_pc` compare.\n33: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r12s0 (improvement, +4.12%): Factoring EX/MEM and MEM/WB producer register matches once in the forward unit can improve Fmax because duplicated rd/rs comparators and priority qualifiers sit directly on the hot EX operand mux select path.\n34: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r12s1 (regression, +0.19%): Registering MEM/WB rd_wdata instead of selecting the WB mux late was effectively neutral, implying the load-vs-ALU writeback mux fanout is not a current timing limiter compared with forwarding select/control cones.\n35: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r13s0 (regression, -11.80%): Removing already-unused hazard_unit load-use ports did not reduce real timing pressure; synthesis had effectively pruned that dead fanout, so pure hierarchy/port cleanup can perturb FPGA QoR unless timing reports show the boundary is limiting.\n36: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r13s1 (regression, -31.12%): Predecoding EX forwarding selects in ID can backfire because dmem stalls and changing producer validity require fallback/valid repair logic on the operand mux path, making dynamic forwarding cheaper to resolve late than to carry stale hints.\n37: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r13s2 (regression, -7.62%): Rewriting the IF predictor as fallthrough-default procedural priority did not remove any target adders or select conditions, so Yosys/nextpnr can still map a costly PC mux and even regress QoR from syntax-only predictor cleanup.\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (regression, +4.17%): Decode-to-IF JAL fast paths can lose more to added imem/decode/PC-mux timing than they save in bubbles, so direct jumps are better handled by a lightweight fetch predictor or kept off the critical PC path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (regression, +3.34%): A sequential IF FIFO that only buffers pc+4 fetches did not hide enough randomized imem/dmem backpressure to pay for its extra queue/control state, so front-end decoupling needs redirect-aware prefetch value beyond isolated stall absorption.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (improvement, +19.74%): Static fetch prediction for JAL and backward BRANCH targets pays on CoreMark's tight counted loops because carrying pred_next_pc to EX removes taken-back-edge redirect bubbles without BTB state or broadening the critical path much.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-to-store stalls can only be pruned if the MEM-stage store-data bypass also updates RVFI rs2 source metadata; fixing dmem_wdata alone leaves stale ID-read operands that riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -10.26%): A one-entry store buffer that still stalls all younger loads/stores behind sb_valid adds dmem mux/control cost without enough CoreMark memory-level parallelism to offset it; store decoupling needs forwarding or deeper disambiguation to pay.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -1.79%): A tiny non-speculative RAS for canonical JALR returns adds IF-stage stack/index/PC-mux control that CoreMark's remaining call-return bubbles do not repay, so indirect-return prediction needs very low fetch-path cost to be worthwhile.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (broken, n/a): Source-aware load-use pruning should gate only hazard comparisons unless the cosim/RVFI contract is updated too; zeroing unused rs1/rs2 metadata for JAL/LUI/AUIPC-style instructions breaks the bench ISS trace, which reports raw instruction register fields.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (improvement, +4.90%): MEM-stage extended load forwarding pays on CoreMark's pointer-heavy load-use chains when dmemReady qualifies the bypass and branch/JALR redirects wait for ready forwarded operands, removing interlock bubbles without weakening RVFI source tracking.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -9.20%): A 16-entry tagged 2-bit BHT in IF adds enough counter/tag read and update state to outweigh the few CoreMark misses left after JAL plus backward-branch static prediction, so dynamic direction needs a cheaper fetch-path integration or stronger bias target.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -11.19%): Sharing RV32M work inside the combinational ALU can hurt synthesis timing more than it saves area; a single 33x33 signed multiplier plus centralized div/rem datapath is a wider rare-op cone than simple per-op expressions.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -9.78%): Refining the static backward-branch predictor by funct3 hurt CoreMark, suggesting backward BEQ and other simple back-edge cases are common enough that the coarse all-backward-taken rule beats extra direction bias logic in IF.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -11.92%): Removing the small reg-file reset loop and x0 storage did not pay on Tang Nano 20K; the reset fanout was not the limiting path, and the irregular 31-entry array can cost more synthesis/routing quality than it saves.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -9.62%): Forcing the reg file toward resetless LUTRAM with scrub/init-mask logic added read-side masking and pipeline holdoff control that outweighed reset-fanout savings, so RF area optimizations must stay off the ID read critical path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -5.56%): Even an exact one-entry JALR target memo regressed after static JAL/backward-BRANCH prediction; its IF-stage opcode/funct3/PC compare and target mux cost outweighed CoreMark's remaining repeated-indirect bubbles.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (regression, -10.61%): Replacing MEM load shifts and shifted byte masks with explicit addr[1:0] lane cases can duplicate mux/decode cones on the load-forwarding path; FPGA synthesis already handled the compact variable-shift form better here.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -13.31%): Exact ID-stage JALR redirects still put rs1 dependency compares, target add/alignment, and an early PC mux on decode/fetch timing, so ready-indirect bubble recovery must be nearly free to beat the current EX redirect path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -11.99%): A one-entry loop-exit predictor still adds IF-stage PC/count compares and predictor update state, and CoreMark's final counted-loop exit misses are too sparse to repay that cost after the static JAL/backward-BRANCH rule.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (regression, -12.38%): Manually splitting late ctrl_t into compact EX/MEM and MEM/WB payloads can hurt more than help when synthesis already prunes unused branch/decode bits, because the added control repacking and trap muxing create new late-stage cones.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.45%): Making MEM-to-EX load bypass word-only saved subword lane logic but added width-dependent interlock and branch-wait control that cost more, so CoreMark's load-use path favors one simple ready-qualified forwarding scheme over selective bypass pruning.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -11.22%): Sharing the static predictor target adder by muxing a 32-bit JAL/BRANCH offset before pc+offset can lengthen the IF critical path more than parallel target adds, so PC-path arithmetic sharing is not automatically cheaper.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778634166046,"end":1778634166052}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b073678932b569d016a03cdb5e598819b9450be2aee7e52b0"}},"id":"prt_e1edb8ef7001D22ZE0pl396rbX","sessionID":"ses_1e1249795ffeRbMy3U6KW9KAfw","messageID":"msg_e1edb68af00152Gv6nETuf2Z41"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778634166077,"sessionID":"ses_1e1249795ffeRbMy3U6KW9KAfw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_f7bYRsUPfXo1xSO7zfURUIH8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: structural|structural|pipeline|stage|skid|IF/ID|EX/MEM|MEM/WB|forward|hazard|retire|register|fifo|buffer","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 39 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Resolve JAL one stage earlier\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark contains frequent unconditional calls and loop-control jumps. The current\\npipeline treats JAL like every other control transfer and redirects from EX, so each\\ntaken JAL pays the same two wrong-path bubbles as a conditional branch even though\\nits target is fully known from the instruction bits in decode.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark contains frequent unconditional calls and loop-control jumps. The current\\npipeline treats JAL like every other control transfer and redirects from EX, so each\\ntaken JAL pays the same two wrong-path bubbles as a conditional branch even though\\nits target is fully known from the instruction bits in decode.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a decode/IF fast path for legal JAL instructions: compute the J-immediate target\\nfrom the IF/ID instruction and redirect the PC before the instruction reaches EX,\\nwhile preserving the normal EX-stage JAL result and RVFI pc_wdata bookkeeping for\\nretirement. JALR and conditional branches remain EX-resolved because they require\\nregister operands or comparison results. This should reduce CoreMark cycles by\\nremoving one redirect bubble from unconditional direct jumps with minimal timing cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire an early JAL redirect path from decode/IF into instruction fetch and hazard flushing without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Let fetch accept an early redirect target for legal JAL so the PC updates before the existing EX-stage redirect point.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose a simple legal-JAL indication and decoded J-immediate target, reusing existing decoder and immediate generation logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Flush the fall-through instruction on early JAL r...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Add decoupled sequential fetch queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is evaluated with roughly 22% randomized instruction and data bus backpressure. The current front end is fully coupled to the pipeline: any imem miss-ready cycle injects a bubble, and dmem stalls prevent useful sequential fetching. A small in-order fetch queue can bank instructions during cycles when the back end is blocked and then drain through short imem-ready gaps, improving iterations per cycle without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is evaluated with roughly 22% randomized instruction and data bus backpressure. The current front end is fully coupled to the pipeline: any imem miss-ready cycle injects a bubble, and dmem stalls prevent useful sequential fetching. A small in-order fetch queue can bank instructions during cycles when the back end is blocked and then drain through short imem-ready gaps, improving iterations per cycle without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two- or four-entry sequential fetch FIFO owned by if_stage. The fetch side should keep issuing pc+4 requests into free FIFO slots whenever there is no redirect and imem_ready is high, while the decode side consumes one queued instruction whenever ID is not stalled. Redirects flush the FIFO and restart fetching at the redirect target, preserving precise pc_rdata/pc_wdata and single-channel RVFI order. This is a structural decoupling change: it should hide many isolated imem stalls and allow useful front-end work during dmem/load-use holds, at modest LUT/FF cost and with limited Fmax risk because the existing decode/execute datapath is not lengthened.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Turn the IF output into a small valid/pc/instruction FIFO with redi...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core fetches sequentially until EX resolves every taken\\nbranch or jump, so tight CoreMark loops pay a two-stage redirect bubble on\\neach taken back-edge. CoreMark has many small counted loops where a simple\\nstatic backward-taken, forward-not-taken predictor should remove most loop\\nback-edge redirects while keeping LUT and Fmax cost low.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core fetches sequentially until EX resolves every taken\\nbranch or jump, so tight CoreMark loops pay a two-stage redirect bubble on\\neach taken back-edge. CoreMark has many small counted loops where a simple\\nstatic backward-taken, forward-not-taken predictor should remove most loop\\nback-edge redirects while keeping LUT and Fmax cost low.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a lightweight fetch-side static predictor that decodes imem_data enough to\\ncompute immediate targets for direct JAL and conditional BRANCH instructions.\\nPredict JAL taken unconditionally, predict conditional branches taken only\\nwhen their B-immediate is negative, and carry the predicted next PC through the\\npipeline. In EX, compare the resolved next PC against the predicted next PC\\nand redirect only on mismatch. This should reduce CoreMark cycles by avoiding\\nflushes on hot loop back-edges without adding a BTB or saturating counters on\\nthe critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 7, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM bundles so retirement RVFI pc_wdata still reports the resolved architectural next PC.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode direct branch and JAL immediates in fetch, choose the static predicted next PC, and expose prediction metadata while preserving reset, stall, and flush behavior.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"descript...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Prune false load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard check compares a load destination against both\\nIF/ID register fields for every following instruction. That is conservative:\\nI-type, load, JALR, U-type, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not consume the rs2\\nfield in EX, and store rs2 is store data that can be supplied later in MEM.\\nCoreMark has many immediate operations and memory copies, so these false or\\navoidable bubbles directly reduce iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard check compares a load destination against both\\nIF/ID register fields for every following instruction. That is conservative:\\nI-type, load, JALR, U-type, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK do not consume the rs2\\nfield in EX, and store rs2 is store data that can be supplied later in MEM.\\nCoreMark has many immediate operations and memory copies, so these false or\\navoidable bubbles directly reduce iterations per cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make the load-use interlock source-aware. Only stall when the following\\ninstruction actually needs the loaded register in EX: rs1 for address/JALR/ALU\\noperations and both operands for R-type or branch compares. For store data\\ndependencies, allow the store to enter EX without a bubble and add a MEM-stage\\nbypass from the current WB value to the store write-data path. This preserves\\nprecise RVFI retirement and memory masks while removing bubbles that do not\\nprotect any real EX-stage operand.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode IF/ID source usage for the load-use interlock so rs2 is ignored for opcodes that do not need it in EX, and store-data dependencies no longer force a bubble.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a WB-to-store-data bypass used when a store reaches MEM immediately behind a load or other producer of its rs...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Add one-entry store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is evaluated with randomized dmem backpressure, and the current pipeline\\nfreezes all stages whenever a store in MEM sees io_dmemReady=0. Stores do not\\nproduce a register result, so blocking fetch, decode, and execute behind every\\ndelayed store wastes cycles that could otherwise retire independent ALU and\\ncontrol-flow work. The prior structural fetch FIFO did not help enough because\\nit buffered only fall-through front-end work; this targets the back-end stall\\nsource directly.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is evaluated with randomized dmem backpressure, and the current pipeline\\nfreezes all stages whenever a store in MEM sees io_dmemReady=0. Stores do not\\nproduce a register result, so blocking fetch, decode, and execute behind every\\ndelayed store wastes cycles that could otherwise retire independent ALU and\\ncontrol-flow work. The prior structural fetch FIFO did not help enough because\\nit buffered only fall-through front-end work; this targets the back-end stall\\nsource directly.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry store buffer between MEM and the external dmem write port.\\nA non-MMIO store can retire into the buffer when the bus is not ready, allowing\\nyounger non-memory instructions to continue while the buffer drains in the\\nbackground. Loads and subsequent stores should stall while the buffer is valid\\nunless the implementation adds exact same-address forwarding; MMIO marker and\\nUART stores should keep the existing blocking behavior so CoreMark timing and\\noutput ordering remain exact. This should recover cycles from randomized store\\nstalls with modest control and register cost, while preserving single-channel\\nRVFI order by retiring each store only after it is captured in the ordered\\nbuffer.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Predict JALR returns with tiny RAS\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current fetch predictor already handles direct JAL targets and backward\\nconditional loop branches, but every JALR return is still predicted as fall-through\\nuntil EX resolves the target from rs1. CoreMark still has call/return structure even\\nunder -O3, so return mispredict bubbles are a likely remaining control-flow cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current fetch predictor already handles direct JAL targets and backward\\nconditional loop branches, but every JALR return is still predicted as fall-through\\nuntil EX resolves the target from rs1. CoreMark still has call/return structure even\\nunder -O3, so return mispredict bubbles are a likely remaining control-flow cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a very small return-address stack predictor for call/return JALR patterns. Keep\\nthe existing static direct-control predictor unchanged, but predict canonical returns\\nin IF from the RAS top and carry that predicted next PC through the existing\\npred_next_pc path. Update the RAS non-speculatively from EX: push pc+4 for resolved\\ndirect calls that write x1/x5, and pop for resolved canonical returns. This targets\\nindirect return bubbles without adding a BTB, tags, or a broad decode-to-PC critical\\npath, and any stale RAS prediction is corrected by the existing EX redirect compare.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a small return-address stack and use its top to predict canonical JALR returns while preserving the existing JAL/backward-branch predictor.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose non-speculative call/return update events from resolved JAL/JALR instructions so the RAS can be repaired by architectural control-flow outcomes.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire EX-stage RAS update signals into IF without changing the ...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Prune safe false rs2 load stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark has many immediate, load, jump, upper-immediate, fence, and system instructions whose instr[24:20] bits are not an EX-stage rs2 operand. The current load-use interlock still compares a load destination against that field and inserts a bubble on accidental matches, directly reducing iterations per cycle under the same single-retire pipeline.\\n\\nThe earlier broader load-use pruning attempt failed because it let stores pass load-data dependencies without keeping RVFI source metadata coherent. A narrower source-aware interlock can keep all store, branch, and R-type rs2 dependencies conservative while removing only false rs2 stalls that are architecturally irrelevant.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark has many immediate, load, jump, upper-immediate, fence, and system instructions whose instr[24:20] bits are not an EX-stage rs2 operand. The current load-use interlock still compares a load destination against that field and inserts a bubble on accidental matches, directly reducing iterations per cycle under the same single-retire pipeline.\\n\\nThe earlier broader load-use pruning attempt failed because it let stores pass load-data dependencies without keeping RVFI source metadata coherent. A narrower source-aware interlock can keep all store, branch, and R-type rs2 dependencies conservative while removing only false rs2 stalls that are architecturally irrelevant.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Teach the hazard unit which IF/ID instructions actually consume rs1 and rs2 in EX, and gate the load-use comparison with those source-use bits. Keep rs1 dependencies unchanged for address, JALR, branch, and ALU operands, and keep rs2 dependencies for R-type ALU, branches, and stores so no new MEM-stage bypass or RVFI source-data repair is required.\\n\\nThis should recover occasional bubbles after loads when the following instruction is an I-type arithmetic op, load...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Add MEM-to-EX load forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still pays a full interlock bubble whenever an\\ninstruction immediately consumes a preceding load. CoreMark's pointer-heavy list,\\nmatrix, and state kernels create many load-use pairs, and the existing zero-wait\\nmemory model makes the loaded word available in MEM soon enough to be forwarded\\ninto the dependent instruction's EX operand path. Prior structural attempts added\\nqueues or buffers with broad control cost; this targets a specific pipeline\\nboundary that directly removes retirement bubbles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still pays a full interlock bubble whenever an\\ninstruction immediately consumes a preceding load. CoreMark's pointer-heavy list,\\nmatrix, and state kernels create many load-use pairs, and the existing zero-wait\\nmemory model makes the loaded word available in MEM soon enough to be forwarded\\ninto the dependent instruction's EX operand path. Prior structural attempts added\\nqueues or buffers with broad control cost; this targets a specific pipeline\\nboundary that directly removes retirement bubbles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-stage load-result forwarding path into EX and make the forwarding unit\\ntreat an EX/MEM load as a valid producer once dmem data is ready. The EX-stage\\noperand muxes should use the sign/zero-extended load data for rs1 and rs2, and\\nthe post-forward operand values must continue to be latched into EX/MEM so RVFI\\nrs1/rs2 metadata matches the architectural source values. With that bypass in\\nplace, the load-use interlock can stop stalling ordinary dependent ALU, branch,\\naddress, and store-data consumers; dmem stalls still freeze the pipeline until\\nthe forwarded load result is valid, and redirect generation must not use an\\nunready forwarded load operand. This should improve CoreMark IPC without adding\\npredictor state, store ordering machi...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny dynamic branch direction predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current fetch predictor already removes most taken-back-edge bubbles by\\npredicting JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. The remaining\\nconditional branch cost is likely from forward branches that are frequently\\ntaken and from backward loop exits, both of which a static sign-of-offset rule\\ncannot adapt to. A very small dynamic direction table can target those misses\\nwhile preserving the existing direct target computation and RVFI next-PC flow.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current fetch predictor already removes most taken-back-edge bubbles by\\npredicting JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. The remaining\\nconditional branch cost is likely from forward branches that are frequently\\ntaken and from backward loop exits, both of which a static sign-of-offset rule\\ncannot adapt to. A very small dynamic direction table can target those misses\\nwhile preserving the existing direct target computation and RVFI next-PC flow.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a compact direct-mapped conditional-branch direction predictor in IF: 16\\nentries, 2-bit saturating counters, optional short tags/valid bits, indexed by\\nfetch PC. Conditional branches use the table's taken bit on a tag hit and fall\\nback to the current backward-taken static rule on a miss; JAL prediction stays\\nunchanged. EX updates the table non-speculatively from resolved branch outcome\\nusing the branch PC already carried in ID/EX, and the existing resolved-next-PC\\nversus pred_next_pc compare repairs any bad prediction. This should recover\\nmispredict bubbles on CoreMark's biased forward branches and one-time loop\\nexits without adding a BTB, RAS, or decode-stage redirect path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a tiny conditional-branch BHT that overrides the static ...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Share RV32M ALU arithmetic resources\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The successful recent change already removed many load-use bubbles, while\\nprior front-end and predictor additions regressed from extra control and fetch\\npath cost. The remaining low-risk fitness opportunity is Fmax/LUT pressure in\\nthe EX-stage ALU: the current combinational ALU unconditionally forms three\\n64-bit products and leaves separate divide/remainder expressions in the result\\nmux even though most CoreMark instructions use the simple RV32I fast path and\\nonly occasional MUL-class operations.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful recent change already removed many load-use bubbles, while\\nprior front-end and predictor additions regressed from extra control and fetch\\npath cost. The remaining low-risk fitness opportunity is Fmax/LUT pressure in\\nthe EX-stage ALU: the current combinational ALU unconditionally forms three\\n64-bit products and leaves separate divide/remainder expressions in the result\\nmux even though most CoreMark instructions use the simple RV32I fast path and\\nonly occasional MUL-class operations.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rework rtl/alu.sv so the RV32I fast ALU path is unchanged, but RV32M arithmetic\\nis resource-shared. Use a single sign-controlled extended multiplier that\\ncovers MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU instead of computing signed*signed,\\nunsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned products in parallel. Similarly factor\\nDIV/DIVU/REM/REMU operand preparation and special-case handling so quotient\\nand remainder selection is centralized rather than replicated per case arm.\\n\\nThis should reduce LUT use and the M-extension fan-in around the ALU output\\nmux, improving median FPGA Fmax with essentially unchanged CoreMark cycle\\ncount. The ALTOPS formal branch must remain byte-for-byte equivalent in\\nbehavior, and the existing cocotb ALU vectors plus cosim should guard exact\\nRV32M arithmetic semantics.\\n\", \"expected_im...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Move DIV/REM off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU contains fully combinational RV32M division and\\nremainder operators. Even when CoreMark rarely executes DIV/REM inside the\\ntimed region, synthesis must still route those large operators through the\\nALU result mux, which is a plausible Fmax and LUT bottleneck on the Tang Nano\\n20K. Prior structural wins came from targeted pipeline-boundary changes, not\\nbroad queues or buffering, so the best next structural angle is to remove a\\nrare long-latency operator from the common one-cycle EX path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU contains fully combinational RV32M division and\\nremainder operators. Even when CoreMark rarely executes DIV/REM inside the\\ntimed region, synthesis must still route those large operators through the\\nALU result mux, which is a plausible Fmax and LUT bottleneck on the Tang Nano\\n20K. Prior structural wins came from targeted pipeline-boundary changes, not\\nbroad queues or buffering, so the best next structural angle is to remove a\\nrare long-latency operator from the common one-cycle EX path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU datapath with a small iterative\\nRV32M divide unit that stalls EX only while an actual divide or remainder is\\nin flight. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/shift/branch address/MUL operations on the\\nexisting single-cycle path, and preserve the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitution\\nas a one-cycle formal-only path. This should raise median FPGA Fmax and reduce\\nLUT pressure with little CoreMark IPC cost, while exact RV32M results remain\\ncovered by the existing ALU/cosim tests and formal-deep.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM/% operators from the common combinational ALU path while keeping non-DIV operations and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior ...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Refine static branch direction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current predictor's biggest proven win is its stateless JAL plus backward-branch rule, while the recent RAS and tagged BHT attempts regressed from extra IF-stage state and muxing. CoreMark still pays occasional redirect bubbles when the coarse \\\"all backward branches taken\\\" rule is wrong, especially on non-loop backward conditionals and loop-exit forms that use equality compares.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current predictor's biggest proven win is its stateless JAL plus backward-branch rule, while the recent RAS and tagged BHT attempts regressed from extra IF-stage state and muxing. CoreMark still pays occasional redirect bubbles when the coarse \\\"all backward branches taken\\\" rule is wrong, especially on non-loop backward conditionals and loop-exit forms that use equality compares.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the existing fetch-side target computation and pred_next_pc plumbing, but make conditional branch direction a slightly richer static heuristic using funct3. Predict backward BNE and signed/unsigned range-test branches taken as loop back-edges, keep forward branches not taken, and make backward BEQ fall through by default because equality branches are more often exits/error checks than hot loop latches in optimized CoreMark. This targets remaining static mispredicts without adding tables, tags, RAS state, or EX-to-IF predictor update wiring, so the Fmax risk should be much lower than the failed dynamic predictor attempts.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refine the static conditional branch predictor to use funct3-specific direction heuristics while preserving the existing JAL prediction and direct target computation.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Trim register file reset cost\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best design already gained IPC from static direct-control prediction and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent attempts that add predictor state or reshape RV32M arithmetic hurt timing. A lower-risk remaining micro-optimization is the integer register file: it synchronously clears all 32 architectural registers on reset even though x0 is hardwired and normal RISC-V software initializes live registers before use. That reset fanout and x0 storage can cost LUT/FF resources and routing on the Tang Nano 20K without improving CoreMark's timed behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best design already gained IPC from static direct-control prediction and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent attempts that add predictor state or reshape RV32M arithmetic hurt timing. A lower-risk remaining micro-optimization is the integer register file: it synchronously clears all 32 architectural registers on reset even though x0 is hardwired and normal RISC-V software initializes live registers before use. That reset fanout and x0 storage can cost LUT/FF resources and routing on the Tang Nano 20K without improving CoreMark's timed behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the register file as 31 physical x1-x31 entries with x0 handled only in the read and write guards, and remove the bulk reset loop from the physical entries. Keep the same write-first bypass semantics so same-cycle WB-to-ID behavior and RVFI source data remain unchanged. This should reduce reset-net fanout, a small amount of storage/control logic, and potentially improve median Fmax without changing cycle count, memory ordering, decode legality, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Store only x1-x31 and remove the synchronous reset sweep while preserving x0 hardwir...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Scrubbed LUTRAM register file\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current register file is a 32x32 flip-flop array with a synchronous reset\\nloop over every architectural register. That costs roughly a thousand FFs plus\\nreset mux/fanout in a design that is already near the LUT budget, while reset\\ninitialization happens long before the CoreMark timing markers and does not\\nneed to be single-cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current register file is a 32x32 flip-flop array with a synchronous reset\\nloop over every architectural register. That costs roughly a thousand FFs plus\\nreset mux/fanout in a design that is already near the LUT budget, while reset\\ninitialization happens long before the CoreMark timing markers and does not\\nneed to be single-cycle.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild the integer register file as a LUTRAM-friendly structure with no\\nper-bit reset, then scrub one register per cycle after reset before releasing\\nfetch/decode. The architectural state remains zeroed before software executes,\\nx0 and write-first bypass semantics stay unchanged, and the RVFI source/write\\ndata contract is preserved. Removing the wide resettable FF array should lower\\nFF/LUT pressure and reset routing enough to improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax\\nwith no CoreMark IPC cost inside the bracketed measurement window.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the reset-cleared FF array with a LUTRAM-friendly register file, add a reset scrub counter that writes zeros sequentially, and keep x0 plus same-cycle write-first bypass behavior.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire the register-file ready signal so the pipeline is held in reset-like bubbles until the scrub completes, without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO or RVFI port set.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an internal pipeline-hold input ...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"One-entry JALR target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current fetch predictor already captures the large CoreMark win from direct JAL\\ntargets and backward conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts that added a\\nBHT, RAS, or richer branch heuristic regressed because they put too much state and\\ndecode/mux logic on the IF path. The remaining predictable control-flow bubbles are\\nlikely JALR returns and other repeated indirect jumps, but they need a much cheaper\\nmechanism than a stack or tagged direction table.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current fetch predictor already captures the large CoreMark win from direct JAL\\ntargets and backward conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts that added a\\nBHT, RAS, or richer branch heuristic regressed because they put too much state and\\ndecode/mux logic on the IF path. The remaining predictable control-flow bubbles are\\nlikely JALR returns and other repeated indirect jumps, but they need a much cheaper\\nmechanism than a stack or tagged direction table.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry JALR target memo in fetch. When a resolved JALR reaches EX, store\\nits PC and resolved target non-speculatively; when IF later fetches a JALR at the same\\nPC, predict the stored target through the existing pred_next_pc path. This is a tiny\\none-entry indirect-target predictor, not a direction predictor: direct JAL and backward\\nbranch prediction stay unchanged, and any stale JALR target is repaired by the existing\\nEX resolved-next-PC comparison.\\n\\nThis should recover repeated return or indirect-call bubbles in CoreMark with less IF\\ncritical-path and LUT cost than the failed RAS attempt because it removes push/pop\\nclassification, stack indexing, and multi-entry state. The implementation must not\\nchange the NRET=1 RVFI port set or architectural pc_wdata reporting.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\"...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Simplify MEM load lane mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained IPC by forwarding extended MEM-stage load data\\ndirectly into EX, but that makes the MEM load extraction logic part of a hot\\nbypass path. The existing implementation uses variable shifts and shifted\\nbyte masks for every access width, which can synthesize into a wider mux cone\\nthan the four byte lanes actually require.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained IPC by forwarding extended MEM-stage load data\\ndirectly into EX, but that makes the MEM load extraction logic part of a hot\\nbypass path. The existing implementation uses variable shifts and shifted\\nbyte masks for every access width, which can synthesize into a wider mux cone\\nthan the four byte lanes actually require.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte/halfword load extraction and store-mask generation\\nas explicit lane case statements keyed by addr[1:0] instead of variable shifts\\nand shift-by-eight arithmetic. Keep the same misalignment gating, RVFI aligned\\naddress/mask reporting, load_fwd_data semantics, and NRET=1 top-level port set.\\n\\nThis should slightly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax by shortening the\\ndmem_rdata-to-load_fwd_data-to-EX forwarding cone and simplifying store mask\\ndecode, with no cycle-count cost and far less risk than adding predictor state,\\nchanging the register file, or restructuring RV32M arithmetic.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load-data shifts and shifted byte-mask generation with explicit addr[1:0] lane cases while preserving misalignment traps, RVFI masks, and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable load-data shifts and shifted byte-mask genera...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve ready JALR in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already predicts direct JALs and backward branches, but\\nevery JALR still waits until EX to compute the target and repair the fetch PC.\\nPrior RAS and one-entry JALR predictor attempts regressed because they added\\nstate and target muxing on the IF path; an exact ID-stage JALR redirect can\\nrecover many of the same call/return bubbles without speculative predictor\\nstate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already predicts direct JALs and backward branches, but\\nevery JALR still waits until EX to compute the target and repair the fetch PC.\\nPrior RAS and one-entry JALR predictor attempts regressed because they added\\nstate and target muxing on the IF path; an exact ID-stage JALR redirect can\\nrecover many of the same call/return bubbles without speculative predictor\\nstate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a structural early-redirect path for legal JALR instructions whose rs1\\noperand is already available from the register file or same-cycle WB bypass.\\nID computes the aligned target from rs1_data plus the decoded immediate,\\nupdates the fetch PC for the next cycle, and records that target as the\\ncarried predicted next PC so EX does not redirect a second time. If the JALR\\nsource depends on an instruction still in ID/EX or EX/MEM, the early path is\\ndisabled and the existing EX-stage forwarding and redirect behavior handles\\nthe instruction normally. This should remove one to two wrong-path cycles on\\nready returns and indirect jumps while keeping the IF predictor simple and\\npreserving the NRET=1 RVFI retirement contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect legal JALR in decode, compute an aligned early target from rs1_data plus the I-immediate, expose an early redirect only when the rs1 producer is not still in ID/EX or EX/M...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Learn one hot loop exit\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL plus backward-branch rule, which\\nremoves most hot loop back-edge bubbles but still misses the final fall-through\\nexit of fixed-count backward loops. Prior predictor attempts regressed because\\nthey added general IF-stage tables, tags, RAS state, or indirect-target muxing.\\nCoreMark has stable counted loops, so a very narrow loop-exit predictor may\\nrecover a recurring miss class without paying the cost of a BHT or BTB.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL plus backward-branch rule, which\\nremoves most hot loop back-edge bubbles but still misses the final fall-through\\nexit of fixed-count backward loops. Prior predictor attempts regressed because\\nthey added general IF-stage tables, tags, RAS state, or indirect-target muxing.\\nCoreMark has stable counted loops, so a very narrow loop-exit predictor may\\nrecover a recurring miss class without paying the cost of a BHT or BTB.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry learned loop-exit predictor for one hot backward conditional\\nbranch. Keep the existing static direct-control predictor as the default: JAL is\\ntaken and backward branches are taken. On resolved backward branches, IF-side\\npredictor state learns one PC and its observed taken-run length before a\\nnot-taken exit. When the same branch is fetched on a later run and the local\\niteration counter reaches the learned exit count, override the static\\nbackward-taken prediction to fall through; all other branches use the current\\nlow-cost static rule. EX still compares resolved_next_pc against pred_next_pc,\\nso stale or aliasing predictor state only causes ordinary redirects and cannot\\naffect RVFI ordering or architectural pc_wdata.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add single-entr...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Trim late pipeline metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained IPC from static direct-control prediction and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that touched IF prediction, the register file, RV32M sharing, or MEM lane muxing regressed. A lower-risk remaining angle is reducing late-stage register and routing pressure without changing cycle behavior.\\n\\nEX/MEM and MEM/WB still carry full decoded control bundles plus branch metadata after EX has already consumed most of it. Those bits are not needed for memory, writeback, or RVFI, but they still widen packed pipeline buses and module boundaries unless synthesis can perfectly prune them through hierarchy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained IPC from static direct-control prediction and MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that touched IF prediction, the register file, RV32M sharing, or MEM lane muxing regressed. A lower-risk remaining angle is reducing late-stage register and routing pressure without changing cycle behavior.\\n\\nEX/MEM and MEM/WB still carry full decoded control bundles plus branch metadata after EX has already consumed most of it. Those bits are not needed for memory, writeback, or RVFI, but they still widen packed pipeline buses and module boundaries unless synthesis can perfectly prune them through hierarchy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the late pipeline metadata into compact stage-specific payloads. Keep the full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, then have EX/MEM carry only memory width/sign, memory enables, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal; have MEM/WB carry only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. Remove EX/MEM branch_taken and branch_target fields because redirect and pc_next are already resolved in EX and no downstream stage consumes those fields.\\n\\nThis should slightly reduce FF count, LUT muxing, and inter-stage routing on the Ta...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Word-only MEM load bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but the\\nforwarded operand path now includes byte/halfword lane selection and\\nsign-extension before feeding the EX operand muxes. A recent attempt to\\nrewrite that lane logic regressed, which suggests the load-forwarding cone is\\ntiming-sensitive and should be shortened rather than expanded. CoreMark's hot\\npointer and array chains are expected to be dominated by aligned LW uses, while\\ndependent LB/LH/LBU/LHU pairs should be rarer.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but the\\nforwarded operand path now includes byte/halfword lane selection and\\nsign-extension before feeding the EX operand muxes. A recent attempt to\\nrewrite that lane logic regressed, which suggests the load-forwarding cone is\\ntiming-sensitive and should be shortened rather than expanded. CoreMark's hot\\npointer and array chains are expected to be dominated by aligned LW uses, while\\ndependent LB/LH/LBU/LHU pairs should be rarer.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the structural MEM-to-EX bypass for word loads only, where the forwarded\\nvalue is simply the ready dmem word, and reintroduce a targeted one-cycle\\ninterlock for consumers of subword loads. Byte and halfword loads still use the\\nexisting sign/zero-extension path for WB and RVFI, but they no longer drive the\\nhot same-cycle MEM-load-forward operand path into EX. This should recover Fmax\\nby removing lane extraction and sign-extension from the load-use bypass while\\npreserving the important zero-bubble LW load-use cases that made the original\\nforwarding change profitable.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a targeted subword-load-use interlock using the ID/EX load width so LB/LH/LBU/LHU consumers wait for MEM/WB fo...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Share static predictor target adder\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\\n\\nThe existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\\n\\nThe existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the direct-control predictor chooses a single signed target offset first, then uses one shared pc-plus-offset adder for both predicted JAL targets and predicted backward branch targets. Keep the default pc+4 path, the JAL-always-taken rule, the backward-branch-taken rule, and the carried pred_next_pc semantics unchanged.\\n\\nThis should preserve the proven CoreMark cycle-count win from static prediction while reducing LUT use and IF-stage timing pressure. Because it adds no predictor state, tags, return stack, loop counter, or new redirect source, it avoids the failure mode seen in the previous predicto...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Isolate M-extension ALU mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\\nand MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\\nMEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\\nthe EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\\nlarge result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\\nthe RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\\nchanging cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\\nand MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\\nMEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\\nthe EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\\nlarge result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\\nthe RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\\nchanging cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv into two local result cones: a compact RV32I result mux for\\nADD/SUB/logic/shift/SLT/LUI and a separate RV32M result mux that keeps the existing\\nexact multiply/divide/remainder expressions unchanged. The final output should be\\nselected by a simple is_m_op