her than an eight-arm case or\\nsynthesized range compare.\\n\\nThis should slightly reduce EX-stage control decode and output-mux fan-in around\\nthe already successful RV32I/RV32M split, improving median FPGA Fmax without any\\nCoreMark cycle-count change. The decoder still recognizes the same RV32IM\\nencodings, the ALTOPS formulas remain behaviorally identical, and the NRET=1\\nRVFI contract is untouched.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Recode ALU_MUL through ALU_REMU to values with bit 4 set while keeping all RV32I ALU op values below 16.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the M-op membership case with the encoded op[4] class bit and keep the existing RV32I, RV32M, and ALTOPS result logic unchanged.\"}, {\"file\"...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Skid one ALU op behind dmem stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry execute skid register for safe younger instructions while EX/MEM is holding an older stalled memory operation. When dmem_stall is asserted and ID/EX holds a valid non-memory, non-branch, non-jump instruction that does not depend on the stalled load's rd, EX computes it once and captures the full ex_mem_t result into the skid entry. The front end and ID/EX then remain held until the older memory operation completes; after the memory instruction retires, the skid entry drains into the normal EX/MEM to MEM/WB path before any newly decoded instruction advances.\\n\\nThis is intentionally not a general store buffer, fetch FIFO, or out-of-order engine. It only hides one cycle of memory backpressure for independent straight-line ALU/LUI/AUIPC/MUL-class work, preserves strict in-order RVFI retirement by draining after the older memory op, and leaves loads, stores, branches, jum...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Gate predictor repair compare\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\\nrule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\\ncheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\\nJAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\\n\\nOne remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\\nincluding ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\\npred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\\nrequire predictor repair.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\\nrule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\\ncheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\\nJAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\\n\\nOne remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\\nincluding ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\\npred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\\nrequire predictor repair.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Preserve the exact existing fetch prediction policy and pred_next_pc metadata,\\nbut gate the EX-stage redirect/mispredict compare with the decoded control-flow\\nclass. Non-branch, non-jump instructions should never assert redirect, so they\\ncan bypass the 32-bit next-PC mismatch check and simply retire with pc+4 as\\ntoday. Branches and JAL/JALR continue to compute resolved_next_pc exactly as\\nthey do now, including misaligned-target trap handling, and still compare\\nagainst pred_next_pc to repair bad pr...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Factor forwarding matches\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but that makes the forwarding selector part of a hot EX operand path. Recent attempts that added state, new stalls, or broad datapath gating regressed, so the next micro_opt should be a very small cleanup that preserves the proven pipeline behavior.\\n\\nThe existing forward_unit repeats the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB register-destination comparisons inside separate ALU-result, load-result, and writeback arms for each source operand. Even if synthesis can sometimes common-subexpression these terms, making the producer matches explicit should reduce comparator duplication, fanout, and select-control depth with no cycle-count or architectural risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but that makes the forwarding selector part of a hot EX operand path. Recent attempts that added state, new stalls, or broad datapath gating regressed, so the next micro_opt should be a very small cleanup that preserves the proven pipeline behavior.\\n\\nThe existing forward_unit repeats the same EX/MEM and MEM/WB register-destination comparisons inside separate ALU-result, load-result, and writeback arms for each source operand. Even if synthesis can sometimes common-subexpression these terms, making the producer matches explicit should reduce comparator duplication, fanout, and select-control depth with no cycle-count or architectural risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/forward_unit.sv to compute per-source producer match terms once: ex_mem_match_rs1/rs2 and mem_wb_match_rs1/rs2. Then choose EX/MEM ALU forwarding, MEM load forwarding, MEM/WB forwarding, or no forwarding from those match terms plus the existing ex_mem_is_load and ex_mem_load_fwd_valid qualifiers.\\n\\nThis keeps the same priority order and preserves the ready-qualifi...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Register final writeback value\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB stage carries both alu_result and read_data, then selects the\\narchitectural writeback value through a combinational WB mux. That mux output\\nfans out to the register file write port, same-cycle regfile read bypass,\\nMEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata. Prior structural attempts that\\nadded queues, buffers, or sidecars regressed because they added broad control;\\nthis targets a narrower pipeline-boundary fanout point without changing IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB stage carries both alu_result and read_data, then selects the\\narchitectural writeback value through a combinational WB mux. That mux output\\nfans out to the register file write port, same-cycle regfile read bypass,\\nMEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata. Prior structural attempts that\\nadded queues, buffers, or sidecars regressed because they added broad control;\\nthis targets a narrower pipeline-boundary fanout point without changing IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a preselected rd_wdata field to the MEM/WB payload and compute it in\\nmem_stage when the MEM/WB register captures. Loads register the extended\\nload_data, while ALU/JAL/JALR/LUI/AUIPC results register the existing\\nalu_result. Then make wb_stage and RVFI consume that registered final value\\ndirectly instead of rebuilding the mem_to_reg mux in WB. This should shorten\\nthe WB forwarding and register-file bypass cone, reduce ctrl.mem_to_reg\\nfanout, and preserve the current single-retire RVFI ordering and all memory\\nmetadata. During dmem stalls, the held MEM/WB fields keep the registered\\nrd_wdata alive for the existing forwarding behavior while valid is cleared.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an rd_wdata field to mem_wb_t so the final architectural writeback value is registere...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Drop JAL fetch prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor lesson is that added state or richer control-flow\\nheuristics have repeatedly cost more FPGA timing than they saved in CoreMark\\nbubbles. The current IF predictor still forms a JAL immediate and JAL target\\nfor every fetched instruction, and the recent attempt to gate that path\\nregressed from extra mux/control cost. If direct JALs are uncommon inside the\\nbracketed CoreMark hot loops after -O3 inlining, removing this predictor path\\noutright may recover Fmax while keeping the proven backward-branch prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor lesson is that added state or richer control-flow\\nheuristics have repeatedly cost more FPGA timing than they saved in CoreMark\\nbubbles. The current IF predictor still forms a JAL immediate and JAL target\\nfor every fetched instruction, and the recent attempt to gate that path\\nregressed from extra mux/control cost. If direct JALs are uncommon inside the\\nbracketed CoreMark hot loops after -O3 inlining, removing this predictor path\\noutright may recover Fmax while keeping the proven backward-branch prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep conditional branch prediction exactly as it is today: backward branches\\nare predicted taken and forward branches fall through. Stop predicting direct\\nJAL in IF, so JAL follows pc+4 and is repaired by the existing EX-stage\\nresolved_next_pc versus pred_next_pc redirect check. This deletes the\\nalways-active J-immediate shuffle, JAL target adder, and JAL arm of the IF\\npredicted-next-PC mux instead of trying to gate them. The expected cycle loss\\nis limited if timed CoreMark has few direct JALs, while the Fmax gain can\\napply to every fetch cycle.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove direct-JAL target formation and prediction from the fetch pred...\n  Line 38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead hazard inputs\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already removed load-use bubbles with MEM-to-EX load forwarding, and the recent successful micro-opt was a tiny cleanup on the forwarding select path. The hazard unit still carries the old load-use interlock inputs from ID/EX and IF/ID even though they are now explicitly unused, which needlessly fans out hot instruction, rd, and control signals into an extra module boundary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already removed load-use bubbles with MEM-to-EX load forwarding, and the recent successful micro-opt was a tiny cleanup on the forwarding select path. The hazard unit still carries the old load-use interlock inputs from ID/EX and IF/ID even though they are now explicitly unused, which needlessly fans out hot instruction, rd, and control signals into an extra module boundary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the obsolete load-use interlock ports from rtl/hazard_unit.sv and their wiring in rtl/core.sv. The unit should continue to control only redirects plus imem/dmem backpressure exactly as it does today, preserving MEM-to-EX load forwarding, RVFI ordering, traps, memory behavior, and the NRET=1 top-level port set.\\n\\nThis should slightly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax by reducing routing pressure and synthesis-visible fanout from IF/ID instruction fields and ID/EX load metadata, with zero cycle-count change and very low architectural risk. It deliberately avoids reintroducing source-aware load-use logic, store bypasses, or any predictor/control-path state that prior iterations showed to be fragile.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Delete the unused id_ex_mem_read, id_ex_rd, if_id_rs1, and if_id_rs2 ports and lint suppressions, leaving only redirect and bus-stall control logic.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"de...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"Predecode forwarding selects\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The most recent improvement came from factoring duplicated forwarding matches, which strongly suggests the EX operand-select path is still timing-sensitive. Prior structural attempts with FIFOs, store buffers, divider sidecars, and dmem skid slots regressed because they added broad control to common paths. A narrower structural retiming can target the same hot forwarding cone without changing CoreMark IPC or memory ordering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The most recent improvement came from factoring duplicated forwarding matches, which strongly suggests the EX operand-select path is still timing-sensitive. Prior structural attempts with FIFOs, store buffers, divider sidecars, and dmem skid slots regressed because they added broad control to common paths. A narrower structural retiming can target the same hot forwarding cone without changing CoreMark IPC or memory ordering.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the producer/consumer rd-vs-rs comparisons for EX forwarding one stage earlier and carry predecoded rs1/rs2 forwarding selects in the ID/EX payload. In ID, compare the decoded instruction's source fields against the current ID/EX producer that will become EX/MEM and the current EX/MEM producer that will become MEM/WB, then latch compact select hints alongside the operands. EX keeps only the small operand muxes and the existing ready-qualified MEM-load handling, with a fallback or hold behavior that preserves correctness through dmem stalls and redirects.\\n\\nThis should shorten the common EX path from comparator-plus-priority-plus-mux to mostly muxing, building on the proven forwarding-match optimization while avoiding new queues, predictor state, or out-of-order retirement risk. RVFI source values remain the post-forward operands latched into EX/MEM, and the NRET=1 retirement contract is unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confiden...\n  Line 40: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Prioritize predictor fallthrough path\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only durable predictor win in the bench core is the stateless direct-control policy: predict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Follow-on attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo, loop-exit state, richer static direction, target-adder sharing, JAL gating, or predictor repair gating mostly regressed because extra IF or EX control cost outweighed the remaining saved bubbles.\\n\\nThe current IF predictor still presents a three-way predicted-next-PC mux over pc+4, backward-branch target, and JAL target on every fetch. CoreMark's hot path is dominated by ordinary fall-through instructions plus loop branches, so making fall-through the explicit fast/default predictor path may reduce fetch timing pressure without changing the successful prediction behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only durable predictor win in the bench core is the stateless direct-control policy: predict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Follow-on attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo, loop-exit state, richer static direction, target-adder sharing, JAL gating, or predictor repair gating mostly regressed because extra IF or EX control cost outweighed the remaining saved bubbles.\\n\\nThe current IF predictor still presents a three-way predicted-next-PC mux over pc+4, backward-branch target, and JAL target on every fetch. CoreMark's hot path is dominated by ordinary fall-through instructions plus loop branches, so making fall-through the explicit fast/default predictor path may reduce fetch timing pressure without changing the successful prediction behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the predictor first computes pc_plus4 as the default predicted next PC, then overrides it only for the two existing taken-prediction cases: direct JAL and backward conditional branch. Keep both target adders and the exact same static dire...","metadata":{"matches":39,"truncated":false},"title":"category: structural|structural|pipeline|stage|skid|IF/ID|EX/MEM|MEM/WB|forward|hazard|retire|register|fifo|buffer","time":{"start":1778634166057,"end":1778634166076}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b073678932b569d016a03cdb5e5a8819ba3bc930660a161ec"}},"id":"prt_e1edb8f1f001Vcj4E6XCBA45hP","sessionID":"ses_1e1249795ffeRbMy3U6KW9KAfw","messageID":"msg_e1edb68af00152Gv6nETuf2Z41"}}
