{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778634226926,"sessionID":"ses_1e1249795ffeRbMy3U6KW9KAfw","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_gLrMNGu4C9VErDTANWDF9Xf4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Register memory request metadata\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already gets its IPC wins from static fetch prediction and\n+  MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while broad structural changes such as fetch queues,\n+  store buffers, IF/ID registration, divider sidecars, EX skid slots, and forwarding\n+  predecode have repeatedly lost timing or control simplicity. A more promising\n+  structural target is the MEM boundary itself: mem_stage still derives byte masks,\n+  replicated store data, aligned RVFI memory addresses, and misalignment traps\n+  combinationally from EX/MEM on the same cycle it drives dmem outputs and load\n+  forwarding.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Move memory request metadata formation into the EX/MEM pipeline register. After\n+  EX computes the effective address and forwarded store data, also compute and\n+  register the byte-lane mask, replicated store write data, aligned RVFI address,\n+  load/store rmask/wmask candidates, and memory-misalignment trap bit. Then simplify\n+  MEM so stores and RVFI memory metadata use registered fields, while the existing\n+  compact load extraction and ready-qualified MEM-to-EX load forwarding stay unchanged.\n+\n+  This keeps the single-retire NRET=1 contract, memory ordering, trap behavior, and\n+  CoreMark IPC unchanged, but shortens the MEM-stage dmem_wen/dmem_wdata/RVFI metadata\n+  cone and avoids the failed pattern of adding new queues or predictor state. The\n+  extra EX-side work depends only on already-available alu_result[1:0], mem_width,\n+  and forwarded rs2, so it should be a smaller timing risk than adding global stall\n+  or bypass control.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Extend ex_mem_t with registered memory request metadata: replicated store data, aligned RVFI address, rmask/wmask candidates, and a memory-misalignment flag.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compute byte-lane masks, replicated store data, aligned memory address, and memory misalignment from the EX effective address before latching EX/MEM.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the registered EX/MEM memory metadata for dmem write outputs, RVFI masks/address, and trap gating while preserving the existing load extraction and load-forwarding behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,36 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Register memory request metadata\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already gets its IPC wins from static fetch prediction and\n+  MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while broad structural changes such as fetch queues,\n+  store buffers, IF/ID registration, divider sidecars, EX skid slots, and forwarding\n+  predecode have repeatedly lost timing or control simplicity. A more promising\n+  structural target is the MEM boun