tion cost instead of adding new prediction behavior.\\n\\nToday IF carries a full 32-bit pred_next_pc through IF/ID and ID/EX only so EX\\ncan compare it with the resolved next PC. For this predictor, correctness only\\ndepends on whether fetch predicted the direct control transfer taken or\\nfall-through: EX can recompute the same direct JAL/branch target from pc and imm\\nwhen needed, and JALR is still predicted fall-through.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the carried pred_next_pc metadata with a compact prediction-direction\\nbit for the existing static predictor. IF still computes the predicted next PC\\nlocally to update the fetch PC, but it exports only whether it predicted a\\ndirect JAL/backward branch as taken. ID passes that bit to EX. EX comp...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Fast-path simple ALU results\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even thou