{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778620018005,"sessionID":"ses_1e1fcdaa8ffez35AcrbTMIWZb3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_VYqGT0n9wCnLcIbQCaNJuqby","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\n+title: \"Add decoupled sequential fetch queue\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark is evaluated with roughly 22% randomized instruction and data bus backpressure. The current front end is fully coupled to the pipeline: any imem miss-ready cycle injects a bubble, and dmem stalls prevent useful sequential fetching. A small in-order fetch queue can bank instructions during cycles when the back end is blocked and then drain through short imem-ready gaps, improving iterations per cycle without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two- or four-entry sequential fetch FIFO owned by if_stage. The fetch side should keep issuing pc+4 requests into free FIFO slots whenever there is no redirect and imem_ready is high, while the decode side consumes one queued instruction whenever ID is not stalled. Redirects flush the FIFO and restart fetching at the redirect target, preserving precise pc_rdata/pc_wdata and single-channel RVFI order. This is a structural decoupling change: it should hide many isolated imem stalls and allow useful front-end work during dmem/load-use holds, at modest LUT/FF cost and with limited Fmax risk because the existing decode/execute datapath is not lengthened.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Turn the IF output into a small valid/pc/instruction FIFO with redirect flush and sequential prefetch into free entries.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the IF queue consume/stall semantics so ID drains queued instructions while fetch can run ahead when the back end is held.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate front-end fetch backpressure from decode consumption so imem stalls do not necessarily bubble ID when the queue is non-empty.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Treat IF queue empty as the only front-end bubble condition and preserve existing flush behavior for redirects and load-use hazards.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\n+title: \"Add decoupled sequential fetch queue\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark is evaluated with roughly 22% randomized instruction and data bus backpressure. The current front end is fully coupled to the pipeline: any imem miss-ready cycle injects a bubble, and dmem stalls prevent useful sequential fetching. A small in-order fetch queue can bank instructions during cycles when the back end is blocked and then drain through short imem-ready gaps, improving iterations per cycle without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two- or four-entry sequential fetch FIFO owned by if_stage. The fetch side should keep issuing pc+4 requests into free FIFO slots whenever there is no redirect and imem_ready is high, while the decode side consumes one queued instruction whenever ID is not stalled. Redirects flush the FIFO and restart fetching at the redirect target, preserving precise pc_rdata/pc_wdata and single-channel RVFI order. This is a structural decoupling change: it should hide many isolated imem stalls and allow useful front-end work during dmem/load-use holds, at modest LUT/FF cost and with limited Fmax risk because the existing decode/execute datapath is not lengthened.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Turn the IF output into a small valid/pc/instruction FIFO with redirect flush and sequential prefetch into free entries.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the IF queue consume/stall semantics so ID drains queued instructions while fetch can run ahead when the back end is held.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate front-end fetch backpressure from decode consumption so imem stalls do not necessarily bubble ID when the queue is non-empty.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Treat IF queue empty as the only front-end bubble condition and preserve existing flush behavior for redirects and load-use hazards.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\n+title: \"Add decoupled sequential fetch queue\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark is evaluated with roughly 22% randomized instruction and data bus backpressure. The current front end is fully coupled to the pipeline: any imem miss-ready cycle injects a bubble, and dmem stalls prevent useful sequential fetching. A small in-order fetch queue can bank instructions during cycles when the back end is blocked and then drain through short imem-ready gaps, improving iterations per cycle without changing the single-retire RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two- or four-entry sequential fetch FIFO owned by if_stage. The fetch side should keep issuing pc+4 requests into free FIFO slots whenever there is no redirect and imem_ready is high, while the decode side consumes one queued instruction whenever ID is not stalled. Redirects flush the FIFO and restart fetching at the redirect target, preserving precise pc_rdata/pc_wdata and single-channel RVFI order. This is a structural decoupling change: it should hide many isolated imem stalls and allow useful front-end work during dmem/load-use holds, at modest LUT/FF cost and with limited Fmax risk because the existing decode/execute datapath is not lengthened.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Turn the IF output into a small valid/pc/instruction FIFO with redirect flush and sequential prefetch into free entries.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the IF queue consume/stall semantics so ID drains queued instructions while fetch can run ahead when the back end is held.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate front-end fetch backpressure from decode consumption so imem stalls do not necessarily bubble ID when the queue is non-empty.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Treat IF queue empty as the only front-end bubble condition and preserve existing flush behavior for redirects and load-use hazards.\"\n","additions":19,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778620018002,"end":1778620018004}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b6d83cba21235b5016a03966c84408198963194b615b3f69b"}},"id":"prt_e1e039859001WRjc1NE0VHkcZ8","sessionID":"ses_1e1fcdaa8ffez35AcrbTMIWZb3","messageID":"msg_e1e035c8b001GN05c6HzriFpDB"}}
