{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778624754977,"sessionID":"ses_1e1b5c3bfffeDl9SPU25UAOtSU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_NkJNfahXOXrYeF5i5l9v1Exp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Scrubbed LUTRAM register file\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file is a 32x32 flip-flop array with a synchronous reset\n+  loop over every architectural register. That costs roughly a thousand FFs plus\n+  reset mux/fanout in a design that is already near the LUT budget, while reset\n+  initialization happens long before the CoreMark timing markers and does not\n+  need to be single-cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rebuild the integer register file as a LUTRAM-friendly structure with no\n+  per-bit reset, then scrub one register per cycle after reset before releasing\n+  fetch/decode. The architectural state remains zeroed before software executes,\n+  x0 and write-first bypass semantics stay unchanged, and the RVFI source/write\n+  data contract is preserved. Removing the wide resettable FF array should lower\n+  FF/LUT pressure and reset routing enough to improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax\n+  with no CoreMark IPC cost inside the bracketed measurement window.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the reset-cleared FF array with a LUTRAM-friendly register file, add a reset scrub counter that writes zeros sequentially, and keep x0 plus same-cycle write-first bypass behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the register-file ready signal so the pipeline is held in reset-like bubbles until the scrub completes, without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO or RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an internal pipeline-hold input or equivalent control path for register-file initialization so normal imem/dmem stall and redirect precedence remains unchanged after release.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Scrubbed LUTRAM register file\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file is a 32x32 flip-flop array with a synchronous reset\n+  loop over every architectural register. That costs roughly a thousand FFs plus\n+  reset mux/fanout in a design that is already near the LUT budget, while reset\n+  initialization happens long before the CoreMark timing markers and does not\n+  need to be single-cycle.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rebuild the integer register file as a LUTRAM-friendly structure with no\n+  per-bit reset, then scrub one register per cycle after reset before releasing\n+  fetch/decode. The architectural state remains zeroed before software executes,\n+  x0 and write-first bypass semantics stay unchanged, and the RVFI source/write\n+  data contract is preserved. Removing the wide resettable FF array should lower\n+  FF/LUT pressure and reset routing enough to improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax\n+  with no CoreMark IPC cost inside the bracketed measurement window.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the reset-cle