\n24:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n25:     description: \"Wire the register-file ready signal so the pipeline is held in reset-like bubbles until the scrub completes, without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO or RVFI port set.\"\n26:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n27:     description: \"Add an internal pipeline-hold input or equivalent control path for register-file initialization so normal imem/dmem stall and redirect precedence remains unchanged after release.\"\n\n(End of file - total 27 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\ntitle: \"Scrubbed LUTRAM register file\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current register file is a 32x32 flip-flop array with a synchronous reset\n  loop over every architectural register. That costs roughly a thousand FFs plus\n  reset mux/fanout in a design that is already near the LUT budget, while reset\n  initialization happens long before the CoreMark timing markers and does not\n  need to be single-cycle.\nhypothesis: |\n  Rebuild the integer register file as a LUTRAM-friendly structure with no\n  per-bit reset, then scrub one register per cycle after reset before releasing\n  fetch/decode. The architectural state remains zeroed before software executes,\n  x0 and write-first bypass semantics stay unchanged, and the RVFI source/write\n  data contract is preserved. Removing the wide resettable FF array should lower\n  FF/LUT pressure and reset routing enough to improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax\n  with no CoreMark IPC cost inside the bracketed measurement window.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r5s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778624759730,"end":1778624759734}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c0d1742a45f7de6016a03a8f70f848194a55d28db75ec52e8"}},"id":"prt_e1e4c0589001QaRUht52rfhay5","sessionID":"ses_1e1b5c3bfffeDl9SPU25UAOtSU","messageID":"msg_e1e4bf60e001Str5zlPHcj40ue"}}
