{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778626103857,"sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","part":{"id":"prt_e1e608a300019p3JoQaMr8EzZ3","messageID":"msg_e1e6083c6001o0x8AJgMkqfmcF","sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","snapshot":"e96e55261c0ad37b514acf7610dfcccab7b4474e","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778626128305,"sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","part":{"id":"prt_e1e60e684001TLAQsnr3jrRhP7","messageID":"msg_e1e6083c6001o0x8AJgMkqfmcF","sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","type":"text","text":"The structural history strongly favors narrow pipeline-boundary changes: broad fetch queues, store buffering, register-file reshaping, and DIV staging either regressed or broke, while MEM-to-EX load forwarding improved IPC. I’m going to avoid adding IF-path predictor state or broad buffering and propose a targeted structural bypass/retiming around the remaining load/writeback boundary.","time":{"start":1778626127492,"end":1778626128304},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0ff8130bdc301229016a03ae4f650881948d34570bb5819c3a","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778626188183,"sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","part":{"id":"prt_e1e61d30c001utTS6WRWUBpD7Y","messageID":"msg_e1e6083c6001o0x8AJgMkqfmcF","sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","type":"text","text":"The hypothesis will target exact early JALR resolution from ID only when the rs1 operand is already in the regfile/WB path. That avoids speculative IF predictor tables and preserves the existing EX redirect path for dependency cases that still need forwarding.","time":{"start":1778626188044,"end":1778626188180},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0ff8130bdc301229016a03ae8bcc608194b68223e907df1623","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778626191397,"sessionID":"ses_1e19faaf0ffe1Ndw1k9sL0CThb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_JiyEJFYihjIKAfkDCt2GKoPF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\n+title: Resolve ready JALR in ID\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already predicts direct JALs and backward branches, but\n+  every JALR still waits until EX to compute the target and repair the fetch PC.\n+  Prior RAS and one-entry JALR predictor attempts regressed because they added\n+  state and target muxing on the IF path; an exact ID-stage JALR redirect can\n+  recover many of the same call/return bubbles without speculative predictor\n+  state.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a structural early-redirect path for legal JALR instructions whose rs1\n+  operand is already available from the register file or same-cycle WB bypass.\n+  ID computes the aligned target from rs1_data plus the decoded immediate,\n+  updates the fetch PC for the next cycle, and records that target as the\n+  carried predicted next PC so EX does not redirect a second time. If the JALR\n+  source depends on an instruction still in ID/EX or EX/MEM, the early path is\n+  disabled and the existing EX-stage forwarding and redirect behavior handles\n+  the instruction normally. This should remove one to two wrong-path cycles on\n+  ready returns and indirect jumps while keeping the IF predictor simple and\n+  preserving the NRET=1 RVFI retirement contract.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect legal JALR in decode, compute an aligned early target from rs1_data plus the I-immediate, expose an early redirect only when the rs1 producer is not still in ID/EX or EX/MEM, and latch the early target as pred_next_pc for that JALR.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a PC-update-only early redirect input that changes the fetch PC on the next edge without flushing the current IF/ID combinational payload, so the JALR itself still enters ID/EX.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire ID-stage early JALR redirect signals into fetch, provide rs1 readiness information from in-flight producer metadata, and keep the existing EX redirect path as the fallback for dependency cases.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Preserve normal JALR execution and RVFI pc_wdata while suppressing duplicate redirects when ID has already carried the exact JALR target in pred_next_pc.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,33 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\n+title: Resolve ready JALR in ID\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already predicts direct JALs and backward branches, but\n+  every JALR still waits until EX to compute the target and repair the fetch PC.\n+  Prior RAS and one-entry JALR predictor attempts regressed because they added\n+  state and target muxing on the IF path; an exact ID-stage JALR redirect can\n+  recover many of the same call/return bubbles without speculative predictor\n+  state.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a structural early-redirect path for legal JALR instructions whose rs1\n+  operand is already available