{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778627336874,"sessionID":"ses_1e18e1a9bffebFZSXJV9acf0Uh","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Cub9JHHvBKsMOfQa2hS6r9Jc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Word-only MEM load bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but the\n+  forwarded operand path now includes byte/halfword lane selection and\n+  sign-extension before feeding the EX operand muxes. A recent attempt to\n+  rewrite that lane logic regressed, which suggests the load-forwarding cone is\n+  timing-sensitive and should be shortened rather than expanded. CoreMark's hot\n+  pointer and array chains are expected to be dominated by aligned LW uses, while\n+  dependent LB/LH/LBU/LHU pairs should be rarer.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Keep the structural MEM-to-EX bypass for word loads only, where the forwarded\n+  value is simply the ready dmem word, and reintroduce a targeted one-cycle\n+  interlock for consumers of subword loads. Byte and halfword loads still use the\n+  existing sign/zero-extension path for WB and RVFI, but they no longer drive the\n+  hot same-cycle MEM-load-forward operand path into EX. This should recover Fmax\n+  by removing lane extraction and sign-extension from the load-use bypass while\n+  preserving the important zero-bubble LW load-use cases that made the original\n+  forwarding change profitable.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a targeted subword-load-use interlock using the ID/EX load width so LB/LH/LBU/LHU consumers wait for MEM/WB forwarding while LW consumers still bypass from MEM.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the ID/EX memory width into the hazard unit and keep the NRET=1 RVFI interface unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Make load_fwd_data/load_fwd_valid represent only ready word loads, leaving byte/half sign-extension for the WB and RVFI paths.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Preserve MEM-load forwarding priority only when the MEM stage reports a valid word-load bypass; subword dependents fall through to MEM/WB after the interlock.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Word-only MEM load bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core gained IPC from MEM-to-EX load forwarding, but the\n+  forwarded operand path now includes byte/halfword lane selection and\n+  sign-extension before feeding the EX operand muxes. A recent attempt to\n+  rewrite that lane logic regressed, which suggests the load-forwarding cone is\n+  timing-sensitive and should be shortened rather than expanded. CoreMark's hot\n+  pointer and array chains are expected to be dominated by aligned LW uses, while\n+  dependent LB/LH/LBU/LHU pairs should be rarer.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Keep the structural MEM-to-EX bypass for word loads only, where the forwarded\n+  value is simply the ready dmem word, and reintroduce a targeted one-cycle\n+  interlock for consumers of subword loads. Byte and halfword loads still use the\n+  existing sign/zero-extension path for WB and RVFI, but they no longer drive the\n+  hot same-cycle MEM-load-forward operand path into EX. This should recover Fmax\n+  by removing lane extraction and sign-extension from the load-use bypass while\n+  preserving the important zero-bubble LW load-use cases that made the original\n+  forwarding change profitable.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a targeted subword-load-use interlock using the ID/EX load width so LB/LH/LBU/LHU consumers wait for MEM/WB forwarding while LW consumers still bypass from MEM.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the ID/EX memory width into the hazard unit and keep the NRET=1 RVFI interface unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Make load_fwd_data/load_fwd_valid represent only ready word loads, leaving byte/half sign-extension for the WB and RVFI paths.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Preserve MEM-load forwarding priority only when the MEM stage reports a valid word-load bypass; subword dependents fall through to MEM/WB after the interlock.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-202605