{"type":"text","timestamp":1778628378784,"sessionID":"ses_1e17dbc63ffeXzcfu8A8hsAMPa","part":{"id":"prt_e1e833d20001BjYXHVeZhnvJPd","messageID":"msg_e1e82b8ad001CtfVXr63G5Eo0t","sessionID":"ses_1e17dbc63ffeXzcfu8A8hsAMPa","type":"text","text":"I’m going to write a structural hypothesis that revisits front-end decoupling, but fixes the prior FIFO failure mode by fetching along the already-successful static predicted path instead of only buffering fall-through `pc+4` instructions.","time":{"start":1778628377888,"end":1778628378783},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_083167c4332cec78016a03b719c6608198af779ebe73bd502c","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778628391021,"sessionID":"ses_1e17dbc63ffeXzcfu8A8hsAMPa","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_urmdcHOhyffPqD66x0VelBLM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\n+title: \"Predicted path fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\n+  front end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\n+  an isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\n+  immediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\n+  pc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\n+  loop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\n+  JAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\n+  to hold correct useful instructions.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure IF into a two-entry predicted-path skid buffer with separate fetch and decode sides.\n+  The fetch side advances its private fetch PC along the existing static predicted next PC whenever\n+  io_imemReady is high and the queue has space, including cycles where dmem backpressure is holding\n+  ID/EX and EX/MEM. The decode side consumes the oldest queued pc/instruction/pred_next_pc only\n+  when ID is allowed to advance; when the queue is empty, decode simply sees an invalid bubble.\n+  Any EX redirect flushes the queue and restarts the fetch PC at the resolved target, preserving\n+  the existing RVFI pc_rdata/pc_wdata ordering and the NRET=1 single-retire contract.\n+\n+  This targets the specific failure mode called out by the prior sequential FIFO lesson: it keeps\n+  front-end decoupling, but makes it redirect-aware and predictor-aware without adding a BHT, RAS,\n+  store buffer, or new architectural retirement channel. It should recover cycles lost to short\n+  imem gaps after dmem holds while keeping the successful static predictor policy unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two-entry queue that stores pc, instr, and predicted next PC; fill it from a private predicted-path fetch PC and flush it on EX redirects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into the fetch queue, split fetch-side progress from decode-side consumption, and preserve the existing NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Stop treating every imem stall as a mandatory decode bubble when the fetch queue has data, and allow the IF fetch side to run during dmem-induced ID/EX holds.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\n+title: \"Predicted path fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\n+  front end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\n+  an isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\n+  immediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\n+  pc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\n+  loop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\n+  JAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\n+  to hold correct useful instructions.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure IF into a two-entry predicted-path skid buffer with separate fetch and decode sides.\n+  The fetch side advances its private fetch PC along the existing static predicted next PC whenever\n+  io_imemReady is high and the queue has space, including cycles where dmem backpressure is holding\n+  ID/EX and EX/MEM. The decode side consumes the oldest queued pc/instruction/pred_next_pc only\n+  when ID is allowed to advance; when the queue is empty, decode simply sees an invalid bubble.\n+  Any EX redirect flushes the queue and restarts the fetch PC at the resolved target, preserving\n+  the existing RVFI pc_rdata/pc_wdata ordering and the NRET=1 single-retire contract.\n+\n+  This targets the specific failure mode called out by the prior sequential FIFO lesson: it keeps\n+  front-end decoupling, but makes it redirect-aware and predictor-aware without adding a BHT, RAS,\n+  store buffer, or new architectural retirement channel. It should recover cycles lost to short\n+  imem gaps after dmem holds while keeping the successful static predictor policy unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two-entry queue that stores pc, instr, and predicted next PC; fill it from a private predicted-path fetch PC and flush it on EX redirects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into the fetch queue, split fetch-side progress from decode-side consumption, and preserve the existing NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Stop treating every imem stall as a mandatory decode bubble when the fetch queue has data, and allow the IF fetch side to run during dmem-induced ID/EX holds.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\n+title: \"Predicted path fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\n+  front end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\n+  an isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\n+  immediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\n+  pc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\n+  loop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\n+  JAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\n+  to hold correct useful instructions.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Restructure IF into a two-entry predicted-path skid buffer with separate fetch and decode sides.\n+  The fetch side advances its private fetch PC along the existing static predicted next PC whenever\n+  io_imemReady is high and the queue has space, including cycles where dmem backpressure is holding\n+  ID/EX and EX/MEM. The decode side consumes the oldest queued pc/instruction/pred_next_pc only\n+  when ID is allowed to advance; when the queue is empty, decode simply sees an invalid bubble.\n+  Any EX redirect flushes the queue and restarts the fetch PC at the resolved target, preserving\n+  the existing RVFI pc_rdata/pc_wdata ordering and the NRET=1 single-retire contract.\n+\n+  This targets the specific failure mode called out by the prior sequential FIFO lesson: it keeps\n+  front-end decoupling, but makes it redirect-aware and predictor-aware without adding a BHT, RAS,\n+  store buffer, or new architectural retirement channel. It should recover cycles lost to short\n+  imem gaps after dmem holds while keeping the successful static predictor policy unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID handoff with a two-entry queue that stores pc, instr, and predicted next PC; fill it from a private predicted-path fetch PC and flush it on EX redirects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into the fetch queue, split fetch-side progress from decode-side consumption, and preserve the existing NRET=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Stop treating every imem stall as a mandatory decode bubble when the fetch queue has data, and allow the IF fetch side to run during dmem-induced ID/EX holds.\"\n","additions":35,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778628391018,"e