n  loop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\n  JAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\n  to hold correct useful instructions.\nhypothesis: |\n  Restructure IF into a two-entry predicted-path skid buffer with separate fetch and decode sides.\n  The fetch side advances its private fetch PC along the existing static predicted next PC whenever\n  io_imemReady is high and the queue has space, including cycles where dmem backpressure is holding\n  ID/EX and EX/MEM. The decode side consumes the oldest queued pc/instruction/pred_next_pc only\n  when ID is allowed to advance; when the queue is empty, decode simply sees an invalid bubble.\n  Any EX redirect flushes the queue and restarts the fetch PC at the resolved target, preserving\n  the existing RVFI pc_rdata/pc_wdata ordering and the NRET=1 single-retire contract.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778628397069,"end":1778628397077}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08c2175f5c9b93e1016a03b72c0138819b81234d83658798c0"}},"id":"prt_e1e838444001lZ4I01eo1UdRWv","sessionID":"ses_1e17dbc63ffeXzcfu8A8hsAMPa","messageID":"msg_e1e8370d3001dcWSTYpD24kNP4"}}
