{"type":"text","timestamp":1778629431489,"sessionID":"ses_1e16dcdc2ffeBnZsTvhJ8lSuav","part":{"id":"prt_e1e934f01001uKIfJ4nGiLVzB9","messageID":"msg_e1e92dcd0001cCvXXASXc10y01","sessionID":"ses_1e16dcdc2ffeBnZsTvhJ8lSuav","type":"text","text":"I’ll write a schema-valid structural hypothesis for a minimal true IF/ID register. It targets Fmax by cutting the current imem-data-to-decode/register-read path, while explicitly avoiding the prior multi-entry FIFO/skid-buffer control that regressed.","time":{"start":1778629431041,"end":1778629431485},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0b51024baff12053016a03bb36d2ec8195a8842fb9a6dec4eb","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778629441870,"sessionID":"ses_1e16dcdc2ffeBnZsTvhJ8lSuav","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_bL5uNFWNjt2Z3WHFlRe4Re6v","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\n+title: \"Register fetch decode boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\n+\n+  A minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single valid IF/ID pipeline register owned by if_stage, with explicit consume/hold behavior so an imem-not-ready cycle drains to one bubble instead of replaying the previous instruction. When decode is stalled by dmem backpressure, hold the IF/ID register and PC; when imem is ready and decode can advance, capture pc, instr, and pred_next_pc from the existing static predictor. Redirects flush the registered IF/ID payload and update PC exactly as today.\n+\n+  This turns the current pseudo five-stage pipe into a true fetch/decode split without adding multi-entry queue state, tags, predictor tables, or a new redirect source. It may add one extra wrong-path slot on unpredicted JALR/forward-branch redirects, but CoreMark's hot direct jumps and backward loop branches are already predicted, so the Fmax gain from breaking the imem-to-ID critical path should outweigh the small IPC loss.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Keep the existing if_id_t payload but treat it as a registered stage boundary rather than a purely combinational bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add the single-entry IF/ID register with valid, hold, flush, imem-ready drain, and redirect handling while preserving the existing static JAL/backward-branch prediction policy.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Separate decode-hold from imem-not-ready bubble behavior so the registered IF/ID slot is not replayed on fetch stalls.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire any new IF/ID consume or hold controls between hazard_unit and if_stage without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO or RVFI port set.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r9s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\n+title: \"Register fetch decode boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than C