{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778631464977,"sessionID":"ses_1e14ed2a4ffehDZT9w0UI0ynQN","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_eeCTJbp9Unw0Lhqupphd4XfO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r11s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\n+title: Gate predictor repair compare\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\n+  rule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\n+  cheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\n+  loop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\n+  JAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\n+\n+  One remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\n+  including ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\n+  pred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\n+  require predictor repair.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Preserve the exact existing fetch prediction policy and pred_next_pc metadata,\n+  but gate the EX-stage redirect/mispredict compare with the decoded control-flow\n+  class. Non-branch, non-jump instructions should never assert redirect, so they\n+  can bypass the 32-bit next-PC mismatch check and simply retire with pc+4 as\n+  today. Branches and JAL/JALR continue to compute resolved_next_pc exactly as\n+  they do now, including misaligned-target trap handling, and still compare\n+  against pred_next_pc to repair bad predictions.\n+\n+  This targets median FPGA Fmax with no CoreMark IPC change and avoids the failed\n+  predictor pattern of adding IF-stage state or new target paths. The change is\n+  intentionally narrower than the failed EX target-arithmetic gating attempt: it\n+  does not gate or restructure branch target, jump target, or comparator inputs,\n+  only the final predictor-repair decision for instructions that cannot redirect.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Gate redirect assertion with the resolved instruction's control-flow class before using the pred_next_pc mismatch result, while preserving existing branch/jump target computation and trap behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r11s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r11s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r11s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r11s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\n+title: Gate predictor repair compare\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\n+  rule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\n+  cheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\n+  loop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\n+  JAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\n+\n+  One remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\n+  including ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\n+  pred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\n+  require predictor repair.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Preserve the exact existing fetch prediction policy and pred_next_pc metada