\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\\n\\nThe existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\\n\\nThe existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the direct-control predictor chooses a single signed target offset first, then uses one shared pc-plus-offset adder for both predicted JAL targets and predicted backward branch targets. Keep the default pc+4 path, the JAL-always-taken rule, the backward-branch-taken rule, and the carried pred_next_pc semantics unchanged.\\n\\nThis should preserve the proven CoreMark cycle-count win from static prediction while reducing LUT use and IF-stage timing pressure. Because it adds no predictor state, tags, return stack, loop counter, or new redirect source, it avoids the failure mode seen in the previous predicto...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Isolate M-extension ALU mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\\nand MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\\nMEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\\nthe EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\\nlarge result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\\nthe RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\\nchanging cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already recovered IPC with static direct-control prediction\\nand MEM-to-EX load forwarding, while recent micro-optimizations that added IF,\\nMEM, or register-file control regressed. A lower-risk remaining timing angle is\\nthe EX ALU result cone: the common RV32I ADD/SUB/compare/address path shares one\\nlarge result mux with all RV32M multiply, divide, and remainder cases.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop control, address generation, and integer arithmetic mostly use\\nthe RV32I subset, so improving the common ALU mux depth can raise Fmax without\\nchanging cycle count or touching the proven predictor and load-forwarding paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv into two local result cones: a compact RV32I result mux for\\nADD/SUB/logic/shift/SLT/LUI and a separate RV32M result mux that keeps the existing\\nexact multiply/divide/remainder expressions unchanged. The final output should be\\nselected by a simple is_m_op predicate, rather than muxing every RV32I and RV32M\\noperation in one flat case statement.\\n\\nThis is intentionally not another attempt to share or redesign RV32M arithmetic,\\nwhich previously hurt timing. The ALTOPS branch must keep the same substituted\\nformulas, a...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Predicted path fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\\nfront end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\\nan isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\\nimmediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\\npc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\\nloop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\\nJAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\\nto hold correct useful instructions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"CoreMark is still evaluated with randomized instruction and data bus stalls, and the current\\nfront end remains tightly coupled to the back end: a dmem stall freezes fetch entirely, while\\nan isolated imem-not-ready cycle becomes a decode bubble unless the instruction is available\\nimmediately. The earlier structural fetch FIFO regressed because it buffered only sequential\\npc+4 fetches before the static direct-control predictor existed, so it could not prefetch useful\\nloop/back-edge work through back-end stalls. The current best core now has a proven low-cost\\nJAL and backward-branch predictor, which makes a small predicted-path fetch queue more likely\\nto hold correct useful instructions.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure IF into a two-entry predicted-path skid buffer with separate fetch and decode sides.\\nThe fetch side advances its private fetch PC along the existing static predicted next PC whenever\\nio_imemReady is high and the queue has space, including cycles where dmem backpressure is holding\\nID/EX and EX/MEM. The decode side consumes the oldest queued pc/instruction/pred_next_pc only\\nwhen ID is allowed to advance; when ...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Encode static prediction as direction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the simple stateless rule: predict direct JAL\\ntaken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior predictor attempts that\\nadded BHTs, RAS/JALR state, loop counters, or extra IF target muxing all\\nregressed, so the next predictor hypothesis should preserve that proven policy\\nand reduce its implementation cost instead of adding new prediction behavior.\\n\\nToday IF carries a full 32-bit pred_next_pc through IF/ID and ID/EX only so EX\\ncan compare it with the resolved next PC. For this predictor, correctness only\\ndepends on whether fetch predicted the direct control transfer taken or\\nfall-through: EX can recompute the same direct JAL/branch target from pc and imm\\nwhen needed, and JALR is still predicted fall-through.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the simple stateless rule: predict direct JAL\\ntaken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior predictor attempts that\\nadded BHTs, RAS/JALR state, loop counters, or extra IF target muxing all\\nregressed, so the next predictor hypothesis should preserve that proven policy\\nand reduce its implementation cost instead of adding new prediction behavior.\\n\\nToday IF carries a full 32-bit pred_next_pc through IF/ID and ID/EX only so EX\\ncan compare it with the resolved next PC. For this predictor, correctness only\\ndepends on whether fetch predicted the direct control transfer taken or\\nfall-through: EX can recompute the same direct JAL/branch target from pc and imm\\nwhen needed, and JALR is still predicted fall-through.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the carried pred_next_pc metadata with a compact prediction-direction\\nbit for the existing static predictor. IF still computes the predicted next PC\\nlocally to update the fetch PC, but it exports only whether it predicted a\\ndirect JAL/backward branch as taken. ID passes that bit to EX. EX comp...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Fast-path simple ALU results\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best improvement came from isolating the RV32M result mux so the hot RV32I path no longer shares one flat selector with multiply, divide, and remainder operations. The remaining EX-stage ALU still routes common ADD/ADDI/address-generation, SUB, and LUI results through the full RV32I case mux even though these operations dominate CoreMark's loop counters, pointer arithmetic, loads, stores, and upper-immediate setup.\\n\\nPrior micro-optimizations that changed predictors, memory lane logic, the register file, or RV32M resource sharing regressed. A narrower ALU-output cleanup keeps the proven predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding untouched while targeting the same timing class as the recent successful ALU isolation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv to compute simple RV32I results in a small fast cone: ADD/ADDI/address-generation as a dedicated sum, SUB as a dedicated difference, and LUI as the direct immediate operand. Keep the existing non-simple RV32I mux for logic, shifts, and comparisons, and keep the RV32M mux and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions behaviorally unchanged. The final ...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Register fetch decode boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nA minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: imem_data flows through fetch prediction packaging, decoder, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Prior structural queues and skid buffers regressed because their control was too broad, but the remaining Fmax pressure may still be this long fetch-to-decode boundary rather than CoreMark IPC.\\n\\nA minimal registered fetch/decode boundary is a narrower structural change than a FIFO: it should cut a large timing cone and preserve the proven static direct-control predictor and MEM-to-EX load forwarding behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single valid IF/ID pipeline register owned by if_stage, with explicit consume/hold behavior so an imem-not-ready cycle drains to one bubble instead of replaying the previous instruction. When decode is stalled by dmem backpressure, hold the IF/ID register and PC; when imem is ready and decode can advance, capture pc, instr, and pred_next_pc from the existing static predictor. Redirects flush the registered IF/ID payload and update PC exactly as today.\\n\\nThis turns the current pseudo five-stage pipe into a true fetch/decode split without adding multi-entry queue state, tag...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Gate static branch target formation\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor change with a large proven CoreMark gain is the current\\nstateless fetch rule: predict direct JAL taken and backward conditional\\nbranches taken. Later predictor attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, skid buffering, or extra target muxing all regressed from\\nIF-stage timing and control cost. The remaining predictor opportunity is\\ntherefore not a smarter predictor, but a cheaper implementation of the same\\nsuccessful policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor change with a large proven CoreMark gain is the current\\nstateless fetch rule: predict direct JAL taken and backward conditional\\nbranches taken. Later predictor attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, skid buffering, or extra target muxing all regressed from\\nIF-stage timing and control cost. The remaining predictor opportunity is\\ntherefore not a smarter predictor, but a cheaper implementation of the same\\nsuccessful policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the exact JAL-always-taken and backward-branch-taken behavior, but\\nrewrite the IF predictor so branch target formation is gated by the cheap\\nbranch-opcode and sign-bit predicate before the B-immediate shuffle and\\npc-plus-branch-target adder are used. Forward conditional branches should\\nfall through through the pc+4 path without driving the full branch-target\\ncone, while JAL keeps its existing direct target path.\\n\\nThis targets median FPGA Fmax with unchanged CoreMark IPC and avoids the\\nfailed pattern of adding predictor state or new redirect sources. Correctness\\nis unchanged because EX still compares the resolved next PC against the\\ncarried pred_next_pc and repairs every mismatch before retirement.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Refactor the existing static predictor...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Gate EX control target arithmetic\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from reducing unnecessary fetch-side branch target work and isolating the ALU's RV32M mux. The execute stage still unconditionally forms branch targets, JAL/JALR targets, pc+4, and branch comparison results even for ordinary ALU and load/store instructions that only need the ALU result and fall-through next PC.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot path is dominated by integer arithmetic, address generation, and loads/stores, so pruning duplicate control-flow arithmetic from the common EX cone may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax without changing cycle count, prediction policy, memory behavior, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from reducing unnecessary fetch-side branch target work and isolating the ALU's RV32M mux. The execute stage still unconditionally forms branch targets, JAL/JALR targets, pc+4, and branch comparison results even for ordinary ALU and load/store instructions that only need the ALU result and fall-through next PC.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot path is dominated by integer arithmetic, address generation, and loads/stores, so pruning duplicate control-flow arithmetic from the common EX cone may improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax without changing cycle count, prediction policy, memory behavior, or the NRET=1 RVFI interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv so control-flow next-PC work is explicitly factored and gated. Compute pc_plus4 once, share one pc_plus_imm target for both conditional branches and JAL, compute the JALR rs1+imm target only for JALR, and only evaluate the full branch comparator case when ctrl.is_branch is set. Non-control instructions should drive resolved_next_pc directly from pc_plus4 and avoid the branch/jump target mux tree.\\n\\nThis is intentionally a narrow timing cleanup, not a new predictor or early redirect. It preserves t...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Sidecar iterative divider\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU still contains full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators even though CoreMark's hot timed path is dominated by loads, stores,\\nbranches, integer ALU ops, and occasional multiply. Prior structural attempts\\nthat added front-end queues, store buffering, early JALR, or register-file\\nrestructuring regressed because they added control to hot paths. Removing the\\nrare divider/remainder cone from the single-cycle EX result path is a more\\nlocalized structural change with a direct chance to improve FPGA Fmax and LUT\\npressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX-stage ALU still contains full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators even though CoreMark's hot timed path is dominated by loads, stores,\\nbranches, integer ALU ops, and occasional multiply. Prior structural attempts\\nthat added front-end queues, store buffering, early JALR, or register-file\\nrestructuring regressed because they added control to hot paths. Removing the\\nrare divider/remainder cone from the single-cycle EX result path is a more\\nlocalized structural change with a direct chance to improve FPGA Fmax and LUT\\npressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M division and remainder out of the combinational ALU into a small\\niterative divide sidecar that is only activated for DIV, DIVU, REM, and REMU.\\nEX should hold ID/EX and suppress EX/MEM advancement while the sidecar is busy,\\nthen inject the completed quotient or remainder into the normal EX/MEM result\\npath with the original instruction metadata intact. ADD/SUB/logic/shift,\\naddress generation, branches, jumps, and MUL/MULH variants remain one-cycle,\\nand RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS keeps its one-cycle substituted behavior. This should\\nimprove median Tang Nano 20K Fmax more than it costs IPC because real divide\\nand remainder instructions are rare in the benchmark window.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_d...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Gate static JAL target formation\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor result is still the stateless direct-control rule:\\npredict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Later attempts to\\nadd predictor state, richer direction heuristics, indirect prediction, or\\nfetch buffering mostly regressed from added IF-path cost. The latest win came\\nfrom keeping the same policy while gating branch-target formation, which\\nsuggests the best remaining predictor angle is another fetch-path pruning\\nchange rather than smarter prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest predictor result is still the stateless direct-control rule:\\npredict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Later attempts to\\nadd predictor state, richer direction heuristics, indirect prediction, or\\nfetch buffering mostly regressed from added IF-path cost. The latest win came\\nfrom keeping the same policy while gating branch-target formation, which\\nsuggests the best remaining predictor angle is another fetch-path pruning\\nchange rather than smarter prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the exact current prediction behavior, but gate JAL immediate shuffle and\\nJAL target addition behind the cheap JAL opcode predicate. Today the fetch\\npredictor still forms the J-immediate and pc-plus-JAL target for every fetched\\ninstruction even though only opcode 1101111 can select that path. Non-JAL\\ninstructions should use the existing pc+4 or gated backward-branch path\\nwithout driving the JAL target cone.\\n\\nThis should improve median FPGA Fmax with no CoreMark IPC change, preserve the\\nsuccessful static predictor, and avoid the failed pattern of adding BHT/RAS/\\nloop/JALR state. EX still compares resolved_next_pc against the carried\\npred_next_pc, so architectural correction, RVFI pc_wdata, and NRET=1\\nretirement behavior are unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"cha...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Skid one ALU op behind dmem stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes every stage whenever a load or store in MEM waits for io_dmemReady. Prior structural attempts that added front-end queues or a store buffer regressed because they added broad control and memory-ordering muxes, but randomized dmem backpressure is still a direct IPC limiter. A narrower structural change can use the first blocked cycle behind a memory operation without changing prediction, memory ordering, or the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry execute skid register for safe younger instructions while EX/MEM is holding an older stalled memory operation. When dmem_stall is asserted and ID/EX holds a valid non-memory, non-branch, non-jump instruction that does not depend on the stalled load's rd, EX computes it once and captures the full ex_mem_t result into the skid entry. The front end and ID/EX then remain held until the older memory operation completes; after the memory instruction retires, the skid entry drains into the normal EX/MEM to MEM/WB path before any newly decoded instruction advances.\\n\\nThis is intentionally not a general store buffer, fetch FIFO, or out-of-order engine. It only hides one cycle of memory backpressure for independent straight-line ALU/LUI/AUIPC/MUL-class work, preserves strict in-order RVFI retirement by draining after the older memory op, and leaves loads, stores, branches, jum...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Gate predictor repair compare\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\\nrule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\\ncheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\\nJAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\\n\\nOne remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\\nincluding ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\\npred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\\nrequire predictor repair.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the stateless JAL-taken plus backward-branch-taken\\nrule, and the strongest recent predictor win came from making that same policy\\ncheaper rather than smarter. Prior attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo,\\nloop-exit state, richer static direction, fetch buffering, adder sharing, or\\nJAL target gating all regressed from added front-end or control-path cost.\\n\\nOne remaining always-active cost of the predictor is in EX: every instruction,\\nincluding ordinary ALU and memory operations, drives the resolved-next-PC versus\\npred_next_pc mismatch comparator even though only branches and jumps can ever\\nrequire predictor repair.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Preserve the exact existing fetch prediction policy and pred_next_pc metadata,\\nbut gate the EX-stage redirect/mispredict compare with the decoded control-flow\\nclass. Non-branch, non-jump instructions should never assert redirect, so they\\ncan bypass the 32-bit next-PC mismatch check and simply retire with pc+4 as\\ntoday. Branches and JAL/JALR continue to compute resolved_next_pc exactly as\\nthey do now, including misaligned-target trap handling, and still compare\\nagainst pred_next_pc to repair bad pr...","metadata":{"matches":29,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\": \"predictor\"|category: predictor|predictor|branch|JALR|BHT|BTB|RAS","time":{"start":1778632363928,"end":1778632363939}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0564bf11d44a80bf016a03c6aba4508198bebdcab2b36de635"}},"id":"prt_e1ec00ef5002DDRA4NNxvw0RrJ","sessionID":"ses_1e140182dffe7R9M16tFZmzq9v","messageID":"msg_e1ebfe833001kSvN61BLGVftOg"}}
