{"type":"text","timestamp":1778632410942,"sessionID":"ses_1e140182dffe7R9M16tFZmzq9v","part":{"id":"prt_e1ec0c4c0001qnDD3qtdzMA4W0","messageID":"msg_e1ec01087001lu0HRHzPpDp8PJ","sessionID":"ses_1e140182dffe7R9M16tFZmzq9v","type":"text","text":"Prior predictor attempts show stateful or smarter predictors consistently lost Fmax, while the wins came from preserving or pruning the static fetch policy. I’m writing a narrow predictor hypothesis that removes the always-active direct-JAL target path entirely while keeping the proven backward-branch predictor.","time":{"start":1778632410304,"end":1778632410941},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_09b5555965f2f780016a03c6da03908198b5dffcb6265870c4","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778632419405,"sessionID":"ses_1e140182dffe7R9M16tFZmzq9v","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_bvSmJlnLjQrXVNZzIZteNqIG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r12s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\n+title: \"Drop JAL fetch prediction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The strongest predictor lesson is that added state or richer control-flow\n+  heuristics have repeatedly cost more FPGA timing than they saved in CoreMark\n+  bubbles. The current IF predictor still forms a JAL immediate and JAL target\n+  for every fetched instruction, and the recent attempt to gate that path\n+  regressed from extra mux/control cost. If direct JALs are uncommon inside the\n+  bracketed CoreMark hot loops after -O3 inlining, removing this predictor path\n+  outright may recover Fmax while keeping the proven backward-branch prediction.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Keep conditional branch prediction exactly as it is today: backward branches\n+  are predicted taken and forward branches fall through. Stop predicting direct\n+  JAL in IF, so JAL follows pc+4 and is repaired by the existing EX-stage\n+  resolved_next_pc versus pred_next_pc redirect check. This deletes the\n+  always-active J-immediate shuffle, JAL target adder, and JAL arm of the IF\n+  predicted-next-PC mux instead of trying to gate them. The expected cycle loss\n+  is limited if timed CoreMark has few direct JALs, while the Fmax gain can\n+  apply to every fetch cycle.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Remove direct-JAL target formation and prediction from the fetch predictor while preserving backward-branch prediction, pc+4 fall-through, flush/redirect behavior, and pred_next_pc metadata.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r12s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r12s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r12s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r12s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,26 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\n+title: \"Drop JAL fetch prediction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The strongest predictor lesson is that added state or richer control-flow\n+  heuristics have repeatedly cost more FPGA timing than they saved in CoreMark\n+  bubbles. The current IF predictor still forms a JAL immediate and JAL target\n+  for every fetched instruction, and the recent attempt to gate that path\n+  regressed from extra mux/control cost. If direct JALs are uncommon inside the\n+  bracketed CoreMark hot loops after -O3 inlining, removing this predictor path\n+  outright may recover Fmax while keeping the proven backward-branch prediction.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Keep conditional branch prediction exactly as it is today: backward branches\n+  are predicted taken and forward branches fall through. Stop predicting direct\n+  JAL in IF, so JAL follows pc+4 and is repaired by the existing EX-stage\n+  resolved_next_pc versus pred_next_pc redirect check. This deletes the\n+  always-active J-immediate shuffle, JAL target adder, and JAL arm of the IF\n+  predicted-next-PC mux instead of trying to gate them. The expected cycle loss\n+  is limited if timed CoreMark has few direct JALs, while the Fmax gain can\n+  apply to every fetch cycle.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confiden