{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778633218201,"sessionID":"ses_1e1339aa6ffe5nCQdLsAolcZhT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_jgK1hksLAut5ZqPQPiFgMOvb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-003-r13s2\n2: title: Prioritize predictor fallthrough path\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The only durable predictor win in the bench core is the stateless direct-control policy: predict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Follow-on attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo, loop-exit state, richer static direction, target-adder sharing, JAL gating, or predictor repair gating mostly regressed because extra IF or EX control cost outweighed the remaining saved bubbles.\n6: \n7:   The current IF predictor still presents a three-way predicted-next-PC mux over pc+4, backward-branch target, and JAL target on every fetch. CoreMark's hot path is dominated by ordinary fall-through instructions plus loop branches, so making fall-through the explicit fast/default predictor path may reduce fetch timing pressure without changing the successful prediction behavior.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the predictor first computes pc_plus4 as the default predicted next PC, then overrides it only for the two existing taken-prediction cases: direct JAL and backward conditional branch. Keep both target adders and the exact same static direction policy, but rewrite the combinational logic as a priority/default assignment rather than a nested ternary select feeding predicted_next_pc.\n10: \n11:   This is intentionally a predictor implementation cleanup, not a smarter predictor. It adds no tables, tags, counters, RAS, JALR target state, extra carried metadata, or new redirect source. The goal is to help yosys/nextpnr map the overwhelmingly common fall-through path with less mux pressure while preserving IPC, RVFI pc_wdata behavior, redirect repair, and the NRET=1 top-level contract.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n17:     description: \"Rewrite static predictor next-PC selection as a pc+4 default with explicit JAL and backward-branch overrides, preserving the existing prediction policy and pred_next_pc metadata.\"\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-003-r13s2\ntitle: Prioritize predictor fallthrough path\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The only durable predictor win in the bench core is the stateless direct-control policy: predict JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. Follow-on attempts that added BHT, RAS, JALR memo, loop-exit state, richer static direction, target-adder sharing, JAL gating, or predictor repair gating mostly regressed because extra IF or EX control cost outweighed the remaining saved bubbles.\n\n  The current IF predictor still presents a three-way predicted-next-PC mux over pc+4, backward-branch target, and JAL target on every fetch. CoreMark's hot path is dominated by ordinary fall-through instructions plus loop branches, so making fall-through the explicit fast/default predictor path may reduce fetch timing pressure without changing the successful prediction behavior.\nhypothesis: |\n  Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the predictor first computes pc_plus4 as the default predicted next PC, then overrides it only for the two existing taken-prediction cases: direct JAL and backward conditional branch. Keep both target adders and the exact same static direction policy, but rewrite the combinational logic as a priority/default assignment rather than a nested ternary select feeding predicted_next_pc.\n\n  This is intentionally a predictor implementation cleanup, not a smarter predictor. It adds no tables, tags, counters, RAS, JALR target state, extra carried metadata, or new redirect source. The goal is to help yosys/nextpnr map the overwhelmingly common fall-through path with less mux pressure while preserving IPC, RVFI pc_wdata behavior, redirect repair, and the NRET=1 top-level contract.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Rewrite static predictor next-PC selection as a pc+4 default with explicit JAL and backward-branch overrides, preserving the existing prediction policy and pred_next_pc metadata.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r13s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778633218194,"end":1778633218200}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d2ed161e438ba1c016a03ca01dbd0819a8d35042843d4c38a"}},"id":"prt_e1ecd17a2001CMu2IbKYCSSY7l","sessionID":"ses_1e1339aa6ffe5nCQdLsAolcZhT","messageID":"msg_e1ecd011a001yv2uxkXzDRBd1p"}}
