{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778635217266,"sessionID":"ses_1e11580c0ffeSwchj8aKCTzhE6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_QwzZ7INqZl3eHVwAfc3LH3fH","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r15s2\n+title: Selective JAL fetch prediction\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The durable predictor win for this core is still the stateless direct-control\n+  policy: predict backward conditional branches taken and avoid adding IF-stage\n+  tables, tags, RAS state, loop counters, or indirect-target compares. Prior\n+  attempts to make the predictor smarter or syntactically rearrange the same\n+  muxes mostly regressed from fetch-path cost. The remaining useful predictor\n+  angle is therefore a policy simplification that removes part of the expensive\n+  JAL target cone while preserving the loop/back-edge behavior most likely to\n+  matter inside CoreMark.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Keep the existing backward-branch predictor exactly as-is, but make direct\n+  JAL prediction selective: predict only linkless JAL x0 jumps and backward JAL\n+  targets in IF, and let forward call-style JAL instructions fall through to the\n+  existing EX redirect repair path. This preserves prediction for unconditional\n+  loop jumps and other local backward control flow, while avoiding the J-immediate\n+  shuffle and JAL target adder on the common path for forward calls that are less\n+  likely to dominate the bracketed CoreMark loops after inlining.\n+\n+  The change is intentionally narrower than adding a BTB/RAS/BHT and less drastic\n+  than dropping all JAL prediction. Bad selective predictions remain ordinary\n+  EX-stage redirects because resolved_next_pc is still compared with pred_next_pc,\n+  so RVFI pc_wdata, trap handling, and the NRET=1 retirement contract are unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change the static fetch predictor so direct JAL targets are predicted only for linkless or backward JALs, while preserving the current backward-branch prediction and EX redirect repair semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,31 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r15s2\n+title: Selective JAL fetch prediction\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The durable predictor win for this core is still the stateless direct-control\n+  policy: predict backward conditional branches taken and avoid adding IF-stage\n+  tables, tags, RAS state, loop counters, or indirect-target compares. Prior\n+  attempts to make the predictor smarter or syntactically rearrange the same\n+  muxes mostly regressed from fetch-path cost. The remaining useful predictor\n+  angle is therefore a policy simplification that removes part of the expensive\n+  JAL target cone while preserving the loop/back-edge behavior most likely to\n+  matter inside CoreMark.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Keep the existing backward-branch predictor exactly as-is, but make direct\n+  JAL prediction selective: predict only linkless JAL x0 jumps and backward JAL\n+  targets in IF, and let forward call-style JAL instructions fall through to the\n+  existing EX redirect repair path. This preserves prediction for unconditional\n+  loop jumps and other local backward control flow, while avoiding the J-immediate\n+  shuffle and JAL target adder on the common path for forward calls that are less\n+  likely to dominate the bracketed CoreMark loops after inlining.\n+\n+  The change is intentionally narrower than adding a BTB/RAS/BHT and less drastic\n+  than dropping all JAL prediction. Bad selective predictions remain ordinary\n+  EX-stage redirects because resolved_next_pc is still compared with pred_next_pc,\n+  so RVFI pc_wdata, trap handling, and the NRET=1 retirement contract are unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change the static fetch predictor so direct JAL targets are predicted only for linkless or backward JALs, while preserving the current backward-branch prediction and EX redirect repair semantics.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,31 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r15s2\n+title: Selective JAL fetch prediction\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The durable predictor win for this core is still the stateless direct-control\n+  policy: predict backward conditional branches taken and avoid adding IF-stage\n+  tables, tags, RAS state, loop