{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778621357490,"sessionID":"ses_1e1e8beffffeb3ODQBMwbR8ms5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_445VGkuy9KrjfLMKI9wiPQWc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\n+title: \"Predict JALR returns with tiny RAS\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current fetch predictor already handles direct JAL targets and backward\n+  conditional loop branches, but every JALR return is still predicted as fall-through\n+  until EX resolves the target from rs1. CoreMark still has call/return structure even\n+  under -O3, so return mispredict bubbles are a likely remaining control-flow cost.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a very small return-address stack predictor for call/return JALR patterns. Keep\n+  the existing static direct-control predictor unchanged, but predict canonical returns\n+  in IF from the RAS top and carry that predicted next PC through the existing\n+  pred_next_pc path. Update the RAS non-speculatively from EX: push pc+4 for resolved\n+  direct calls that write x1/x5, and pop for resolved canonical returns. This targets\n+  indirect return bubbles without adding a BTB, tags, or a broad decode-to-PC critical\n+  path, and any stale RAS prediction is corrected by the existing EX redirect compare.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small return-address stack and use its top to predict canonical JALR returns while preserving the existing JAL/backward-branch predictor.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose non-speculative call/return update events from resolved JAL/JALR instructions so the RAS can be repaired by architectural control-flow outcomes.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire EX-stage RAS update signals into IF without changing the NRET=1 RVFI 