{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778621363760,"sessionID":"ses_1e1e8beffffeb3ODQBMwbR8ms5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Kq9bqfOFpc37BGUSOpUJniZK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\n2: title: \"Predict JALR returns with tiny RAS\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current fetch predictor already handles direct JAL targets and backward\n6:   conditional loop branches, but every JALR return is still predicted as fall-through\n7:   until EX resolves the target from rs1. CoreMark still has call/return structure even\n8:   under -O3, so return mispredict bubbles are a likely remaining control-flow cost.\n9: hypothesis: |\n10:   Add a very small return-address stack predictor for call/return JALR patterns. Keep\n11:   the existing static direct-control predictor unchanged, but predict canonical returns\n12:   in IF from the RAS top and carry that predicted next PC through the existing\n13:   pred_next_pc path. Update the RAS non-speculatively from EX: push pc+4 for resolved\n14:   direct calls that write x1/x5, and pop for resolved canonical returns. This targets\n15:   indirect return bubbles without adding a BTB, tags, or a broad decode-to-PC critical\n16:   path, and any stale RAS prediction is corrected by the existing EX redirect compare.\n17: expected_impact:\n18:   fitness_delta_pct: 4\n19:   confidence: medium\n20: changes:\n21:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n22:     description: \"Add a small return-address stack and use its top to predict canonical JALR returns while preserving the existing JAL/backward-branch predictor.\"\n23:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n24:     description: \"Expose non-speculative call/return update events from resolved JAL/JALR instructions so the RAS can be repaired by architectural control-flow outcomes.\"\n25:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n26:     description: \"Wire EX-stage RAS update signals into IF without changing the NRET=1 RVFI interface or retirement behavior.\"\n\n(End of file - total 26 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\ntitle: \"Predict JALR returns with tiny RAS\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current fetch predictor already handles direct JAL targets and backward\n  conditional loop branches, but every JALR return is still predicted as fall-through\n  until EX resolves the target from rs1. CoreMark still has call/return structure even\n  under -O3, so return mispredict bubbles are a likely remaining control-flow cost.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a very small return-address stack predictor for call/return JALR patterns. Keep\n  the existing static direct-control predictor unchanged, but predict canonical returns\n  in IF from the RAS top and carry that predicted next PC through the existing\n  pred_next_pc path. Update the RAS non-speculatively from EX: push pc+4 for resolved\n  direct calls that write x1/x5, and pop for resolved canonical returns. This targets\n  indirect return bubbles without adding a BTB, tags, or a broad decode-to-PC critical\n  path, and any stale RAS prediction is corrected by the existing EX redirect compare.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778621363751,"end":1778621363759}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09a9b0e0cd04e182016a039bb31814819a8704629913b607f1"}},"id":"prt_e1e18341e002fN7SHHDul5n2x9","sessionID":"ses_1e1e8beffffeb3ODQBMwbR8ms5","messageID":"msg_e1e181e09002ImDTcq6sKHW63J"}}
