{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778622374486,"sessionID":"ses_1e1d8d188ffeI8HH6BcoO1TVOI","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Q47YxCPh9yTtMCHQBHYeALXF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\n+title: \"Tiny dynamic branch direction predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current fetch predictor already removes most taken-back-edge bubbles by\n+  predicting JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. The remaining\n+  conditional branch cost is likely from forward branches that are frequently\n+  taken and from backward loop exits, both of which a static sign-of-offset rule\n+  cannot adapt to. A very small dynamic direction table can target those misses\n+  while preserving the existing direct target computation and RVFI next-PC flow.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a compact direct-mapped conditional-branch direction predictor in IF: 16\n+  entries, 2-bit saturating counters, optional short tags/valid bits, indexed by\n+  fetch PC. Conditional branches use the table's taken bit on a tag hit and fall\n+  back to the current backward-taken static rule on a miss; JAL prediction stays\n+  unchanged. EX updates the table non-speculatively from resolved branch outcome\n+  using the branch PC already carried in ID/EX, and the existing resolved-next-PC\n+  versus pred_next_pc compare repairs any bad prediction. This should recover\n+  mispredict bubbles on CoreMark's biased forward branches and one-time loop\n+  exits without adding a BTB, RAS, or decode-stage redirect path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a tiny conditional-branch BHT that overrides the static backward-taken rule on tagged hits while reusing existing B/J immediate target logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose resolved conditional-branch update signals from EX so IF can train counters only on real retiring-path branch outcomes.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire EX branch predictor update signals into IF without changing the NRET=1 top-level interface or RVFI channel shape.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\n+title: \"Tiny dynamic branch direction predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current fetch predictor already removes most taken-back-edge bubbles by\n+  predicting JAL taken and backward conditional branches taken. The remaining\n+  conditional branch cost is likely from forward branches that are frequently\n+  taken and from backward loop exits, both of which a static sign-of-offset rule\n+  cannot adapt to. A very small dynamic direction table can target those misses\n+  while preserving the existing direct target computation and RVFI next-PC flow.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a compact direct-mapped conditional-branch direction predictor in IF: 16\n+  entries, 2-bit saturating counters, optional short tags/valid bits, indexed by\n+  fetch PC. Conditional branches use the table's taken bit on a tag hit and fall\n+  back to the current backward-taken static rule on a miss; JAL prediction stays\n+  unchanged. EX updates the table non-speculatively from resolved branch outcome\n+  using the branch PC already carried in ID/EX, and the existing resolved-next-PC\n+  versus pred_next_pc compare repairs any bad prediction. This should recover\n+  mispredict bubbles on CoreMark's biased forward branches and one-time loop\n+  exits without adding a BTB, RAS, or decode-stage redirect path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a tiny conditional-branch BHT that overrides the static backward-taken rule on tagged hits while reusing existing B/J immediate target logic.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose resolved conditional-branch update signals from EX so IF can train counters only on real retiring-path branch outcomes.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire EX branch predictor update signals into IF without changing the NRET=1 top-level interface or RVFI channel shape.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\n+title: \"Tiny dynamic branch direction predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current fetch predictor already removes most taken-back-edge bubbles by\n+  predicting JAL taken and backward conditional branches ta