{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778624686128,"sessionID":"ses_1e1b5c423ffeJqKIDO72eUxe5w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_SDF9sTA8lTdGILjQn80zQBNu","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\n+title: \"One-entry JALR target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current fetch predictor already captures the large CoreMark win from direct JAL\n+  targets and backward conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts that added a\n+  BHT, RAS, or richer branch heuristic regressed because they put too much state and\n+  decode/mux logic on the IF path. The remaining predictable control-flow bubbles are\n+  likely JALR returns and other repeated indirect jumps, but they need a much cheaper\n+  mechanism than a stack or tagged direction table.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry JALR target memo in fetch. When a resolved JALR reaches EX, store\n+  its PC and resolved target non-speculatively; when IF later fetches a JALR at the same\n+  PC, predict the stored target through the existing pred_next_pc path. This is a tiny\n+  one-entry indirect-target predictor, not a direction predictor: direct JAL and backward\n+  branch prediction stay unchanged, and any stale JALR target is repaired by the existing\n+  EX resolved-next-PC comparison.\n+\n+  This should recover repeated return or indirect-call bubbles in CoreMark with less IF\n+  critical-path and LUT cost than the failed RAS attempt because it removes push/pop\n+  classification, stack indexing, and multi-entry state. The implementation must not\n+  change the NRET=1 RVFI port set or architectural pc_wdata reporting.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry JALR PC/target memo and use it only on exact PC hits for fetched JALR instructions, preserving the existing JAL/backward-branch predictor fallback.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose a non-speculative update event for valid resolved JALR instructions with the instruction PC and resolved target.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the EX-stage JALR predictor update signals back to IF without changing the core IO or RVFI retirement path.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r5s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\n+title: \"One-entry JALR target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current fetch predictor already captures the large CoreMark win from direct JAL\n+  targets and backward conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts that added a\n+  BHT, RAS, or richer branch heuristic regressed because they put too much state and\n+  decode/mux logic on the IF path. The remaining predictable control-flow bubbles are\n+  likely JALR returns and other repeated indirect jumps, but they need a much cheaper\n+  mechanism than a stack or tagged direction table.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry JALR target memo in fetch. When a resolved JALR reaches EX, store\n+  its PC and resolved target non-speculatively; when IF later fetches a JALR at the same\n+  PC, predict the stored target through the exi