{"type":"text","timestamp":1778627280891,"sessionID":"ses_1e18e1a3affejfQrNsUBf0JFiO","part":{"id":"prt_e1e727f6a001JurQcctQlGjokn","messageID":"msg_e1e727098001vnsuL4qqvYE3Gf","sessionID":"ses_1e18e1a3affejfQrNsUBf0JFiO","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the hypothesis as a single-adder static predictor refactor: preserve the proven JAL/backward-branch behavior, but remove redundant target adders from the fetch predictor path to improve Fmax with no IPC downside.","time":{"start":1778627280746,"end":1778627280891},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0655d12c00d894bc016a03b2d0a76881949a7b19dbb3662b4e","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778627288610,"sessionID":"ses_1e18e1a3affejfQrNsUBf0JFiO","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_D8SALsv5RHt9JS5kvwTt8a6d","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Share static predictor target adder\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\n+\n+  The existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the direct-control predictor chooses a single signed target offset first, then uses one shared pc-plus-offset adder for both predicted JAL targets and predicted backward branch targets. Keep the default pc+4 path, the JAL-always-taken rule, the backward-branch-taken rule, and the carried pred_next_pc semantics unchanged.\n+\n+  This should preserve the proven CoreMark cycle-count win from static prediction while reducing LUT use and IF-stage timing pressure. Because it adds no predictor state, tags, return stack, loop counter, or new redirect source, it avoids the failure mode seen in the previous predictor regressions and should be low risk for RVFI pc_wdata correctness.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Share one target adder between JAL and backward-BRANCH prediction by selecting the predictor offset before adding it to the fetch PC, while preserving the existing static prediction policy and pred_next_pc behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Share static predictor target adder\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\n+\n+  The existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the direct-control predictor chooses a single signed target offset first, then uses one shared pc-plus-offset adder for both predicted JAL targets and predicted backward branch targets. Keep the default pc+4 path, the JAL-always-taken rule, the backward-branch-taken rule, and the carried pred_next_pc semantics unchanged.\n+\n+  This should preserve the proven CoreMark cycle-count win from static prediction while reducing LUT use and IF-stage timing pressure. Because it adds no predictor state, tags, return stack, loop counter, or new redirect source, it avoids the failure mode seen in the previous predictor regressions and should be low risk for RVFI pc_wdata correctness.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Share one target adder between JAL and backward-BRANCH prediction by selecting the predictor offset before adding it to the fetch PC, while preserving the existing static prediction policy and pred_next_pc behavior.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Share static predictor target adder\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best predictor is the stateless fetch-side rule that predicts direct JALs taken and backward conditional branches taken. Prior attempts to add BHT, RAS, JALR, or loop-exit state all regressed because extra IF-stage compare, table, and mux logic cost more Fmax than the remaining mispredict bubbles were worth.\n+\n+  The existing static predictor still appears to compute separate JAL and branch target additions before selecting the predicted next PC. That keeps the successful prediction policy but may leave unnecessary 32-bit adder and mux pressure on the fetch-to-PC critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the direct-control predictor chooses a single signed target offset first, then uses one shared pc-plus-offset adder for both predicted JAL targets and predicted backward branch targets. Keep the default pc+4 path, the JAL-always-taken rule, the backward-branch-taken rule, and the carried pred_next_pc semantics unchanged.\n+\n+  This should preserve the proven CoreMark cycle-count win from static prediction while reducing LUT use and IF-stage timing pressure. Because it adds no predictor state, tags, return stack, loop counter, or new redirect source, it avoids the failure mode seen in the previous predictor regressions and should be low risk for RVFI pc_wdata correctness.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Share one target adder between JAL and backward-BRANCH prediction by selecting the predictor offset before adding it to the fetch PC, while preserving the existing static prediction policy and pred_next_pc behavior.\"\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r7s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778627288583,"end":1778627288589}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0655d12c00d894bc016a03b2d0ce508194bb1d93e77d0d8e33"}},"id":"prt_e1e727ffc001FL7LC2Dt1yFBwg","sessionID":"ses_1e18e1a3affejfQrNsUBf0JFiO","messageID":"msg_e1e727098001vnsuL4qqvYE3Gf"}}
